Name: Marius Pilipas
University/Course: Middlesex University London, BA Photography
Description: I am presenting Heroes I keep on chasing – my most beloved photographers, who let me capture the portraits of them. Their faces, style, personalities – I was trying to get it all. It is a collaboration in which my idols became the sitters they usually photograph. I tried to capture the best in them, while they gratefully invited me to dive into the world in which they live and learn something new from it. In this particular image I photographed Martin Parr, doing a selfie with a selfie stick - something he had photographed for ages, but never done himself.

Name: Lucia
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, Graphic Design
Description: Due to Coachella festival 2020, the brand Barefoot Wine has decided to make a limited edition labels, inspired in this music event, art installations and characteristic style of its. It is necessary to design three different labels, accompanied by a carrier bag/box

Name: Niamh Shaw
University/Course: Dundee University (DJCAD) Illustration
Description: I create illustrations combined with graphite and digital techniques which help enhance my art work and gives it movement. I really enjoy creating Picture books with a narrative based around nature or Celtic mythology.

Name: Sam Cunningham
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire
Description: This is a panel from my comic about the Syrian Civil War and the children living through it. All told from the perspective of the last garden centre in Aleppo.

Name: Jack Rowlands
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Graphic Communication
Description:
This project reveals the hidden truths behind the tourist industry, focusing on those working within the hospitality sector in Spain. Many Spanish businesses thrive from the tourism, as the country has become one of the most popular holiday destinations in the world. Although the tourism sector has such a positive impact on the Spanish economy, due to a lack of modernisation, regulations are now outdated and scarce. During this major season for the Spanish economy, businesses are constantly finding ways to exploit their assets for further financial gain. 

‘Spill the Sauce’ is a campaign focusing on the impact that this has on the employees who are forced to succumb to various forms of worker exploitation, where job security and rights are non-existent. The campaign has been formed around a series of interviews which express the true emotions of the people affected, offering them a chance to come together, serve justice and make a change to current working conditions in the hospitality sector.

Name: Shivali Patel
University/Course: University of Westminster — BA Graphic Communication Design
Description: This poster design is one of many pieces which has been created for a hypothetical exhibiton. The content of the exhibition is on the development of typography.

Name: felicity fulwood
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College  BA/HND Textiles specialising in weave and print
Description: this was created as a piece of weave using an overshot pattern as part of a nightlife brief project

Name: Feli Yaucat
University/Course: University of Arts London (LCC)
Description: Panaché is a drink you crave, a refreshing beer with a hint of citrus lemonade without side effects of alcohol.  The mission of this brand is to provide an alternative drink for those who like the social aspects of beer drinking but don’t want to get drunk.

Name: Chloe Sparks
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Hons Textile Design
Description: My project is called ‘Botanica’ and is a high end printed womenswear collection portraying the innate connection we have for nature and the amazing feeling we have when surrounded my flowers, throughout my collection I have explored florals and created something that will make the consumer feel special.

Name: Ben Chamberlain
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description: Poster design for a retro café named 'Arcade Food Theatre' which uses food photographed from above to create one of the most iconic retro game characters, Pac-Man.

Name: Heather Bell
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art
Description: Hollowed Out.What happens when you struggle to recognise yourself and the person you were (or want to be) can no longer be found? I use my work to explore relationships and the impact they have on me.

Name: Lilith Piper
University/Course: BA Fine Art at Falmouth University
Description: I try to illuminate the fixed medium of painting and etching through the exploration of Horor Vacui 'the fear of empty space'. This piece is called 'the Ask of Youth and the Point of Wisdom' representing the timeless weaving of the web. Collaged and layerd Imagery intertwining, a pickilith of objects and obsessions in a time of darkness and hibernation. Living in a world of suppression expressed as a fear of turning to stone. The devotion to the dance begins with ecstatic liberation of the body and an Explosion of emotions and relentless rivers of tears. Fabrics beat to the drum that the people used to make when chattering the living energy in to circles of stone.

Name: Catherine
University/Course: Cambridge School of Art, Anglia Ruskin University - Illustration
Description: A visual response of the contents of my mother’s address book. This image represents the people added in (children, partners etc) as well as people who have been removed (ex-partners, deceased).

Name: Natalie Robinson
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University BA (Hons) Animation
Description: A small selection of personal character designs and screenshots from my current showreel submitted as part of my course

Name: Lewis Webster
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University & Graphic Design
Description:
Inspired by 90's Hardcore band, Earth Crisis and their album 'Destroy the machines', the project is based on a fictional direct action protest movement centred around Earth and animal liberation, known as DESTROY THE MACHINES.

Linking Hardcore / DIY culture and militant direct action, an interactive element on the vinyl sleeve sleeve allows the viewer to destroy the 'machines' which are destroying our planet and those that inhabit it. It serves as a purpose for the viewer to get involved and take action against those who are decimating the planet.

Name: Alice Gompels
University/Course: University of Brighton, Illustration
Description: This project is documenting COVID-19 through letter writing. So far over 140 letters have been received internationally, with more coming in each day.  It aims to serve as a time capsule, as well as offer people a sense of sense of connection during this strange time period, albeit remotely (www.lettersfromcovid.com)

Name: Erika Gabalyte
University/Course: Middlesex University
Description:
This is an anonymous portrait of a person living illegally in the UK. After escaping from his homeland, where he felt he was under constant surveillance, he came to a land of possibilities but ended up facing fear, rejection and isolation.

It’s a collaboration in which I collected my subject’s personal drawings and tried to visualise his inner thoughts and feelings as well as the wider issues concerned with living under these circumstances.

Name: Billy Nhiwatiwa
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts - Graphic Design
Description: The task was to refresh a famous old brand. Sailors used to take water biscuits on long voyages. This fresh new packaging for Carr's Biscuits celebrates exploration by housing the water biscuits in a tube styled like a rolled-up map.

Name: Heather Bell & Zac Hughson
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art
Description: What happens when you struggle to recognise yourself and the person you were, or want to be, can no longer be found? I use my work to explore relationships and the impact they have on me. Here I used Zac Hughson's work to add an edge of domesticity.

Name: Melisa Hassan
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Fashion Design
Description: Final collection designs exploring the concept of ‘Home Sweet Home’, and it's associations with the owner such as pride, attachment, and identity. Captivated by 70s furniture, it has inspired my modular collection.

Name: Hannah Bradley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University. BA Textile Design
Description:
My degree collection, entitled Bloom, is an exploration into a serene, tranquil and slow paced environment, inspired by the hazy countryside of Ireland. With Northern Ireland having the highest suicide rate in the U.K., it is ever so more important to me that we are able to engage and connect with the outdoors, to relieve our stresses and anxieties, and to take a step back to simply breathe. 

The bedroom  is often viewed as a safe place of comfort. My collection of soft furnishings created for a bespoke glamping pod setting within a wellness retreat centre, that through soft moody colours juxtaposed against bursts of the fresh floral tones of the Irish countryside, will create a space that provides calm and comfort yet also empowers. Wild florals and botanical imagery in the collection connect the inside with the outdoors. Simulating the feeling of tranquillity and wellness when amongst nature, it creates an environment to relax and feel safe to bloom.

Name: Melanie Grandidge
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh, Illustration BA (Hons)
Description: My main project in my final year was my picture book called 'Pier Pressure'. It is about a squabble of cheeky seagulls that steals chips in a quiet seaside town. This illustration complements this picture book and is drawn in the same style with ink and watercolour. It is based off a seagull I saw at the Botanic Gardens who stole someone’s cup of tea from the outdoor café!

Name: Julia
University/Course: Bradford College/ University of Bolton, BA(Hons) Graphic Design & Illustration
Description: My final major project was work placement with Bradford College Personal Development teams as graphic designer with focus on communication. The aim was to promote sport activities and increase students participation. Some of the concepts has been already used. The weekly schedule and set of sport posters have been used on tv screens across College sites, in print, on website and on social media. There wasn't existing any visual identity for sports before in College. I had blank page I could start with but most of stuff have to match with Bradford College brand guideline.

Name: Jaleel Hudson
University/Course: De Montfort University and Graphic Design (Illustration)
Description: My work comes from my tutor telling me to draw what I like - food. Reportage illustration in food has become one of my favourite specialities. Food illustrations should be more widely used, it is a fun way to captivate the movement and character in dishes in whatever style imaginable.

Name: Yve Slater
University/Course: Manchester School of Art, Illustration with Animation
Description: In 1995, a fruit and veg stall opened on a crumpled sidewalk, in a busy city centre. Local produce for local people. Today, it competes with supermarkets, take-aways, vending machines and apps. This their story.

Name: Harriet Davey
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic Design
Description: This is the main character concept design for the publication of my 3rd year dissertation. I built an Unreal Engine interactive 'game' experience in which the viewer navigates a simulated world, (controlling this character) in search of a series of mirrored simulacrum objects that speak excerpts of my thesis alongside submissions from fellow artists, thinkers, and writers.

Name: Sophie Niamh Preisler
University/Course: BA (Hons) Costume Design and Making at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Bambi: exploring how environmental problems can be approached through design for film and how timeless tales are recreated to make them relevant and magical to the contemporary society. The image shows the Great Prince; a stately, proud character, admired by all creatures in the forest. Kind but powerful, the costume aims to bring to life a deer that is smart and influential; a country businessman who pays close attention to the fine details and watches over forest life, protecting the natural world.

Name: Jessica Hand
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University. Textiles Design.
Description:
DIVINE COMFORTS
A versatile, androgynous menswear collection, which aims to explore the popularity of biblical references within trends and merchandise from a non-religious consumers perspective.

Name: Paulius Daunys
University/Course: Kingston School Art, BA Graphic Design
Description: A cover for a publication of my thesis which investigates the Socio-political impact of the Eurovision Song Contest.

Name: Molly Jones
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, studying International Fashion Business
Description: When researching into gender in fashion I was amazed at the lack go gender-neutral fashion on the high street, especially in this era of inclusivity. My work is about looking into the non-binary community and creating a collection that accurately represents gender identity for non-binary consumers. I designed a five outfit collection for the high street retailer Zara as I felt their 2016 ungendered collection was particularly poor.

Name: Kirsty McMillan
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, HND Fashion Textiles
Description: A hand painted self-portrait using procion dye onto cotton fabric from an upcycled dress as part of a refashioned project for Stella McCartney.  I wanted to depict the emotion of a strong female protagonist based on the book 'Sunset Song' by Lewis Grassic Gibbon.  I embroidered back into the portrait to bring out some of her features.

Name: Hannah Riordan
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh, Ba(hons) Illustration
Description: This is an editorial illustration about weekend getaways and cheap and sustainable travel. Something I am sure we are all hoping we can do safely very soon.

Name: 智鹏 Jacky
University/Course: Communication University of China, Nanjing
Description: There is no eternal glory, time is the ultimate winner. The once prosperous house is now only accompanied by cobwebs and various kinds of garbage.
Website: The site is the ruins of an estate in China's Shanxi Province, once a land that flourished hundreds of years ago and was home to families of about 500 people. But war and political turmoil quickly brought the family home to an end and it is now empty.

Name: Lisa Meikle
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College
Description: My work is about capturing what farming is about in Britain. Behind what the media and activists groups make farming in Britain to be. This is more behind the good farming.

Name: Kim Watson
University/Course: MA Photography at Nottingham Trent University
Description: My work is a visual, historical and sensory exploration of a small piece of local woodland called Ploughman Wood, once a part of the greater Sherwood Forest. The work uses historical and alternative photographic methods alongside moving image and audio to  collect, document and preserve the woodland, with particular emphasis on recording the overlooked botanical specimens within it.

Name: Ronald Gregory-Clark
University/Course: University of Plymouth
Description: My work is my personal brand.  I created a folder which contains a business card, a thank you note and a poster of my personal brand. The branding represents my enjoyment of creating custom type.

Name: Katie Richardson
University/Course: Kingston School of Art and BA Graphic Design
Description: This project is about an ancient Egg Foraging folklore I created to ignite individuals imaginations. With the world turning into Zombies fixated on digital media, we've lost our childlike minds. Imagination gives us new ideas and new perspectives on life, which in our current situation seems necessary.

Name: Joshua Donkor
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, BA Illustration
Description: This painting is an exploration of me and my family's connection to Ghana across three different time periods. My Fathers childhood growing up in Ghana, my Mothers experiences working as a VSO in Ghana during the 70's and my own visits back to Ghana. It is designed to question how time effects our connection with our places of origin and the impact this has on our identity's.

Name: Miriam Woodburn
University/Course: Graphic Design (BA), Kingston School of Art
Description: My photography practice is concerned with gender, sexuality and ambiguity. With an honest yet vulnerable approach, I find the magic in everyday people and situations.

Name: DuoDeus Game Team
University/Course: WSA - University of Southampton, BA Game Design and Art
Description:
DuoDeus is a 2D local multiplayer music game in which two deities cooperate to create their own universe by composing music.

Jumping, collecting and connecting stars: the players need to help each other fill the void with shapes, sounds, colours and reach further distances. Every choice and every action the two deities make will have an influence on the outcome, and only by communicating with each other will they manage to create a harmonious universe.

Whether you are a skilled musician, or whether you haven’t had any interaction with this creative process before, DuoDeus will allow you and your friend to experiment and compose your very own piece of music!

Name: Lucy Bentley
University/Course: Kingston University, Illustration Animation
Description: During lockdown I have been creating a new environment of escapism, using magic realism to create an outside space filled with impossible and exciting characters and objects. The world helps you escape from current life, appreciating the smaller joys of life. The objects featured are my favourite parts of the world, soon to be turned into a pilot episode of characters coming together to enjoy a large picnic. This has been heavily inspired by Sylvanian Families and old children's programmes such as Bagpuss. This has been a collaborative project, where both me and another student have been making things.

Name: Kayleigh Harrison
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Graphic Design
Description:
The battle against mental health is a worldwide issue and one that is prevalent within the pop punk music genre. From lyrics to press interviews the topic is key.
 
Upsides 2020 is a festival which, not only raises money for charity, but also benefits the attendees’ mental health. It uses the pop punk community to promote emotional wellbeing and shift social stigma through various methods.

Name: Leah Kemp
University/Course: Staffordshire University- Cartoon And Comic Arts
Description: This is a splash page from the comic I’m working in for my final project. It serves as the villains reveal. I illustrated this in photoshop.

Name: Ellie Prichard
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
Oi! is a mixer that turns pink if spiked, giving you a deliciously bold base to mix with your spirits and 
confidence in what you drink.

Name: Mary Morrison
University/Course: University of Ulster, Belfast. Textile Art, Design and Fashion
Description: I come from a family of collectors and hoarders and just like them I am a collector of old, eccentric items from different decades. I have always been interested in my family’s history, and with so much consistent documenting of family life, I have created work that has allowed me to make a comment on how my family lived its life. I combine traditional methods of capturing a moment with modern embroidery software that allows me to recreate these moments as a piece of textile art.

Name: Josie Thomas
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: A textile collection titled Down to Earth, for high-end casual spring/summer 2021 menswear. A concept initiated by natural forms and beauty of the world, developed into a bold print collection. Seeking to inspire beauty within menswear.

Name: Marion Small
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University Fashion Communication
Description: My concept was based around athleisure clothing. The in-between clothing we are wearing at the minute through lockdown. Joggers, cardigans - Feeling good and cosy in comfortable clothing.

Name: Rosie Wells
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Fashion Accessory Design
Description: My collection is inspired by different interpretations of armour, in buildings, nature and for protection. My research developed into the theme of exoskeletal, and looking at different areas of protection and barriers. Looking further into different elements of protection I researched into traditional knotting to make fenders to protect boats, and traditional leather braiding techniques. I took inspiration from gun and knife holsters to design accessory pieces on the body, as I wanted the pieces in my collection to act like a layer of protection to the wearer. From this research I gathered shapes, patterns and a colour pallet to take forward into my own designs. selecting complimentary neutral coloured leathers in my final collection, alongside a natural coloured rope for decorative details. I used orange edge paint to colour the ends of my rope to add a bold accent to my line up. This image is my line up for my final collection.

Name: Lucy Dodds
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description: A mock editorial done for the Guardian article "The Tiger next door" about how there are now more tigers living as pets in the USA than there are in the wild

Name: Victoria Eddi
University/Course: Kingston University Creative & Cultural Industries: Design Marketing
Description: A poster for my reinterpreted opening credit scene for the existing film  "Le Samourai" (1967).                                   The theme is the perceived stereotype of samurai in Western Film. I want viewers to take their own interpretation of who a samurai is in "Le Samourai" (https://vimeo.com/405009535)

Name: Conor Mullin
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art
Description: A Dartmoor inspired beer bottle sticker for a hamper style pub box, to support local businesses.

Name: Sophie Sankey
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Photography
Description: A series about home and the relationships built within it. The work explores a notion of belonging, finding a sense of self within a space that people call home.

Name: Saskia Wright
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: In 2019 it was reported that as many as 320,000 people were living on the streets in the UK alone and almost all of them suffered from mental health conditions. The idea behind this campaign is to simply encourage people to smile or interact with homeless individuals rather than ignore them as they walk past. Often dehumanised, the simplicity of just saying 'hello' aims to make homeless individuals feel valued once again. Contrary to other campaigns, the poster designs will be placed in locations deemed typically homeless, a shop front for example, to help them stand out in a conventional street setting.

Name: Benjamin Rostance
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Somebody else's good food' is a video performance piece that highlights the existence of the 'inner child' within the adult body of the artist. Growing up in a poor, working class family often meant having to wait for the Xmas party at primary school to be able to eat brand named foods. This film is about the artist allowing the deprived 'inner child' to buy anything and everything they wish, from a shop similar to the one the artist’s parents shopped at called 'KwikSave'. This piece of work reflects on working classness, growing up in an abusing environment, mental health and recovery.

Name: Bartlomiej Kisiel
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College - Cardonald. HND Fashion Textiles.
Description:
I imagined it as a tiny dress for a toddler. 
I re-used materials from charity shops. This piece was made from an old knitted sweater and a organza top.

Name: Poppy Ash
University/Course: University of Southampton, studying Fine Art
Description: My work explores the everyday, currently focusing on my surroundings during the Lockdown period. Creating a drawing every day (starting with a month of continuous line drawings) I am finding new ways to engage with the space I am in and adapting to the situation by finding new ways of working.

Name: Saskia Wright
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Dyscalculia is a specific learning difficulty which affects almost 5% of the population, making it as common as dyslexia. But the condition, often referred to as ‘the forgotten learning disability’, is neither well researched nor entirely understood. While most people accept that it is ‘a difficulty with maths’, it is so much more than that.  This book looks at real-life experiences of dyscalculia and how people cope with simple tasks on a day to day basis. It is designed specifically with dyscalculia in mind, playing on the legibility and illegibility of type to simulate the difficulties associated with the condition.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Distracted Driving is a campaign which highlights the dangers of distracted driving by using metaphor design to visually show the potential outcome of becoming distracted when driving. Mobile notifications are crushed, distorted and destroyed, this represents possible effects that distracted driving could have on the driver and those nearby.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: London Balloon Festival celebrates the sport of ballooning by using a colourful and vibrant identity to raise awareness for the sport and get the community involved. The visual identity allows for an unlimited amount of patterns and colours to do used to show the subject of hot air balloons, as well as showing the sheer scale of hot air balloons.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Distracted Driving is a campaign which highlights the dangers of distracted driving by using metaphor design to visually show the potential outcome of becoming distracted when driving. Mobile notifications are crushed, distorted and destroyed, this represents possible effects that distracted driving could have on the driver and those nearby.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Digital Joy creates a moment of joy for train station visitors by using the existing infrastructure of train stations such as screens to share playful messages and animations to raise a smile and the mood of travellers and staff in stations.

Name: Amy Grumble
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Illustration BA (Hons)
Description:
The light emerging through the cracks, the beauty of the broken, the discarded living up to a new potential. This project aims to illustrate the story of re-birth, and the possibility of the end bringing a fresh, new beginning into life. This collection of work became a way to explore and cope with the personal loss of a family member, and discover how something negative can be used to fuel a show of beauty, in memory and in an educational form, understanding grief and the possibility of an afterlife. Exploring the use of paper folding techniques, the re-birth of old/discarded work into new 3-dimensional forms displays a new life after what could have been the end for the 2-dimensional work it was formed from. Inspired by the story of ‘The Secret of the Dragonfly’, this work is aiming to give hope to those grieving, whilst also supplying an immersive escapism area, where the broken is free to fly. This project paved the way for an exploration across a wide range of multi-disciplinary art techniques, pulling apart 2-dimensional forms in order to change its dimensional value.
This response shows the delicacy, but also the poignancy of life and judgement, how one may see the end or the break of something, another may notice a growing potential. The urchins representing fragility alongside the fearful self defence of the wall of spikes, but also the inevitable break down/ decay of this wall, showing that beneath the surface, we are all one and the same.

Name: Aaron J Davies
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University CSAD
Description:
Capturing the scale of the universe and commemorating 30 years of the Hubble Deep Field Telescope.
Using simple data processing methods to create galactic sculptures, this work aims to illustrate the vastness of space. The work is comprised of 2,000 gilded sculptures, set in a grid like structure. These forms are representational of the 10,000 galaxies captured by Hubble, over a distance of 13 billion light years. Galaxies which exist in a patch of sky no greater than the size of a pin head held at arm’s length.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Time To Rebel is a campaign which highlights the increasing severity of global warming. The campaign shows global surface temperature changes through the lyrics of the song ‘The 1975’. This song features a powerful speech about the climate crisis and how we can rebel against it, spoken by the environmental activist Greta Thunberg.

Name: SHIYA XU
University/Course: ILLUSTRATION MFA, EDINBURGH COLLEGE OF ART
Description:
People like pickles.
People are living in pickles.
People are like pickles.
Do you like pickles?

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: London Balloon Festival celebrates the sport of ballooning by using a colourful and vibrant identity to raise awareness for the sport and get the community involved.  The visual identity allows for an unlimited amount of patterns and colours to do used to show the subject of hot air balloons, as well as showing the sheer scale of hot air balloons.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Elevate is an electric lock-based bike hire scheme based in San Francisco. The brand identity uses the theme of contour lines and perspective which reflects the landscape of the city and the motion of cycling. The identity encourages viewers to opt for a bike as a mode of transport by highlighting the opportunities, benefits and experiences that bike hire can offer.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Time To Rebel is a campaign which highlights the increasing severity of global warming. The campaign shows global surface temperature changes through the lyrics of the song ‘The 1975’. This song features a powerful speech about the climate crisis and how we can rebel against it, spoken by the environmental activist Greta Thunberg.

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Distracted Driving is a campaign which highlights the dangers of distracted driving by using metaphor design to visually show the potential outcome of becoming distracted when driving. Mobile notifications are crushed, distorted and destroyed, this represents possible effects that distracted driving could have on the driver and those nearby.

Name: Khairun
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: A film about a girl who takes home a cat only to discover it isn't what I seems

Name: Steve Garnett
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Digital Joy creates a moment of joy for train station visitors by using the existing infrastructure of train stations such as screens to share playful messages and animations to raise a smile and the mood of travellers and staff in stations.

Name: Abi Lewin
University/Course: Textile Design at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Taking inspiration from my travels over the Cyprian waters, my project 'Beneath the Waves' is a niche children’s interiors and pyjama collection encapsulating sea life in a fun, illustrative and and stylised way. The concept of this collection is to create awareness through an interactive, subtle approach about the growing environmental impact our oceans face with plastic pollution. It highlights the beauty of sea creatures and aims to create more conscious consumers, not only for young children, but for their parents too.

Name: Annalise Burton
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (Hons) Costume Design & Making
Description: Fully functioning costume of Caliban from Shakespeare's 'The Tempest'. Designed and made by Annalise Burton with machine embroidered moss & lichen. Latex skin details and hand worked textural surfaces.

Name: karlis kah
University/Course: cardiff MET university / graphic communication
Description: The Wisdom of the Cave* is an experimental installation that explores the thopical themes of misinformation & what role data personalization plays in it. Who builds our reality? What shapes our perspective of the world? The project uses symbolism from Plato's Allegory of the Cave.

Name: Rosalie Wood
University/Course: Manchester School of Art : Graphic Design
Description:
In a sphere where we sit to create it’s time to take a stand and ‘measure’ a work mate. 

Designed to live in a studio the probacktor raises awareness of bad posture giving opportunity to record those studio slumps!

Name: Ethan Milner
University/Course: Birmingham City University, Photography BA Hons
Description: MILNER in these images is taking a step back and looking at his childhood and his interpretation of life from a young age. MILNER’s parents were divorced when he was 3 leaving him with two separate homes, separate families, separate realities. He would live with his mother and sister during the week but on weekends go down to his father’s where he might have met his half-brother. MILNER only found out he had a half-brother in primary 3, he was one day taken out of class and told when his dad picked him up today, that he would have a half-brother. These images take a deeper look at the locations that would affect and change MILNER’s life forever. However, he looks back with no regret, instead with interest and happiness as it is as much a personal discovery of himself for himself. All the images are supported with audio, designed to be listened to with headphones while viewing the images. The audio files are recorded conversations with MILNER, his brother and his father talking about the locations and their own personal memories attached to the locations. The audio and visual experience together is designed to allow the viewer to fall deep into their own memories of their childhood.

Name: Tobi Meuwissen
University/Course: Manchester School of Art
Description:
This is a spread from a recipe book/publication called 'Home Cooked' which explores the relationship between food and memories of comfort, focusing on the refugee struggle. It explores the notion that food can be used as a way of keeping a cultural identity in a foreign and quite often an unwelcoming place. 
The publication draws upon personal recipes from refugees who I worked with and articles/online papers to demonstrate how food can help create a home from home.

Name: Jill Dack
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts (NUA) Graphic Design
Description: Vivido Loma' is inspired by the mosaic steps of loma san jeronimo in Paraguay. A bright, colourful town and a big tourist spot, created and developed by the locals.

Name: Raahim
University/Course: De montfort university, Graphic design & Illustration
Description: This is a illustration from a poster to encourage students to visit 'The Drawing Centre'  which is a centre at dmu helping students develop their creative skills and bring their imagination to life.

Name: Kaila Nesukaityte
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (Hons) Animation
Description: My work is based of the Greek gods and goddesses, the main characters in this work include Persephone, Hekate and Hades.

Name: Niamh
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Photography
Description: This is an untitled image from my photobook, Me, The Landscape and Us. It is a body of work addressing issues around the representation of landscape. Landscape photography was traditionally a visual appreciation of the land through three major aesthetic modes; the sublime, picturesque and the beautiful. The 1975 New Topographics exhibition viewed the land in a different way- a vantage coined by an objective and unemotional gaze with an interest in the politics of the land pictured. My work is situated between the two extremes. It values empathy towards the subject matter while exploring how the land is impacted by humanity.

Name: Adonia Hirst
University/Course: Newcastle University, BA Fine Art
Description: My work explores communication, intimacy and movement, using new ways in which we can experience softness and volume with our human bodies. Situating the physical disconnection of modern society, with my interest in the diminished use of textiles techniques. The tactility of my sculptures is explored through organic exploration of our senses. This work is part of a body of textile pieces that are ongoing in experimentation, using my close friends to interact with the work, through video, photography and performance, exploring the relationship between textiles and contemporary art.

Name: Elizabeth Tania
University/Course: Raffles Design Institute, with Graphic Design
Description: Interstellar tells the story of a father and daughter who are separated by time and dimension. Inspired by time dilation, a real time difference between space and earth, scenes on earth travel faster than space and the mobile interactivity allows the audience to experience both Cooper and Murph’s life on the same platform.

Name: Lydia Hand
University/Course: Hereford College of Arts, Illustration BA(Hons)
Description: My work is about memory, space and place. This illustration captures a memory from my time in Savannah, Georgia last year, walking and exploring the beautiful streets. Currently I am working on a comic based around a sentimental memory of a dress, the story behind the memory.

Name: Harry Lam
University/Course: York St John University, Graphic Design
Description:
The aim of this project is to spread useful information for people within the UK regarding the COVID-19 pandemic, including correct information of how to protect yourself, Stop Spreading, and knowing the symptoms, all the information are found from the UK Government website, NHS website and  the World Health Organization website. 
There are a lot of people dealing with stress and fear during this difficult time, and there are researches shown some people are glad they can spend more time with their family, due to the lock down and work from home situation. 
Base on the research, I have decided to create a double-sided A1 paper, which can be fold down to A4, including a poster to on one side, and some useful information / mini games on the other side. The poster will be a full A1 side poster which people can hang on walls; the aim is to spread positivity using illustrations. The half other side will be information about COVID-19, such as what we can do to stop the spreading, some most common symptoms, and how to wash hands correctly. Another half are some simple paper and pen games that people can play with their family.
The plan is to set up a subscription, and have it mailed to people physically, spread positivity as well as show case some artist’s design. All the profit can be donated to health career.

Name: Daniel Hadley
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University, Graphic Arts and Design
Description: This poster  considers branding a fictional craft beer brand known for their attitude, in a way that disrupts the usual advertising aesthetic.

Name: Elle Davies
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description:
The costume is of a Hag from the fairytale 'East of the Son, West of the Moon' by Peter Christen Asbjørnsen and Jørgen Moe.
 However, I adapted this fairy tale into a futuristic performance where the Earth has been destroyed by climate change.  
The Hag represents the fashion industry and the harmful effects it has on the environment; from fast fashion, river pollution and the waste the industry causes

Name: Duncan Lomax
University/Course: Ruskin School of Art, University of Oxford - Fine Art
Description:
What does it mean to wash a Mobike?
2019
Large scale digital print

This work is a photograph documenting a durational performance piece. It shows a busy intersection. At its centre the artist kneels, washing a Mobike bike-sharing bike by hand. 

Throughout the last year cities across the UK have been awash with competing bike-sharing schemes. In Oxford there are three: Mobike, Ofo, and Pony. The bikes constitute mobile architectures blurring public, private, and personal space; physical indexes of global venture capital. I spent a week walking around the city, washing bike-sharing bikes where I found them with a bucket of soap and water.

Name: Rebecca Dawson
University/Course: Ulster University, Fine Art.
Description:
My work explores the relationship we have with landscape, nature and our surroundings.  On closer inspection the landscapes and 'natural' environments are in fact constructed spaces. Man-made and controlled.  
The perception of natural spaces interests me and how we interact with them, where in my work I question: what is natural?

Name: Emily Kent
University/Course: University of Brighton and Graphic Design
Description: A photograph from a project where I documented my family caravan. I have so many nostalgic memories of staying in the caravan and even though it is falling apart it is such a special place.

Name: Veronika Marxer
University/Course: Kingston University - School of Art
Description: This is a speculative project tackling the issue of urban trees within 10 meters of an street light becoming stressed within 30 minutes! It is widely known that plants need light to survive, grow and reproduce. It is often assumed that more light is always beneficial; however, excess light can actually be harmful for plants.

Name: Vitória Damiani
University/Course: Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp, Graphic Design
Description: Time seems to push and cast people’s routines and habits, often imprisoning or dictating a sort of unbalanced rhythm. The supremacy of the uncontrollable and formidable fourth dimension has to be measured and analysed in order for us to feel slightly dominant in relation to time. What kind impact do these time annotations have in our lives? "It's a matter of time" attempts to explore the possibilities of time-registering, as well as understand the influence of this standardisation in society.

Name: James Sheard
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA(Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Display typeface Castle, and accompanying type specimen, was inspired by Welsh history. It references these visually through exaggerated serifs as well as Wales' rich Industrial Revolution which is shown through the block type style.

Name: Joanna Dunne
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA (Hons) Textile Design
Description: This beetle pattern has been created using a digital tissue paper collage effect. It was made for my collection Wild Garden for childrens-wear, focusing on the tiny world outside in your garden, and reconnecting with nature.

Name: Holly Kennedy
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University and Fashion
Description: My digitally designed collection is surrounding the beautiful patterns found within bacteria. Inspired by the good news and deeds happening around the world, following the Coronavirus outbreak. Proving that beauty really can come from anything.

Name: Keaton Powell
University/Course: Leeds Beckett, Graphic Art & Design
Description: Influenced by football match day programmes from the 70s, I created Halftime—a limited series of publications that celebrate niche and humorous topics within football through photographs and essays. The four topics include pies, streaking, mascots, and hairy footballers. I wanted to challenge current-day programmes and see if an alternative narrative could be used to create a more entertaining half time read.

Name: Emily James
University/Course: Textile Design at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Daydream is a collection of products designed to create a calming room for young children who are suffering from mental health issues. An environment for children, where everyday distractions are removed, and relaxation and concentration is encouraged. With the use of calming colours, imagery and tactile embroidery, Daydream creates a road to a mental escape in a safe and secure environment. With inspiration drawn from nature and the wild imaginations of children, the collection has a sophisticated yet childlike quality. The mood is exciting yet calming, filled with colourful and innocent imagery designed to provoke the need to express their thoughts and feelings.

Name: Maroa-Isabell Al-Sahlani
University/Course: De Montfort University
Description: This is from a book called "Cables" I made in my final year at university, about the unstable electricity situation in Iraq. I was able to visit Iraq in 2019, one of the first things I noticed were the exposed wiring all around Baghdad. I took many photographs and compiled them into this editorial driven book with an emphasis on the images. Through research I found out a lot of the real reasons for the deteriorating grid and the politics of why Iraq has such a bad electricity system when it is one of the largest exporters of oil. A mixture of political meddling from neighboring Iran and the US with a corrupt government has ultimately led to images shown in my book. I explored this project using reportage illustration as well.
Website: I'm in the process of creating a website, stay tuned!

Name: Charis Dussek
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Animation
Description: A still from my short animated film "Trapeze", the story of a clumsy clown who dreams of being a graceful trapeze artist. He overcomes his fear to realise his dream, but not without his fair share of obstacles!

Name: James Scott
University/Course: Fine Art at University of Oxford
Description: Through the setting up of investigations I play the role of the pioneer. These investigations often remain futile, yet they are achieved through precision to question our relationship to objects and systems. 'something may happen with PVC tape' documents an experimental set up that considers the play between independent and dependent variables.

Name: Sarah Krajovska
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art - Graphic Design
Description:
When life gives you lemons' 2020 by Sarah Krajovska
Original: 40cm x 50cm acrylic on canvas

This piece is inspired by the COVID-19 circumstances, in response to which I am attempting to spread some light-hearted optimism. PS SMILING AND LAUGHING decreases stress hormones and increases immune cells and infection-fighting antibodies! Stay creased :)

Name: Lily Laura Jane
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Animation
Description:
My 2D Animated Show-reel, showcasing my best work.
Including, walk cycles, cats, and scenes from my short Animated films.
You can watch it on my website.

Name: Patrick Thomas
University/Course: Camberwell. Illustration BA
Description:
My final project explores the history of Cornwall through a series of narratives. This image displays two smugglers delivering cargo. Characters of southwest  folklore and real characters of history coexist in the same narrative world. 

The work aims to inspire adventure through history and folklore, employing artefacts and parts of the landscape to aid adventure.

This illustration is from early on in the book, it feels tense. What might await them in the dark woods? What might await our smugglers in this mysterious world?

Name: Nure Abbas
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University International Fashion Business
Description: Finding out if Digital Clothing has the potential to reduce physical clothing waste consumption in Gen Z
Instagram: My account got hacked during quarantine, for this submission I previously submitted the wrong image. Please ignore that one. And forward this one as a submission instead, Thank you.

Name: Jenna Hewitt
University/Course: Leeds Arts University studying Textile Design
Description: This collection of designs is based on the flora of the Yorkshire Dales - taking inspiration from the plants and colours and translating them into designs for interiors. I wanted to explore the huge variety of flora through my love of drawing and painting and to show some of what I see when I am walking in the Yorkshire Dales

Name: Linzi MacLaren
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, and I study Textile Design.
Description: To combat fast fashion, I am challenging stereotypes of beauty by finding the allure in what we may usually deem repulsive. I have developed imagery from decaying raspberries to create timeless and handcrafted Textile pieces to be cherished. Like fast fashion, this raspberry has gone out of date, but by finding the beauty within it I want to show that fashion should have no expiry date.

Name: Vivian Phang
University/Course: University of Hertfordshire, BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description:
A campaign to help me find a British spouse before my Tier 4 Visa expires. This is to highlight the challenges and difficulties faced by international students when they want to work in the UK after graduation. 

Marrying a British citizen so I am able to stay in the UK seems like an easier and more probable solution than getting a job.

Name: Tami Aftab
University/Course: London College of Communication, BA Photography
Description:
“The Dog’s in the Car” Mum shouts from upstairs. Dad’s been running around the house, in and out of the garden thinking that he has lost Rudi, our dog. This is a common occurrence, where Dad drives back from a dog walk, forgets he’s in the car, comes in to the house and proceeds to think that he has lost him.  My Dad, Tony, suffers with an illness called hydrocephalus, which causes him to build up too much fluid in the brain. 25 years ago Dad went in for an operation to put a hole in his head that would allow the liquid to flow. However, during the operation his short-term memory was accidentally damaged, permanently leaving him with a unique short term memory difficulty.

The Dog’s in the Car is a collaboration between the artist and her father. Using a playful voice, the artist questions the hushed tones that can surround illness, questions on collaboration and consent, family as subject and the space between documentary and performance. Moreover,  it is a story about a father - daughter relationship, and how one family deals with illness and identity.

Name: Megan Dymock
University/Course: Illustration at Cambridge School of Art
Description: The image is based on Gartur Stitch Farm in Scotland. This photo forms part of a bigger project aimed to promote the brilliant classes and workshops they offer where people of all ages can learn about the natural world and invaluable skills about how we can use natural ingredients in our every day lives.

Name: Isaac Izekor
University/Course: Ravensbourne University - Advertising and Brand Design
Description:
Greenwich Psychology - Not To Scale

The closer you are to a setback, the bigger it seems. This OOH Advertising campaign for Greenwich Psychology aims to demystify therapy. And highlight the value of speaking to the right person at the right time.

Name: Molly Whitt
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, I studied Animation BA (Hons)
Description: This is a close up shot of a scene from my third year Look Development Project.

Name: Simranjeet Garcha
University/Course: University of Westminster, BA (Hons) Contemporary Media Practice
Description: A women's football documentary based on the lower tiers of the game.

Name: Claudia Aggett
University/Course: Falmouth University and I studied BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description:
Manchester has long been recognised for its rich musical heritage. Having birthed the likes of The Smiths, Oasis and New Order, the city is known for being a hub for all genres of music, with these iconic names in British pop culture not only putting Manchester on the map, but also paving the way for future generations. New emerging artists prove that Manchester’s music scene continues to thrive, rightfully earning its status as the music capital of the UK. 

In June 2019, The Institute for Public Policy Research released a report labelling Manchester’s pollution levels as “lethal and illegal”. With this in mind, how can we combine the city’s love of music with a more sustainable mode of transport to tackle Manchester’s air quality crisis?

Introducing 45RPM, Manchester’s revolutionary bike hire scheme in partnership with Spotify – celebrating the city’s rich music culture – past, present and the future. 

With its name deriving from the most common vinyl single, the 45 (and the records’ revolutions per minute) this dock-based hire scheme encourages an innovative and safe inner-city cycling experience with its fun, pedal-powered musical bikes.

So how does it work? At the turn of the bike wheel, music will be played aloud, the song’s tempo determined by the cyclist’s speed and revolutions of the pedals. Simply, the faster the pedalling, the faster the song. This ensures the recommended inner-city cycling speed is always maintained, providing a safe environment for all.

Name: Cara Kennedy
University/Course: Sculpture and Environmental Art at the Glasgow School of Art
Description:
Clay is a notoriously stubborn, labour-intensive and unforgiving material. Embracing these properties, I create ceramic vessels and sculptures marked by my tactile experience of sculpting the clay with my hands. The audience encounters the physical as well as visual: finger imprints, throwing rings, join lines and scoring, emphasising the artist’s hand in the creation of each individual piece. I avoid placing a narrative on the work, instead, the markings narrate the self-contained personal histories in the clay body of each vessel.

In this installation, I have assembled groups of clay objects; some clustered together, others decidedly separate, at varying heights. Inhabiting the space in this way, the unique handcrafted vessels lose their autonomy, gaining an aesthetic force within groups of related forms. Inspired by the installations of Edmund de Waal, the unusual groupings and placement of the work challenges traditional arrangements of functional ceramics with a theatrical twist.

Name: Georgia Bolton
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description:
‘Terms of Disservice’ is a broadsheet newsprint of Facebook’s data policy in response to a dissertation questioning ‘how graphic design be a disruptive force
for social change?’ It uses typography and editorial distortions to highlight the manipulative tactics in online data collection.

Name: Nure Abbas
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University International Fashion Business
Description: Finding out if digital clothing has the potential to reduce physical clothing waste consumption in the future

Name: Nikoletta Hristova
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University - Graphic Design and Illustration
Description: Motif is a set of playing cards designed especially for one of the most popular card games in Bulgaria - Belote. The design of the cards and the box is inspired by popular Bulgarian embroideries and motifs. On the right corner of each card is presented its power for both variations of the game - AT (all trumps) and NT (no trumps). This aims to help new players learn the rules fast and start playing, simply by placing the most important details on the cards themselves.

Name: Nicole Hall
University/Course: Grays School of Art Contemporary Art Practice
Description: I am inspired by everyday happenings, emotions and the seemingly banal. I use film photography to investigate the Maternal experience. I place my daughter at the centre of my work exploring our relationship and my own identity in the realm of Motherhood. I believe my work is as much about my daughter as it is myself, detailing where we have been and where we are now in an autobiographical visual telling.

Name: Zoë Victoire
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores, studying Fashion Communication
Description:
The image was taken to be included in an editorial for Wonderland Magazine.
Inspired by the classic fairy tale 'Snow White' by The Brothers Grimm.

Name: Victoria
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art
Description: Victoria Rankin is predominantly using latex and silicone rubber to create small text works and skin-like sculptures covered in hair to symbolise social pressure to conform to ideals, masking the true self for fear of judgement, and the wearing of a persona that is not actually who you really are, but who you pretend to be to others and at times, even to yourself.

Name: Tijana Petrovic
University/Course: University of the Arts London
Description: The atmosphere on this painting is lonely and melancholic. The subject matter is related to time passing, limited number of things we are going to be able to experience during our lifetime, and, consequently,  the importance of choices we make.

Name: Yanis Berrewaerts
University/Course: A master degree in graphic design at The Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp
Description: In my master project i researched the possibilities of using your own body as a graphic design tool. This autonomous anatomical design experiment resulted in a world where the real is synthesized with new elements, inflated dreams, materialized feelings, draped with my own skin, creating new perspectives for my own design practice. It is essentially merging the anatomical designer with the autonomous design into a hybrid.

Name: Phoenix Almeida-Amir
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, studied Animation BA (Hons)
Description: The film is about artificial intelligence, conflicting goals between a boss and an employee, and rivalry between human and machine.

Name: Tijana Petrovic
University/Course: University of the Arts London
Description: This is a portrait of boyfriend and girlfriend – boyfriend being the shorter one.

Name: George Davison
University/Course: Kingston School of Art
Description: My submission entry into the ISTD student assessment, where I updated the whole of The Divine Comedy Paradiso book. This included using the English Longfellow translation, interweaved between that is the original Italian poem, with commentary along the outside column from Charles S. Singleton, and the etymology and definitions of archaic words in the inside column. I have also cut my own version of Bembo to include custom designed glyphs, highlighting ornate craft from the 1300s and how that has changed within contemporary book design.

Name: Tijana Petrovic
University/Course: University of the Arts London, MA Fine Art
Description: On this painting strawberry is a substitute for a figure. The atmosphere is ominous and alludes that the subject matter could be serious. Yet, the choice and combination of motifs gives it a slight comical value.

Name: Rosanna O'Kane
University/Course: University of Ulster - BDes Graphic Design & Illustration
Description: I designed a print newspaper called The Mediator which provides unbiased journalism and rejects the sensationalism of the 24hr news cycle. Multiple journalists writing from multiple perspectives contribute to each single article, and the cover story is depicted by two conflicting headlines on the front cover layered over each other. A newspaper which challenges your beliefs, asks you to think and understand, and doesn't tell you how to think.

Name: Hamzah Shaikh
University/Course: De Montfort University- Graphic Design
Description: My work is inspired by nature, I envision a world where nature become part of our daily lives and I intend to show this through my art work. This particular book cover is about the Japanese art of Shinrin-Yoku which translates to forest bathing. I intended to encourage people to take part in this activity and spent more time with nature to help with health and relaxation.

Name: Sharon Maycock
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University BA(Hons) Fine Art
Description: From a small town in Derbyshire artist Sharon Maycock works with a number of different mediums, predominantly moving image, to create a dystopian/utopian mix of worlds. Having grown up watching Star Trek and nature documentaries she explores the unknown and what the world could look like in a post-apocalyptic, post human future. Coming from Derbyshire which is the birth place of the industrial revolution Maycock has an interest in the Anthropocene and her work raises concerns over the effect humanity has had on the planet during this period of geological time and what it could mean to the world in the future.  Creating sculptural maquettes out of circuit boards she uses computer software to give these films a science fiction edge. Maycock then uses large scale projections to show her moving image pieces thus playing with scale. Informed by her love of reading science fiction writers such as J. G. Ballard focusing on the books ‘Hello America’ and ‘The Drowned World’ she uses these due to the references to global collapse with a science fiction undertone.

Name: Charlie Shreeve
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth,  Graphic Design
Description: The Posh Pig is a stout infused with premium British bacon made in response to JDO Mash Brief. I created a marquee character, “Porky Poshington” to be the centralisation for all marketing and packaging as I aimed to bring a quirky and intriguing beer into the market, with “Porky” personifying this desire. The vibrant design hones in on the flavour, with the bacon-themed colour palette and textures featured through-out. “Porky Poshington” will help the brand become recognisable and spark intrigue into the product through the playful nature of the brand allowing for endless creative opportunities, pushing the brand further and allowing for adventurous and fun marketing material to be played with.

Name: Rajal Chita
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic Design
Description: A new pop up restaurant rebrand for Pizza Express that explores 8 different countries and cultures around the world through pizzas made on national foods of each country. It will additionally explore other cultural foods from a range of countries in the restaurants special menus and aims to bring people around the world together through food.

Name: Natasha S. Fletcher
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art: Sculpture/Environmental Art
Description: I am an environmentally-based artist interested in the body's relationship to space and place. Viewing the city as a living organism, buildings and streets become external bodies through which we localise and experience the human consciousness. With particular focus on domestic dwellings, I explore the sense of belonging and being belonged to an external space.

Name: Emily McNeill
University/Course: DJCAD, BA Fine Art
Description:
My work strives to create a cosy, fantastical dreamworld with fluffy fabrics and sweet colours, serving as a hug for the eyes, blurring the semantic boundary between art and craft. 
Through my art I showcase craft as a viable means of expression within the art world, exploring and confronting the dismissal of the typically feminine and domestic craft spheres. My work is self-nurturing, joyful, and celebrates the decorative with optimism.

Name: Ceidra Moon Murphy
University/Course: Fine Art at Ruskin School of Fine Art, Oxford University
Description: My work explores the disintegration of meaning and understanding within forms of communication. Experimenting with multiple media, I generate an archive of information which binds past to present, accident to intention, memory to false memory. In doing this, I question how truth is circulated and managed in contemporary society.

Name: Carly Cuddy
University/Course: Ulster University
Description: Pushing the Limits. Pushing till the metal rips, frays and tears. Stressing the traditional foldforming technique, producing extremely thin and fragile sculptural table-top pieces. Creating a range of pieces, which have an organic look and each with it's own unique form

Name: Eleanor Spickett
University/Course: University of Central Lancashire
Description: The sun is the traditional way of telling the time. Aperitivo, pre meal drinks with the ones that matter most to us, as the sun goes down. Telling time via the sun to indicate ‘Martini Time’. Keeping tradition and friendships alive with Martini.

Name: Hazel Molly Laing
University/Course: University of Edinburgh - Illustration
Description: This illustration is a spread from my Swan Lake children's picture book. It depicts the ladies who were turned into swans by the sorcerer Von Rathbort, back into their human selves again.

Name: Katie May Anderson
University/Course: University of Edinburgh
Description: I study the design and making of costumes for performance, with a particular interest in researching and creating historical garments. This costume is inspired one of my favourite novels The Tenant of Wildfell Hall by Anne Brontë. The book is cited as one of the first feminist novels, as it follows the story of an abused woman running away from her husband to protect herself and her child. My designs seek to reflect the vibrant characters the book contains and illustrate the unique fashion of the era. As well as the dress I created a corset, piped petticoat and arm supports to help create the dramatic 1830s shape

Name: kaitlyn
University/Course: northern school of art
Description: This is an illustration I did for my final show which was a part of six illustration all of mythical creatures which have feature from animals form different countries and environments. I wanted to do something relating to nature because I love for animals and the outdoors.

Name: Kai Ting Wong
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Inspired by the ever changing seasons of mother nature, flower child is a series of candles that celebrates the empowerment and transformation of a woman. By transforming an ordinary product into something extraordinary, Flower child has created the first candle that blooms, embracing a woman's growth as something precious and should be enjoyed to the fullest, just like a flower in bloom.

Name: Gergana Popova
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University, Graphic Design and Illustrations
Description:
Rakia is a Bulgarian alcohol drink, usually produced at home. It is made of fruits (plum, pear, peach, etc.) and sugar. It has a strong spirit taste and unique flavor that makes it a favorite drink of many.

I designed a newspaper that not only informs its readers about the drink but also puts it into a social context, explaining the meaning of the process for Bulgarian people and culture:

“It is there, in an old grandad's copper kettle, on cracking firewood, surrounded by the sound of lively conversations and exhilaration, is where real rakia is born"

I believe that fonts, the same way as drinks, have their home country. Therefore, I revived the typeface from a Bulgarian newspaper heading from the 1940 edition of "Народна отбрана" /National Defence/ and named after the drink.

Name: Isabella Loughlin
University/Course: University of Central Lancashire
Description:
Construction work has become the deadliest profession in the UK.

The long hours, poor working conditions, unsteady employment and the overly masculine culture,
is helping push two workers a day over the edge.

Destruction Workers is a social awareness campaign created to shed light on the suicidal rates of men in the profession.

Name: Athelia White
University/Course: Textile Design at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Changing the way we think about fashion, this concept thrives off the exaggeration of shape and form. Taking inspiration from common garment defects, the collection showcases ideas that challenge conventional dress. Having a theatrical presence, EXAGGERATE ME! consists of fabrics that bulge, pucker, and expand, forming a ‘Make to State’ collection, fit for the catwalk.

Name: David Marshall
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University - Graphic Arts & Design
Description: Photomontage piece inspired by fashion and 50s/60s/70s science fiction. Designed to be displayed at large scale - ideally billboard.

Name: Noah Silver
University/Course: Kingston School of Art and Graphic Design
Description: A character from a speculative TV show called the Grassroots that educates children about activism. The Grassroots teaches children about justice, resilience, creativity and hope and most importantly how to change the world. This character is called ‘Blomst’ which is the Danish word for flower.

Name: Maisie Farrer
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design
Description:
My work explores the relationship between the raw do-it-yourself aspect of punk and the luxurious made-to-measure detail celebrated in couture. 

Each collection is inspired by the history of feminine fashion and looks to challenge silhouette and form.

Name: Olivia Hindle
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: My degree show brief is to design for a Mallorcan home renovation project.  This particular design is created for the application on a linen wall mural and is painted from a primary image which holds meaningful memories for my client.  My collection intends to provoke emotional attachments between the client and their home, in order to reduce the desire to consume and minimise the discarding of interior textile products.

Name: Molly Redmond
University/Course: Robert Gordon University
Description: My work is about bringing as much colour and positivity into the world as I can. This particular piece is about the world being in lockdown; together but alone

Name: Shuangge Song
University/Course: CCCU, Photography
Description: This photograph is selected from my series "Another World" which I made during January - May. This particular work presents the desire of people escaping this COVID-19 situation to an alternative reality or an another world in a fictitious way. However it is not a staged work.

Name: Imi Gash
University/Course: Kingston School of Art Graphic Design
Description: And no you cannot nip in and get milk'. What if the authoritative dialect that surrounds us had a voice.  As humans we are conditioned to trust all things that conform to a certain visual language. Designed to make us question the lawful language we are surrounded by, the sign exploit the truths of parking using passive aggressive language.

Name: Natalia Losowicka
University/Course: Robert Gordon University, Communication Design
Description: RGU Ride is a bike scheme available to students and staff at Robert Gordon University. The brand promotes physical and mental well-being through exercise.

Name: Natty Hawkings
University/Course: Falmouth University, Graphic Design
Description:
Unwind.

A  repositioning of the UK's No.1 Rioja, Campo Viejo. Partnering with BA, consumers will see the brand from a new perspective. 

The interactive concept extends from packaging, to a smart watch app and even an airport lounge experience. Unwinding  the full story of the brand, the consumer is invited to discover what truly goes into each bottle, while they themsleves unwind and relax. 

Playful colour and gradients embody the craft and artistry of each bottle in a dynamic and fun style true to the brand’s personality. The river Ebro, flows through the campaign. In real life, it flows through the Campo Viejo vineyard, bringing their grapes to life. To celebrate its unique qualities, its organic form is used as the visual knot that ties touch points together. 

From check in to arrival and of course on board,  Campo Viejo gives you multiple opportunities to unwind, so you can focus on the moment, and live a life more colourful.

Name: Thomas McKay
University/Course: Gray's School Of Art - BA(hons) Communication Design
Description: This project was a smaller brief that I had carried out rather close to my final year hand in. I wanted to explore how we as creative students go through the motions of a project whilst we carry it out. I created one poster each day that corresponded to a 6 day deadline that I had given myself to complete one of my projects for hand in. Each poster represents visually the emotions I was feeling at the end of each day.

Name: Lisa Reynolds
University/Course: I am graduating from DJCAD and I studied Fine Art
Description: My work focuses on the thin line between fact and fiction. To explore this I created the 'Mothbam' - a fictional creature who allegedly stalks the streets of Scotland at night. Inspired by the 'Mothman' of West Virginia, I wanted to give Scotland its own legendary creature.

Name: Shuangge Song, but usually I create with my alternative name which is "RiddleViernes" on social media (IG)
University/Course: CCCU, Photography.
Description: This photograph is selected from my series "Another World" which I made during January to May. This particular work presents the desire of people escaping this COVID-19 situation to an alternative reality or an another world in a fictitious way. However it is not a staged work. I don´t know is it is allowed here but please have a look too the entire series at www.riddleviernes.com/another-world#1

Name: Courteney King
University/Course: University of Hertfordshire - Graphic Design
Description: Daddy Crafts is a brand that sells personalised colouring books, that demonstrates the love between a father and their child.

Name: Alex Fage
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: Amazon spirit is a habanero flavoured gin that is designed to challenge the current market. It is a medium to educate the world on the indigenous women of brazil's on going struggle in protest to protect their homeland from man made forest fires.

Name: Juliette Stuart
University/Course: University of the Arts London - BA(hons) Illustration and Visual Media
Description: Ogle' is a short film that functions as a surreal instructional video on how to behave as a human being.

Name: Ashley Chadwick
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire, BA Fine Art
Description:
The relationship between expectation and reality allows for a double existence; a delivery of distorted encounters that contradict one another. What you see is not what you get. 
Roman architecture, the visual perceptual system and illusionistic spaces led my inquisition into challenging the relationship between the physical and digital way things are viewed. 
This particular work embodies mathematical roulette curves found in hypotrochoids, challenging associated dimensions of drawings and the notion of expected scale.

Name: Myles
University/Course: Loughborough University (Graphic Communication)
Description: Inspired by The Beatles song of the same name, the work submitted is an extract from my most recent project 'When I'm Sixty Four', which is a typography lead campaign that aims to tackle head on the underfunding of care homes in the UK in the wake of COVID-19. The specific image I have submitted is a collection of posters from THE campaign, which utilises a combination between clean modern typography design and handwritten elements to convey the illusion of underlining messages within the music, whilst simultaneously showing the disparity in funding of the care sector when compared to the NHS. I chose to submit this particular extract from my work as care homes at the epicentre of the COVID-19 death toll and I think it is extremely important that people do not overlook one of the most harshly impacted areas within this country.

Name: Sarah McAlpine
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description:
This was a submission for ISTD 2020, as a response to the Migration brief.

This screw-bound landscape book explores the future of human migration, which will be into space, most likely to the Moon and on to Mars. The design piece communicates the urgency of our migration, using the landscape format, shocking type and contrasting paper colours.

Name: Sam Perryman
University/Course: Kingston school of art, design marketing
Description: The little ballerina is about opening up the LGBTQ community and the journey, showing a little boy wearing a ballerina dress try and find where he fits in the world. The augmented reality brings a world of colour to the pages and hidden real life stories from the LGBTQ community too.

Name: Ainsley Eagle
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description: A whiskey with 0% alcohol distilled and bottled within Thameside prison as part of a rehabilitation program for prison inmates

Name: Julie Stone
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth Illustration
Description: I made a series of postcards which could be sent to loved ones to remind them of helpful wellness habits, such as staying hydrated and breathing in morning air. This one was about keeping in touch with others, both physically and emotionally.

Name: Kangwa Saili
University/Course: UAL:LCC Graphic Branding and Identity
Description: Clits, Tits & Other Bits is an activity-based game to educate you on you guessed it… clits, tits and other bits!  Be inspired and get creative with our 4 different activity rounds tailored to help you gain knowledge and understanding. There is a lack of education for women about their bodies, sexual and vaginal health. This is apparent in all ages of development as the taboo of speaking about anything other than basic wants is carried through to adulthood. Women can become unaware of their bodies as they follow misleading information from various mediums such as online videos, television shows and even from conversations.  This is why exploring the body on a personal level allows for us to become independent in understanding both our needs and wants through our own personal boundaries. Clits, tits & other bits is a game made for all ages, genders and beliefs to allow for the societal barriers to be excused in a safe place as a community of players. The game aims to allow players to truly understand the details of the bodies which they live in or partner with.

Name: Katie Marshall
University/Course: University of Dundee (DJCAD), Textile Design
Description:
I believe the future of sportswear needs to incorporate the use of environmentally positive materials. 

I have designed a collection that can be printed on recycled materials, including Econyl and eco regenerated Lycra. The wild, thrilling essence of the ocean moulded my design work into a collection that visually encapsulates the electric energy of the sea, and the motion of the active wearer. The playful, electrifying nature of the undulating forms, with dynamic colour stories and powerful contextual poses, embody the positive and exciting potential of eco design.

Name: Charlotte Key
University/Course: Nottingham Trent , Graphic Design
Description: A Braille children's book collection, about inspirational blind people and their carers. Braille is important for blind children as it teaches them vital literacy skills such as spelling, punctuation and grammer which audiobooks can not teach.
