This is a photo from A for Astronomy, focusing on Nic Bonne a visually impaired astronomer. The book is printed in both Braille and text, with tactile illustrations throughout.

Name: Victoria King
University/Course: Robert Gordon University
Description: I am researching alternatives to the supermarket experience. I have designed a brand for a plastic free supermarket in the city of Aberdeen. This is a custom logo where the letterforms are designed to look like aisles.

Name: Nada khartabil
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: It’s called ‘It’s my heritage’ with the key focus on these rocks I had taken as a souviner of some case to show my heritage from these two cities (family came from originally)which were destroyed in the occupation of Palestine 1948
Website: I don’t have a specific link to it all

Name: Jessica Butler
University/Course: Ulster University, Belfast Textile, Art Design and Fashion
Description: My final print collection is based on the obscure natural formations in the environment from a satalite viewpoint. I wanted to explore the bizarre shapes and colours found- mostly due the impact humans have had on the planet.

Name: Eve Wallis
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description:
Endometriosis is the second most common gynaecological condition in the UK, with 1 in 10 women effected worldwide. However, only 20% of the population know what endometriosis is, resulting in women being diagnosed incorrectly. 

The Endo Tales is a campaign that aims to generate awareness of the menstrual condition and educate both men and women worldwide. Its strategy is to build a community of people, driven by sufferers, who can use their personal experience to teach the public about endometriosis. Their stories have shaped and formed each touchpoint, creating a personal and honest campaign.

Name: Eve Wallis
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description:
The 2020 Tokyo Olympics has been postponed to 2021 due to a world pandemic. Train like an Olympian is turning the year wait into a positive, aiming to boost morale globally. By partnering with Durex, it has created a limited-edition product range that rebuilds anticipation and excitement for the 2021 Tokyo Olympics, whilst advertising safe sex.  

It’s your time to shine, so grab your baton, stay safe and train hard. 

Get fit with Durex this year. 

JOINT PROJECT with Alice Stone @alicestonedesigns / alicegstone99@outlook.com

Name: Jessica Murray
University/Course: WSA, University of Southampton
Description:
Jazz and Azul is a single-player story-driven adventure game set within a world segregated by jazz and blues music.  

Players embark on an adventure in which they are able to relive an important chapter in both Jazz and Azul’s lives; the day these two young friends went on a journey to destroy a wall that divided them. With the powerful combination of both puzzle-solving and music, players must overcome the challenges of this cruel, diverse world. 

Jazz and Azul inspires conversation and cooperation to encourage players to reflect on real-world issues, as it’s fundamental core is heavily influenced by the music, history and culture of jazz and blues. This coming-of-age adventure exposes players to the harsh realities caused by segregation and discrimination, whilst also emphasising how cooperation, determination and friendship can break that vicious cycle. 

What trials did Jazz and Azul face that day? How were they able to help each other on either side of the Great Divide? Were they be able to destroy the wall or did their overbearing, bigoted communities still have a hold over them?
Website: Instagram/twitter= @jazzandazul, website = www.jazzandazul.com (under development) , uni games hub/other 3rd year games = https://wsagames.com/
Instagram: @queengamemachine and @adam._w_ (we are a team of two!)

Name: Rosie McIlwaine
University/Course: Ulster University - Ceramics, Jewellery and Silversmithing
Description: Inspired by the rainbows cast from prisms and the light refracting abilities of gemstones such as diamonds, Rosemary embeds small acrylic and glass objects into resin which at first glance aren’t visible but when interacted with in the light reveal themselves. Each piece is unique as she hand carves the resin into angular shapes with a geometric-like feel but without the regularity. With a colour palette inspired by the rainbow, she adds pigments and reflective glitters to the resin, enhancing the texture that the embeds create within her pieces. Worn on the hand, Rosemary’s work placed within the light, ignites a spark and asks that the wearer look at things from a different perspective, so as to reveal the beauty that lies beneath the surface.

Name: Tia Collis
University/Course: Portsmouth University. Graphic Design.
Description:
I was asked for a new way to interpret the final Canto in Dante’s book, Paradiso, from the Divine Comedy series. The aim was to appeal to a new audience using any method of communication that would suit the text and my chosen concept.

Paradiso details Dante’s journey through Heaven and the series of spheres that he traverses to meet God.  Throughout Paradiso, especially within the 33rd Canto, Dante uses the imagery of light repeatedly as a metaphor for Heaven and uses the brightest light as a representation of when he meets God Himself.  Light and dark (shadow) has been used frequently throughout history to represent heaven and hell; good and bad. 

This design is based around the idea of using light and shadow to read the text from the 33rd Canto in Paradiso.  The lampshade is attached to a ceiling fitting or light stand and, once the light is switched on, the text is projected onto the nearby walls surrounding the consumer with the Canto thereby transporting the reader into the representation of Paradise.

Name: Mattie Amatt
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Ba Ceramics
Description: My work explores the tactile relationship we have with the land. Pieces are handbuilt through a slow, rhythmical coiling of clay, then covered with slip or inscribed with porcelain. The rich colours are revealed once fired, a minimal palette of earthy tones created through the blending of clay bodies.

Name: Schwarz
University/Course: GBMC Greater Brighton Metropolitan College
Description:
I play with ideas of Detritus. Gathering it, manipulating it, layering it.
I look for beauty beneath the surface of the insignificant and the everyday, exploring a visually disjointed style.

Name: Izzy Latimer
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA Graphic Design
Description: Dancing Queen' is a J card design based upon the micro genre of Swedish Schlager. The J card represents the narrative of  the popular Swedish show named 'Melodifestivalen' with iconography displaying the journey of a successful schlager song.

Name: Kristy Gray
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University Artist Designer Maker
Description: This design is part of a lighting collection manufactured from sustainably sourced Ash and European Walnut. The designs aim to bridge the gap between smart lighting technology and traditional materials. The form and function of the lighting designs are driven by the importance of usability. I focus my designing on creating a positive impact, both mentally and physically. The integration of affordance and adaptability aims to improve the experience the user has with the design.

Name: Isobelle Brogan Hadley
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College
Description: My work is inspired by patterns found in nature, focussing on sustainable practice and circular design.

Name: Calum
University/Course: University of South Wales BA (Hons) Advertising Design
Description: A hypothetical collaborative project involving Vans and Tokyo 2021 Olympics to promote the introduction of skateboarding to the games.

Name: Tom
University/Course: Shillington College of Graphic Design London
Description:
The brief was to rebrand an existing Museum or Cultural Space. I took on the challenge of giving the H.R MacMillan Space Centre a new identity, designing a new logo, tone of voice, and graphic identity. This is a poster series campaign for the museum which aims to incorporate all of these and inspire more people to 
visit and explore the space centre.
Website: More work available on request (unfortunately no online portfolio just yet, watch this space)

Name: Dorota Liwacz
University/Course: I graduated at Academy of Fine Arts in Katowice in December 2019, I studied Graphics, did diploma in Intermedia and Illustration
Description: "Alien abduction" - this is a digital version of the illustration that I painted as a mural for my master's degree. It depicts a girl surrounded by objects of our era: fast food, drinks, technology, gadgets, cigarettes. We live in world of consumption and expressing identity through objects. My generation grew in this system and we try to find ourselves there, living between real life and fantasy. This illustration is expression of wanting to experience another world, some form of change, because the reality is not enough.

Name: Jaeyeon Choi
University/Course: Central Saint Martins (UAL)- MA Fine Art
Description: My work focuses on the abstract and the formless because existence cannot be defined as a single image or a single concept, and because, even if such a thing exists, it can be variable.

Name: Jessie Delatousche
University/Course: Graphic design at Dundee University (DJCAD)
Description: For a brief set by HSBC where they asked for an illustrated or animated campaign for the slogan "Together We Thrive". I based this campaign on HSBC's 5 main values - sport, trade & commerce, sustainability, education and diversity.  This is the sustainability poster (RGB) and the diversity poster (CMYK).

Name: Anastasia Frost
University/Course: University of Suffolk
Description: A campaign that aims to motivate students to use their smartphones less to engage with the real world while educating the importance of human interaction.

Name: Sophia Wee Blázquez
University/Course: University of Oxford, Fine Art
Description: Slick like oil, tough like rubber. Chicken feet for wandering, eating, viewing.

Name: Shohaib Bahadar
University/Course: Birmingham City University, I studied Graphic Communication
Description: The work which I'm submitting is apart of the Design Bridge Dog’s Bollocks Student Awards Brief 2020 in collaboration with The Guardian where I have been tasked to produce a campaign based on a headline, the headline which I've chosen was "Tokyo calling 20 Olympians ready to shine this summer" I have decided to use the brand Adidas in order to aid me with the campaign of #TeamSuperstar

Name: Emma Parker
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores Graphic Design and Illustration
Description: Illustrations of old tattoos found on heavy metal musicians in the style of blackwork tattoo genre

Name: Iona French
University/Course: Graphic Design at Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design
Description: Re-Gro is an initiative which recycles old baby gro's into hats for newborns in refugee camps. This poster is one of a set of 4 which describes the different ways the scheme provides hope to families living in refugee camps.

Name: Emily Knowles
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description:
A illustrative campaign for climate change involving postcards to show what our beautiful sights you stereotypically see on postcards could look like if we continue polluting our planet.

The idea is to make people aware of the effects of pollution on our planet by using something that is recognisable to everyone.

Name: Jessica Megan Roberts
University/Course: University of East London BA Fashion Design
Description:
My collection, named ‘God’s own Country’ is based on my family history and the lifestyle and characters of my grandparents. I grew up in Barnsley, south 
Yorkshire, a small mining town in the north of England. My grandad worked as a draughtsman in a lightbulb factory which I drew a lot of inspiration from. My Grandmother raised me, and my memories of her from my childhood also informed my collection. My collection is a love letter to my Grandparents and to my hometown.

Name: Amber Davies
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University. BA, Product Design
Description: Accessing reliable information sources for *ostomates with regards to daily living can be difficult with subject matters considered embarrassing or taboo unanswered leaving ostomates feeling isolated and confused. Inside Out is a social styled app with one of its key features being a podcast series that handles these unmet topics informatively but, importantly, personably with aim of breaking stereotypes, raising awareness and helping others feel less alone. *Ostomate - term for a person living with a stoma

Name: Shae Myles
University/Course: Gray's School of Art - Contemporary Art Practice
Description: Stemming from a fascination of psychosexual analysis, the basis of Shae's research explores our two most primitive and basic urges, the pleasures of hunger and sex. This series was born out of the conflicting emotions experienced during the lockdown of the COVID-19 pandemic. By using her alter-ego Cherry Shakes, Shae aims to capture the dual personality associated with stereotypical clowns; split between being bringing joy and delight to those around them, while displaying a cavernous sense of sadness and pain. Cherry Shakes embodies this contrast while she mourns her life and passions pre-isolation.

Name: Mahina Carver
University/Course: Falmouth University, Graphic Design
Description:
Chronic health awareness. 
Spoon theory is a way to communicate energy levels for people suffereing with chronic illnesses.
I feel it is important for this to be common knowledge as it will help many people in thier everyday lives. 
The orange spoon could become as recognisable and respected as a pink ribbon or a yellow daffodil.

Name: Saffron Laishley
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth, BA (Hons) Photography
Description:
In my work, I use mirrors in order to create illusion and visual tension. 

I aim to challenge the viewer’s perception by subtly intervening within the landscape. I would like to confuse the viewer and encourage them to question their own sight.

Name: Reanne McArthur
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, HND Graphic Design
Description:
Poster 1 of a set of 2 based on the theme of Silence. 

After researching I found out about the 'Cichociemni', who were Polish paratroopers who fought in WW2. The name literally translates to 'silent and unseen'. They were special agents, trained in a variety of highly skilled techniques, such as: silent killing, cryptography, and guerrilla tactics. The arrangement of the type is designed to represent a cipher, with the words 'silent' and 'unseen' as the hidden message.

Name: My name is Ioannis Evangelou
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic Design
Description: The project is a documentary photography publication, named "C O L D". This publication is a collection of photographs and quotes on the subject of homelessness in Leicester. The experimentation with the physicality and the layout of the publication was significant to deliver this final piece. As a designer, I strongly support the consideration of one's basic senses when I make design choices regarding physicality and layout.

Name: Dan
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Absent is a project that I created as part of my final year project. It focuses on ideas of loneliness and isolation by photographing empty, mundane human spaces. The still and quiet nature that the spatial and environmental conditions possess add an eerie and atmospheric feel to the images which are anchored by my exaggerated use of contrast and desaturation.

Name: Vanna Paabor
University/Course: Edinburgh University
Description: The Wood Dress. This is a piece from my first year project on the MFA Performance Costume course at Edinburgh College of Art. It is part of a project on sustainable consumption and production where I designed for groups of materials and represented them as industries. The shape is inspired by late 18th century as a reference to the start of the industrial revolution. The dress is made from wood (incl. veneered plywood, marquetry and burnt wood) cork and paper. It was an amazing challenge to make!
Website: Under construction, will be ready soon.

Name: Lucy
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic Design and Illustration
Description: This is an illustration from a series that I created for the book Goodnight Mister Tom. I wanted to create simple illustrations, that would subtly direct attention to the time period, without being too direct.

Name: Nathan Rowan
University/Course: Nottingham Trent Animation Ba
Description: I love turning mine and other peoples ideas into forms that can have life and performances brought to them

Name: Ellie Hall
University/Course: Graphic Design at Nottingham Trent University
Description: This series of postcards is my design led response to the Coronavirus Lockdown, encouraging people to reach out and write to one another. We are all stuck at home but making a ‘holiday’ out of the everyday can put a positive perspective on an unsettling time. Despite being separated physically, this is one way we can stay connected so the designs will take the form of physical postcards, digital greetings cards and social media filters on Snapchat and Instagram!

Name: Ruth Liggins
University/Course: I am graduating from Livepool John Moores University with a degree in Graphic Design and Illustration
Description:
Armchair Olympics 2020
My work is about the way we have all adapted our workouts to suit our home environments due to Covid-19. From squatting with our dogs to replacing a swimming pool with a wheelbarrow it is evident that athletes, parents and grandparents alike we have all found creative ways to keep moving  and to stay healthy at home.

Name: Rosie Bebber
University/Course: NUA, Graphic design
Description: This is a rebrand for Taylors of Harrogate coffee. The idea is based around the great number of unique mineral springs that have come to the surface in Harrogate than at any other known place on earth. Using this research the logo mark focuses around the well going into a cup that also has a hidden 't' and 'h'.

Name: Lottie Wittich
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, BA Product Design
Description: Medi lolli improves the storage system of self-administered injections that require home refrigeration and allows more freedom to travel.  It is difficult to keep on top of injection supplies, so the integrated LED system visually communicates by changing from white to red when an injection is no longer present.  The product is designed to stay cold during travel via cooling plates, a heat sync and a rechargeable battery.  The app has huge organisational benefit.  Reminders are created for: when the next injection is due, showing the date, time and location, the next delivery of medication and the capacity of the sharps bin with a reminder to be collected once full.  The app is synced with Medi lolli to ensure it is fully charged and maintains the correct temperature when the medication is being transported.

Name: Lottie Plimmer
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: My work was originally inspired by Graffiti found in Berlin. The graffiti read ' Too alien for earth, Too human for space' it made me reflect on the idea of individuality and what style and fashion meant for me. Creating my own sense of style by the people I meet and places I visit I wanted to create a collection that celebrated my approach to style and identity. The collection focuses on the idea of a human case study, exploring the idea of someone from out of this world interpreting my clothing and influences in an eclectic celebration of textile, pattern and layering.

Name: Bez Hall
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA Illustration
Description: This piece is from a larger work titled 'The Comfort of Stone'. The project as a whole is about exploring my identity as a Butch Lesbian, and how I relate to vulnerability within the context of external materials. This image in particular is about looking at the similarities between stone and skin within that context, and focusing on magnifying subtle differences, explored though experimenting with scale.

Name: Natasha Crudgington
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Third Year
Description: Bellywash is a charcoal shot created for the health drink sector. Charcoal energises and restores the body. Inspired by coal and the mining community, Bellywash is a term used by miners for a non-alcoholic drink.

Name: Ella Lovell
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Textile Design: Print
Description: My work is based on the concept of unknown territories, such as outer space and the deep sea. This design is called Kaleidoscope, and is inspired by the profusion of colour in the universe. I imagine travelling at light speed through space as galaxies, nebula and stars spin past. I envision that the colours would look as abstract and chaotic as this print.

Name: Natasha Crudgington
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Third Year
Description: Bloom is the healthy snack alternative that you’ve been waiting for once and flo-ral! Our brand is respectfully inspired by the Amazon rainforest and the tribes found within. Our snacks are healthy, sustainable and nutritious, with packaging designed to present the healthful alternative. The brand uses different aspects of the Amazon Rainforest across brand extensions, which helps you interact with the brand.

Name: Bethany Lawrence
University/Course: University of Portsmouth
Description:
This piece of work was for the ISTD Brand Type Brief created by Monotype. The brief was to design and create a fashion accessories brand that had been running for five years and looking to transition from a
designer/maker to a larger but sustainable brand. It had to be a locally manufactured, sustainable, and a luxury product for the discerning, design-aware but cost-conscious customer. Therefore, I started by thinking about how I could make this brand sustainable and environmentally friendly. Living in Portsmouth I am aware of plastic pollution, so my brand called 'Turn The Tide' makes jewelry from beach-combed materials. The name is supposed to reflect what the brand is doing by making something new and valuable from the waste we have created. I created the packaging, stationery, and look-book (as pictured) as well as having a go at making beach-combed jewelry myself.

Name: Louis Loveless
University/Course: Fine Art BA at University of East London
Description: My work involves assembling paintings like a collage, painting different images ontop of shapes and pasted materials, building up the image. I also collage different spaces, going from illusionistic depth to abstract flatness in a flowing line around the canvas. The paintings work almost like a relief. The content of the collage is about a search for truth and answers, via different forms: religion, science, conspiracy theories, philosophy etc. whilst simultaneously trying to demonstrate the issues with absolute belief in ideology.

Name: Eoin Monaghan
University/Course: I'm Graduating from Ulster University Belfast and I studied Animation.
Description: My animation is a silent, succinct, short film of a boy kidnapped from his family in a small rural village on the outskirts of a savanna. Focusing mainly on the boy, I wanted to portray a story of freedom and innocence, cut with an abrupt abduction into a life of captivity and war. I'm using my skills in animation to shed some light on this under-reported, global calamity.

Name: Alice Bramley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Costume Design and Making
Description: This is a costume design for the original Little Mermaid by Hans Christian Andersen for the daughters of the air. The concept is showing the story with the affects of pollution and considering how the costumes would have been decayed by this. In this instance lungs and air pollution have been factors to influence this particular design while also trying to appear beautiful and delicate.

Name: Tyler Sankey
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art- Illustration
Description: Experimenting with collage inspired by electro-swing and 90's rave music.

Name: Raellen Oceana Bonny
University/Course: university of the arts London, LCC
Description: Clits, Tits & Other Bits is an activity-based game to educate you on you guessed it… clits, tits and other bits!  Be inspired and get creative with our 4 different activity rounds tailored to help you gain knowledge and understanding. There is a lack of education for women about their bodies, sexual and vaginal health. This is apparent in all ages of development as the taboo of speaking about anything other than basic wants is carried through to adulthood. Women can become unaware of their bodies as they follow misleading information from various mediums such as online videos, television shows and even from conversations.  This is why exploring the body on a personal level allows for us to become independent in understanding both our needs and wants through our own personal boundaries. Clits, tits & other bits is a game made for all ages, genders and beliefs to allow for the societal barriers to be excused in a safe place as a community of players. The game aims to allow players to truly understand the details of the bodies which they live in or partner with.

Name: Claudia
University/Course: University of Portsmouth studying graphic design
Description: My book is a guide book for lifeguard to learn the hand signals we use to communicate. Having every pool using the same hand signal lifeguards won't get confused when working at a different pool.

Name: Ruth Foster
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Textile Design BA (Hons)
Description: Using sustainable, recycled, and natural fibres, my work aims to embody a stripped back and essential way of life suggested through the means of knitted interior fabric collections. I create lifestyle trends through research of the current global climate crisis, and hope to develop a connection between the consumer and nature by bringing the outdoors in, and designing environmentally-conscious fabrics using robust knitted techniques.

Name: Amy Haselden
University/Course: The University of Huddersfield - Graphic Design BA (Hons)
Description: For my final major project I branded a pop-up creative space and the organisation that ran it, which I called PLAY. From February to March 2020, I held creative workshops, exhibitions and drink & draw events at PLAY, which was situated in a unit in Huddersfield town centre, thanks to Kirklees council. The image shows the logo and one of the custom typefaces I created. The idea for PLAY began in my placement year, my passion to try new creative processes as potential answers to client briefs was not always fulfilled due to tight deadlines and small budgets in industry. I wanted a space where people could come and play. The branding was born from the same idea of playing with new techniques and seeing where they could lead.

Name: Hazal Ozkeles
University/Course: Leeds Arts University Illustration
Description: In this piece, I'm exploring a dreamlike landscape.

Name: Ruby Gardner
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art, Textile Design
Description: Informed by her experiences of road trips, Ruby explores scenery in motion; drawn to the nostalgic sensations of watching the landscape pass by the car window as a distorted blur of colour and form. She considers how the landscape is navigated, how the eye is drawn to signage and road markings; this imagery permeates her designs. During lockdown Ruby has used the structures and yarns she had been developing in the studio to create a digital collection of woven fabric simulations.

Name: Laura Chen
University/Course: Birmingham City University, BA (Hons) Photography
Description: This is an image from my series Killer Queens, for which I have photographed around 40 individuals from Birmingham's (UK) LGBTQ+ and drag community. The colourful portraits celebrate and explore performance and self-expression. The work addresses current issues surrounding identity, sexuality and community spirit, and tells a strong collective story about discovery. I am fascinated by the ways in which drag artists can create endless variations of characters, in the most unique ways possible. They do this by playing with different fabrics, colours, patterns, textures, shapes and forms. With these photographs, I aim to make aware that despite that everyone is born in a specific shape and form, we have the freedom to discover new appearances and attitudes through re- invention. We are never fully formed.

Name: Suzie Cichy
University/Course: MDes Communication Design at Glasgow School of Art
Description:
Through open submissions over the past 18 months people have been sharing their stories, experiences, and images of cyber flashing, which have been retold and represented through explorations across different media. 

The intention of the work was to create discourse around the subject: something that isn’t usually widely discussed, has little research on, yet happens to 41% of British women aged 18-35. Reactions to the project have led me to explore ideas of censorship and the obscene, as well as links between art and pornography. Ultimately it has shown that we still live in a society that is dictated by the male gaze, which decides for us what type of nudity can be deemed ‘acceptable’ and which is still taboo.

Name: Gary Williams
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College - Fashion Technology
Description: I have created a garment inspired by World War II in the form of a steel boned corset. It is intended to look like armor and represents the safety and security felt by women during the time as a result of the men in their lives fighting for their freedoms.

Name: Lauren Waters
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University studying BA (Hons) Fashion Marketing and Branding
Description: Exploring how intelligent technology (AI, robotics, machine learning) makes individuals more creative, leading to a highly creative workforce as technology permeates into more of the workplace.

Name: Toby Edmunds
University/Course: Cardiff metropolitan
Description: This is my major project which focusing on providing a solution to enable greater photography results using a Phone camera in low light environments

Name: Jamie Shannon
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: I am an Illustrator who creates surface patterns for children, utilising traditional material and collage to create my work. This piece focuses on the seaside towns of Cornwall.

Name: Rosa Kusabbi
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University
Description: The whole project was about female punk bands and how they influenced women in music and other creative professions to pursue their dreams. This particular piece focuses on protest and the dr marten boot as it was a symbol for the punk movement.

Name: Zoe Scott
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores
Description: Thread Heads is a video that connects the complicated goings on of many individual minds, to highlight the differences but also the prominence of mental health. A cross section of what might be going on in someones head and how that can change over time. The book is made up of the developments and changes that occurred along the way.

Name: Daniel Randall
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts, Fine Art
Description: This piece originated as a still from the film, 'Coral Ghost', a part of our collaborative film project 'Solidarity', between myself and fellow Fine Art students Emily Turner and Kim Ryan. The film is based on ideas of isolation through the use of a confined, statuesque costume worn by Kim. The stills from the film have become works of art in their own right, and reflect on the current issues we face in this climate. The statuesque pose and vibrant colour of the 'ghost' aims to inspire strength and power in times of isolation and social withdrawal.

Name: Natalie Whitney
University/Course: University of Leeds. - BA Fine Art with Contemporary Cultural theory
Description: ‘Confined behind the cat’s eyes’ is a playful projection installation referencing our current situation, communicating through disembodied heads on screens, staying within the safety guidelines or ‘cat’s eyes’. Also in this time of making with what you have to hand, why not include your cat in your art.

Name: Heather Wilson
University/Course: Cardiff School of Art and Design, Cardiff Met University. Ceramics
Description: Within domestic spaces are narratives of our lives, told by the intertwining relationship between objects and experiences. My objects aim to uncover these quiet moments within the everyday that connect us to the spaces they occupy.

Name: Kristen Wong
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, Graphic Design
Description: In every Chinese household, there has to always at least have this one, probably oddly suspicious-looking, medication or relief that your mother seems to brand as some sort of magical all-cure — but really, what exactly are they and are they legitimately what your mother claims to say it's for? Chinese Witch Brews is a web guide of commercialized traditional Chinese medicine and remedies for the modern generation aiming to extend its relevance, especially for second-generation (and beyond) Chinese immigrants through deeper understanding of what they are.

Name: Megh Jones
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University
Description: Encouraging inclusivity within design and technology classes for children in mainstream education, with additional learning needs. Developing a learning aid to assist in the design making and justify processes when choosing materials.

Name: Kate Muldowney
University/Course: Nottingham Trent MA Animation
Description: My project is focusing on the visual development aspects of an animated film and environmental factors. I developed a script about a Forest Giant who is facing problems with a pollution monster in his Forest. He meets a young boy Gerald, who helps him combat the monster. Gerald also learns that humans need to take better care of the nature around them.

Name: Roo
University/Course: University of Bristol
Description: Roo is a historically inspired jewellery brand with an educational core, which I will launch later this year, post-graduation (& post-virus). My concept is all about making material cultures of the past accessible, and engaging people with the original contexts and creators. All pieces are designed & made by my two hands, and then reproduced in small UK workshops using age-old craft techniques. All of my metals are responsibly sourced, with consideration for our planet, and its people. It's an accessible collection, and it doesn't cost the earth.

Name: Abbie Hughes
University/Course: Leeds Arts University , BA Hons Creative Advertising
Description:
An Adshel created for an Independent Business in Leeds who specialise in crafts and bespoke gifts.
 
Insight: The gifts in-store are so unique, they'll remind you of people you know. 

Big Idea: gifts so personal it's creepy.
 
Anyone receiving a gift from this store will be truly spooked out. As if the gift has come from the fly on the wall or the FBI man listening to you through your phone. The gifts are so unique and personal you'll be creeped out.

Name: Mary-Jean Kingston
University/Course: University of Brighton, Graphic Design
Description: My Grandad is a photographer who enters his work into competitions. I applied his way of working with his competition images to his collection of 700 family photos, creating this series. It was to pay homage to his talent.

Name: Louise Bowker
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and studying Costume design and making
Description: My topic is of swan lake that explores social and environmental issues within the characters costumes. This is how I incorporated a contemporary look along side keeping the traditional story and characters alive ! This specific costume is one of ten designs that was made and is of the character Odile who was inspired by swans and the effects caused from oil pollution.

Name: Saskia Vokes
University/Course: Kingston University
Description: School children across the UK are being disadvantaged due to familial finances. Unable to afford after school sports, some children are left feeling left out. We wanted to design a football that was made by the children, for the children. Giving them an equal opportunity to play - The game is dictated by the group and not by external situation.
Website: No additional platforms as of yet

Name: Aillie Nicholson
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College
Description: This body of work was created to show the migration of disease and the vaccinations which where created. These vaccinations then went onto save the lives of millions of people world-wide. This project shone a light towards scientists who have spent their lives work researching cures for diseases such as Malaria and Small Pox. In addition to these cures I also created a section based on the current affairs of Covid-19.

Name: Hannah Turley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Theatre Design
Description: The image depicts scene 5 of The Libertine, a play for which I designed the set and costumes. It is a restoration era play which I chose to set in a more modern period - loosely the 1980's - to reflect the  rakish and excessive behaviour of the titular character, seen frequently in troubled rock stars of the 80's. The brutalist inspired concrete structures of the set provide an apt setting for the dark and debauched underworld that John Wilmot inhabits.

Name: Chloe Turner
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
Using thermochromic inks to visualise the impact of global warming a poster was screen printed to reveals facts and figures about the growing climate crisis. 

The process of printing the poster was also recorded and
turned into a supporting film.

The aim of the posters is to raise awareness about global warming and climate change.

Name: Angela Boyle
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College HND Fashion Technology
Description: This collection explores using circles or circular shapes and bold colours combining craftsmanship and innovative pattern cutting. Inspired by COS and Creating with Shapes by Usha Doshi.

Name: Lowri Humphreys-Jones
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University. BA Theatre Design
Description: A set and costume design for the play 'The Libertine' by Stephen Jeffreys, which is based on the life of John Wilmot, the 2nd Earl of Rochester. Designed for the Nottingham Playhouse Prize 2020.

Name: Chloe Hunter
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Graphic Design
Description: Mend is a male skincare range which offers overnight sleep masks to restore and fix damaged skin while sleeping requiring little time and effort. The range contains 5 face masks all serving different purposes as well as a hand and a foot mask. They contain CBD oil and focus on calming and de-stressing men as well as encouraging them to invest more time and effort into their skincare.

Name: Brandon O'Rourke
University/Course: National College of Art and Design, Dublin. Illustration.
Description: My main final year project is centred on the apocalypse and the fascination with the end of the world. As one of my outcomes for my final year project I orchestrated a fake satanic cult called The Movement who believe the return of the antichrist and the eventual doomsday he brings is their key to freedom in the afterlife.

Name: Rebecca O'Doherty
University/Course: University of Ulster & Fine Art
Description: My work explores the idea of memory and how that can be distorted by the imagination and storytelling in a dreamlike/fantasy way. I like the idea of the subconscious influencing my work as it is unexpected and not planned

Name: Elaina Soteriou
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University- Graphic Design
Description: ‘Mooney’s Cookies’ is a space themed sugar cookie brand, aimed to give children a sense of feeling like an astronaut by experiencing what they would enjoy as a sweet treat while in space. They are fun picture cookies which also aim to be educational. A variety of fun facts about space and planets can be found on the back of each cookie box.

Name: James Wilson
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, Fashion Textiles HND
Description: My work is a modern take on 60's colour block fashion, bringing the idea of using contrasting colours on a garment whilst keeping it modern through embellishment. My aim was to capture a holiday feel in this sample as my garments were specifically designed for resort wear. The patterns of stitch-work on the sample are very wavy and loose conveying the feeling of being on holiday and being able to let go.

Name: Callum Baxter
University/Course: I'm graduating from The University of Central Lancashire and I have been studying BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: This piece was entered into the 2020 Carmelite Prize for children's book illustration. The competition asked us to illustrate a narrative written by Jeanne Willis.  The story follows a 'Lonely Bird of Paradise' and his pursuit to find a friend. In this scene he sits upon a branch for as he patiently waits for a bird to answer his call.

Name: Thomas Pearson
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Graphic Design
Description: This hypothetical drinks branding project is named Hector & Sylfan Brewing Co. They brew a particular blend of smooth silky stout beer with ground black pepper for a spicy kick. The brand draws on their backgrounds and experiences from childhood to WW2. This hero page shows the bottle designs in all their glory.

Name: Ellen Powley
University/Course: Central Saint Martins, Graphic Communication Design
Description: "The Covid-19 Cookbook: Digesting the Pandemic" is a WIP publication which explores food and cooking as a form of comfort during these unprecedented times. It takes the form of a recipe book-cum-journal, to discuss the the various ways that the pandemic has impacted our relationship with food. It is also an opportunity to document any thoughts and feelings surrounding the current climate, using food as the conversation starter.

Name: Karen Jones
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, BA hons Ceramics
Description:
Artist Statement

There is beauty in the natural world, the texture, colour and formations of land and sea. The colours of the ocean and organic structures of the coral reef, the intricacy of plants, petals and wildflowers can all be captured through clay.
The ever changing seasons  remind us of the natural transformation in nature.

Fired porcelain in particular can appear as if growing in naturally occurring delicate and fragile structures. These multiple hand-formed ceramic shapes recreate the effect of fractals assembled onto organic forms.

Name: Jane Woodside
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Decorative Arts
Description: Bespoke Interior installation prints, that can be Dye sublimation printed onto glass, metal or plastic. Or made into wooden panels with Digitally Printed habotai silk fixed to the wood displaying the print.

Name: Laura Walker
University/Course: Textile Design at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Enhanced Existence is a high-end accessory collection with a focus on colour, tactility and wellbeing. Taking inspiration from organic forms and growth within nature, it aims to improve wellbeing by evoking optimism through the use of a vibrant colour palette and bold, abstract shapes.

Name: Rebecca Jones
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - BA Fine Art
Description: My work is about the relationship between humans and technology. We have created some amazing technologies and so frequently they are used for mediocre tasks or to scam fellow humans. Technology (and subsequently the internet) offers a wealth of fantastic possibilities - yet humans are content to spend their time using these devices in a way that seems inconsequential.

Name: Abi Wakeling
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire- BA Advertising
Description: During the coronavirus people have been using FaceTime more than ever to stay connected. But those who aren’t all that great with technology (shoutout to most grandparents) are trying their best to stay connected. Even if there are a few hiccups.

Name: ella cosham
University/Course: university of brighton, graphic design
Description: A3 risoprinted typography and the body form based on Russell W. Belk’s five part formulation.

Name: Devon Chance
University/Course: York St. John
Description:
Penguin Awards 2020.
A Short History of Nearly Everything.

The book aims to be a fun, relatable and easy to read version of mundane science publications. What is more relatable and easy to understand than objects we all come into contact with, every day, no matter our age?

Name: Sara Szalai
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art, Performance costume
Description: A fresh interpretation of San Exupery's classic 'The Little Prince', using both modern and 18th century fashion elements. This costume is designed for stage for the Queen character. She is dressed in pink to represent her femininity.

Name: ella cosham
University/Course: university of brighton, graphic design
Description: 1 A2 portrait painted with acrylic in the style of pigeon post portraits, a traditional way of communicating before technology was around. The portrait took 54.03 hours to paint and minimised digital usage down 50%.

Name: Holly Moxham
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic Design BA Hons
Description: In response to a sustainability brief, this poster campaign uses the visual of fruit stickers to encourage and provide awareness to students about buying seasonal fruit and vegetables.

Name: Jordan Lucas
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic Design (Illustration)
Description: An abstract scene of unique flower illustrations, representing my love of flowers, textures and bright colours.

Name: Beckie Clarke
University/Course: De Montfort University - Graphic Design (Illustration)
Description: This is an illustration that I submitted to the Loop Open 2 exhibition and it was displayed in the LCB Depot, Leicester, from 4th - 25th of October 2019. For this piece, I drew the linework traditionally, using fine liner pens. I then coloured the illustration digitally.

Name: Owen Mountfield
University/Course: De Montfort University: Graphic Design
Description:
Found sound is an abstract music score designed to be heard through visuals. Taking the concept from the pattern of rhythm and the visuals that come from individual notes. Rather than robots making music, what if we made music for robots?

All shape seen in prints were found in the recycle/scrap pile in a laser cutting lab.

Name: Lauren Mclardy
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores studying Illustration
Description: For my dissertation research I explored the fascinating world of modern British Folk traditions and their growing popularity across the UK.  Community togetherness has never been so important and events such as the Nettle Eating Championships, Tar Barrel Racing and Bog Snorkelling have  given local communities a sense of identity.  My illustrated map of the UK shows many of these weird and wonderful events.

Name: Matthew Webb
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Photography
Description: This image comes from the collection '6 Feet Under', exploring the different ways in which cellars and basements are used in urban areas of Kent and Nottinghamshire. This photograph; 'Bill, 2019.' portrays Bill from Luton in Kent, displaying the use of his basement to store treasured items, and things that he has collected over his life.

Name: Lauren Jefferis
University/Course: Loughborough University- Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: The Poisons of Agatha Christie' is an interactive experience for fans of Agatha Christie's work.  The illustrations tell stories based on her books and the use of poison within them, the most used weapon in her books. As part of a celebration of 100 years since her first published novel, the site will give users insights into the inspiration behind the poisons in the novel and some real life cases which could have influenced Christie.

Name: Ângela Gabriela Nascimento Silva Aires Augusto
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Costume Design and Making (BA)
Description: This image consists of the 10 character designs for my final year degree show, for which I made 2 costumes and worked on for the whole academic year. It's to be a 3D animation Tv Series adaptation of the game Assassins Creed Black Flag. The project is about a group of warriors that revolutionze against control and globalization discrepancies. In search for a land where people are free and equal, culture and tradition is aggrandized and can coexist in symbiosis with mother Nature.
Website: Although it is being finished as we speak I'll leave the link : https://ekothread.wixsite.com/online

Name: Finlay Hamilton-Sardesai
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College, graphic design
Description: My piece is based on the theme of sound and silence, and what it is like for a deaf person to walk through a busy street not being able to hear all the noises made around them.

Name: Drew Montgomery
University/Course: De Montfort University, Illustration & Graphic Design BA Hons
Description: I am passionate about creating art that makes women feel seen and empowered.

Name: Jak McKinley-Good
University/Course: Ravensbourne (Advertising and Brand Design)
Description: Just be decent is a behavioural change campaign that encourages people to be nicer to each other in these uncertain times.

Name: Dain Kim
University/Course: Royal College of Art (Intelligent Mobility)
Description: Prototype 03 : The project starts from the humanity perspective: how does the future mobility express the user-focused value with car exterior design? The project solves this question with ‘premium ROBO sharing’ concept called ‘Prototype 03’. The mobility enhances the user’s experience in 3 independent spaces with ‘big contrast’ design feature.

Name: Kezia Lovell
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: My project is about positivity and spreading positive messages in difficult times. This is one of the pieces I have created as a digital illustration, but I have also embroidered the design too.

Name: Martha Waters
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Costume Design and Making
Description: This is a costume design for my concept of a TV series 'Pink Rabbit'. It tells the story of Judith Kerr and her family's escape from Berlin in the 1930s. The SA character design combines with the tiger from The Tiger Who Came to Tea.

Name: Rosalie Herrera
University/Course: De Montfort, Graphic Design & Illustration
Description: This is a snapshot of a scene from a series of interactive illustrations. You can explore the forest and play with different elements in each scene to discover more about the forest and its inhabitants.  The aim of the project is to provide people stuck inside with a digital source of nature.

Name: Isabell Kaley
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic design
Description: Workwear is described as "heavy-duty clothes for physical or manual work", yet it is worn daily for fashion. Office jobs are at an all time high whilst manual labour professions decrease.  Workwear being worn as fashion is Britain's ghost of real production.

Name: Irene Sweeney
University/Course: Ulster University , Fine Art
Description: Catharsis and the enigmatic presence that nuanced trauma emits characterise my practice. By cultivating a conversation with the audience that feels ‘one-to- one’, I endeavour to create a wider understanding of trauma’s effect in the subconscious. My aim is to create artworks which have an affective quality, questioning what is ‘depicted’ through an intro and extrospective lens.

Name: Rebecca Ritchie-Smith
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College.                   HND in Fashion Technology and Manufacture with Costume
Description: Corset inspired by snow covered fir trees

Name: Jemma Chatwin
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: The symbol in the centre is one that was created for football supporters, to come together through the love of the sport, with the aim to try and minimise acts of hooliganism. The placement on the England flag is relevant, to enhance the idea of unity and all representing under the same country.

Name: XIAOMIN MAO
University/Course: the University of Edinburgh （major in Illustration）
Description: This piece of work is one of the project about memories of childhood. The concept of that is “Searching for The Missing Dreams” which address several themes of memory, personal experience，gender and things like the human condition in relationship to our nature.

Name: Shuting Zhang
University/Course: Central Saint Martins/Fine Art
Description: It called : "Falling Awake". Negative emotion, Depression, Insomnia which are harmful to people's health. Green part is mold represent  how negative emotions grows in daily lives, which is fast and poisonous, but people sometimes will ignore it.

Name: Shannon Greer
University/Course: Ulster University, Belfast, Graphic Design & Illustration
Description: 75% percent of disabled people say that they have difficulties meeting sexual partners due to their disability and the huge misconception around sex being ‘just penetration’. However, 58% of disabled people admitted to being more inventive in the bedroom due to the restrictions they face from their disability, so I named these unique and inventive forms of pleasure a ‘Sexability’. Audiences who download the app can answer a few questions to uncover their unique Sexabilility which is designed as a ‘blue badge’. They can then use it as a conversation starter on dating apps or wear it as a symbol of empowerment. Instead of a blue disability badge defining what you can’t do with sex, the aim of a blue Sexability badge is to get people talking about what you can do.

Name: Corinne Snell
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, Textile Design
Description:
Titled 'Botanical Utopia' this work is part of a collection of printed textiles for womens fashion. Featuring  statement designs which capture the infinite beauty of the natural world through exuberant, colourful prints. The collection is inspired by the appeal of escaping to a botanical utopia in times of uncertainty. Evoking a sense of positivity and 
optimism by creating the feeling of summertime in bloom.

Name: Rebecca Orr
University/Course: Ulster University - Fine Art
Description:
At its base level, my work is about soil. Connection to nature is inherent to my emotional well-being and so my work is a reflection of this relationship. What I see and experience in nature is translated into drawings and prints whilst a more physical connection is kept through ink making and sculpture. I work in a process based way allowing random accidents to occur and open own new avenues of exploration.
Of most personal significance to me is the making of hikaru dorodango. These polished spheres of mud originate from Japan, their formation is slow but simple, repetitive and meditative. The transformation of humble soil into polished sphere seems unreal. Working with soil allows me the direct connection with nature I desire even when not directly outdoors.

Name: Brandon Dempsey
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone, Fine Art
Description:
Using paint, pastel and collage, I Intentionally weave thoughts and conversations amongst crudely drawn imagery. Depicting the destructive ethos of graffiti and post-punk, from my application of paint to the choice of material. Painting over boards and found objects interpreted as less sacred like household furniture.
I am interested in developing my visual vocabulary, appropriating imagery from punk fanzines, Slam skateboarding magazines, matchbook boxes to yogurt cartons. Remixing references from residual marks left after graffiti removal, street signage, architectural motifs and counterculture artists like Raymond Pettibon, Jamie Reid and Wes Wilson.
Working primarily in paint, I create accumulative neo-expressionist scenes with an aim to capture angst and mess. Embracing mistakes and imperfection to communicate a feeling over aesthetic values.

Name: Niamh Rock
University/Course: Brunel University London
Description: Urban Air the portable air purifier for commuters

Name: Laura Chu
University/Course: Loughborough University
Description: Urbanarium is an interactive digital experience designed to spark joy in commuters at train stations. The experience immerses the users in an underwater aquarium world at tube stations and allows them to own several fish through an app. This innovative and captivating experience would keep the target audience entertained while waiting for their train, allow them to give back to society by donating to our charities, encourage human interaction and improve commuters' mindfulness.

Name: Matthew Price
University/Course: University of Edinburgh - ECA
Description: Many people feel uncomfortable on public transport and avoid making contact or talking to their fellow passengers. Scared of rejection or just that it would be ‘weird’. Chatty Coaches is a no pressure to talk environment on trains. By just being there you are showing you are willing to talk, for 3 hours or just a short chat depending who you meet. This will break down the stigma and normalise talking, while putting a smile on each of the passengers’ faces after having a connection with a real person, not a screen.

Name: Madeleine Burt
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, MA Illustration
Description: I am an illustrator whose work explores different approaches to representing the metaphysical world. My MA main project is a graphic novel that comments on the creative process, memory and different metaphysical states. This image is one of the more accessible, standalone images from the book and is to do with starling murmurations, which are used throughout the work as a metaphor for the gradual, lyrical, sometimes unpredictable, but beautiful formation of creative thought.

Name: Nicola Lammin
University/Course: Birmingham City University
Description: These Illustrations are the visuals for a brand experience based in Italy.

Name: Lee, Yi Ting
University/Course: Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp. Graphic Design
Description: A Story book called "A Stone, A Man and A Crow". This picture is for the stone chapter.

Name: Clareth Anyanwu
University/Course: Kingston University
Description: What if choosing the right woman was as easy as “Click & Collect”?   What I want to do is express to you my customers/audience how easy it is to get lost in the initial phase of seeing people. I want to enlighten you to the fact if you haven't already realised the dominance of the male gaze in our mainstream media. I want to bring forth the unrealistic expectations we put on women to fit a stereotype of the perfect women. Judging every detail down to the eye colour.  When you use the website you will find that after creating your own perfect woman that, that person could never truly exist. Taking parts from different women to create one. Media has warped our minds(including women) into believing that we can truly have a perfect woman without any imperfections and to not settle for anything less. Yes, we should be free to not settle but at what cost to our society?

Name: Phoebe St Leger
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Fashion Knitwear Design and Knitted Textiles BA
Description: My collection imagines what our clothing would look like if it accurately reflects ourselves. I have envisioned, through a retro futuristic lens, with 1980s undertones, what it would be like if a computer tried to simulate these clothes for us. It would be conflicting, glitching, confusing and bizarre.

Name: Alisha Daniels
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University
Description: This project was about looking into providing more suitable upper body protective gear to freestyle riders, with the solution being a lightweight, breathable, flexible, discrete upper body protective unit that provides full coverage.

Name: Matthew Mcgill
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College HND Textiles
Description: My chosen theme for my project was “Graffiti”. I looked at how we can take this Art and turn it into Wearable Art. I wanted to show people how something we so often perceive to be vandalism and disruptive to an area can be turned around and looked at form a different aspect. This piece I designed portrays  “Graffiti” from my research I did and shows various aspects of my photos I took to create this final piece.

Name: Lucy May Robinson
University/Course: De Montfort University, Photography and Video (Ba)
Description:
A film adaptation on the history of Lady Jane Grey, the 9 days Queen of England.
Pictured is John Dudley (Duke of Northumberland), who played a role in getting Jane on the throne for his own political gain.
The work looks at the importance of fictional representation, when remembering historic events.

Name: Catriona Phillips
University/Course: University of Edinburgh - Illustration
Description: These flying flamingos are from a project about badly designed birds. Birds with huge beaks, extravagant plumage, and gangly legs. Birds that look like they shouldn't be able to fly at all. There is something very joyous in their sheer improbability and I wanted to celebrate that.

Name: Eve Gordon
University/Course: University of Ulster - Textile Art, Design and Fashion
Description: Six Inches of Terror is a materialization of the physical and visual anxiety, discomfort and pain I experienced during and following being raped. This materialization was a therapeutic process to make trauma something I have control over, rather than something that controls me.

Name: Agata Tomaszek
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic Design
Description: The project was to brand the waterside area in Leicester which goes through the regentrification process. It highlights its industrial character, also through using traditional letterpress typography.

Name: Jasmine Nichols
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (HONS) Photography
Description:
The Social Distance Door-Shoot'
is a project created out of the social lockdown that has encased the country at the current time. Whilst shooting the project, the outcome has allowed a build in the community, social interactions with others that would never have crossed paths before and a level of security and connectiveness from the isolation of one’s own home. 
The project is about producing a scene where the pets are the star; representing the pets to be the kings and queens of the scene, through the relationship we share with them.

Name: Lydia Rylance Murdoch
University/Course: Edinburgh Napier University, Creative Advertising MSc
Description:
One of a series of posters to make people who could benefit from Al-Anon UK Family Groups aware of them, their helpline and the meetings they run. Al-Anon provide a safe and judgement free space for anyone who is or has been affected by someone’s drinking. 

These posters will be placed in locations where people are more likely to be alone and introspective e.g. on the commute, in bathrooms and changing rooms.

Name: Emily Williams
University/Course: Loughborough University, Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: This work is part of a two in one comic book that I wrote and illustrated myself, exploring the theme of The Rashomon Effect, or the use of different perspectives in storytelling. My two comics "Pig in a Poke" and "The Fiddle Game" tell the story of the same con, as perceived by the conmen and the mark, with seemingly different outcomes.

Name: Florence Ingrey
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: The digital, narcissistic identity. The work intends to depict the artificial shield and disconnect between humankind and nature. Seeking a state of authenticity.
Website: Can supply upon request! (In more than one place)

Name: Alice Clarke
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University Fine Art BA(Hons)
Description:
Within Alice Clarke’s practice, she explores the processes within the creation of artworks and how they are affected by past experiences. Clarke explores how her materials, especially clay, interact with herself, their surrounding space and the viewer. Clarke manipulates and models clay directly, leaving evidence of the artist’s hand within the finished work.  

Clarke is fascinated by the different textures, colours and patterns within the work she produces and how they are able to allow the viewer to have an insight into her mind and her creative process. Clarke’s ceramic works exert a strong tactile feeling, therefore allowing the viewer to have a strong visual insight into how the work has been created.

Clarke uses personal memories of the sea to establish a connection with the viewer. Although Clarke’s work is heavily influenced by these memories and experiences, this is not what the artwork is necessarily focused on. These hints towards influence should be present within the artwork but still leave enough space for the viewer to have their own individual experience with Clarke’s work.

Name: Rachel Owen
University/Course: Ulster University,  Belfast BA Hons Fine Art painting
Description: This piece explores civil engineering and how we could take a more sustainable approach to construction by adopting a new approach to road verge management to allow wildflowers to grow.  This painting is about making people notice nature more and appreciating the importance it has on our lives.

Name: Donatienne Borione
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, BA (hons) Illustration
Description: I made this personal piece to celebrate love in all its forms, in parallel with the IAmLabel exhibition in Plymouth, UK. The bold colours I used reflect the pride and joy I find in my sexuality.

Name: Gemma Tavner
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: I've looked into medieval illustration and the depiction of women in medieval society. They had these hand made books called illuminated manuscripts, mostly written and illustrated by men but some by women too. They would write about morals and illustrate social and political issues, but often in very weird surreal ways like using mythical creatures. The manuscripts basically were a way for people to document societal opinions and stereotypes.I've made correlations between the manuscripts and the way we use social media to document our opinions in the 21st century, with an overall focus on women. The quotes on my posters are things I've heard women say on the bus.

Name: Ella Magiera
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University- Costume Design and Making BA
Description: This costume was created for the Foreign Princess in the opera Rusalka. Inspiration was taken from the human impact on the natural world as a result of their greed for cheap disposal electronic items.

Name: Charlotte Crawford
University/Course: Photography with Video at the University of Ulster.
Description: ‘Eye of the Beholder’ is a body of work documenting the marks and traces present within the urban environments of various city locations across Europe. This series of 35mm images highlights the details which often go unnoticed in daily life, encouraging the viewer to consider the mundane as a beautiful subject. By approaching these observations from an aesthetic point of view, I use the shapes, lines and colour within the landscape to visually connect one image to the next, highlighting moments of beauty within our everyday surroundings.

Name: Ioannis Andreoglou
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, University of Dundee
Description:
Dundee is the only Unesco city of Design in U.K. and Dundonians are proud of their city (and their accent). Now they will be proud of their bikes too. 

OOR bikes is not a common bike share. It has a mission to reduce emissions by discovering the fun, design and culture in Dundee. Discover dundee and reward yourself. By every mile you cycle you will get an 1% off to local attractions and places of interest.

The visual identity and tone of voice was inspired by classic comic books and video-games as part of Dundee’s design culture.

Name: Sophie Gottlieb
University/Course: University of Leeds, Fine At
Description: My work is about my struggle with expressing my Jewish identity and encouraging those who don't have any knowledge about it to understand it, versus the inner turmoil I experience of 'explaining away' my identity.

Name: Hello, I'm Simona Hodonova
University/Course: Robert Gordon University, Communication Design BA (Hons)
Description:
This illustration was used as a part of a stationery set that I designed for competition and as a part of my course work. This collection is intended to make people look at the bright side of life, even if it gives them lemons. The idea of getting a bunch of lemons can be turned into a positive thing and my designs are trying to show just that. Humour is the main ingredient for making that lemonade taste sweeter.

The stationary set includes designs for postcards, notecards, notebooks, wrapping paper and a gift bag. These products can be a great reminder of being grateful and staying calm during the days when you just want to squeeze that lemon in someone's face.

Name: Jose Garcia Oliva
University/Course: Royal College of Art – Visual Communication
Description: The uncertainty of the Cup-and-ball (Balero) keeps people playing. It gives you hope to achieve it, and at the same time, plays with frustration. This traditional children's toy portraits the timeless social-political tension scenario globally. The constant duality between failure and victory, between uncertainty and hope.

Name: Aayushi Vadgama
University/Course: Graphic Design at the Arts University Bournemouth
Description: Herb & Fruits brings you the very first CBD Infused jam, as it puts nature in a jar. Infusing CBD oil with fresh fruits, creates and new and exciting edge to this well-known condiment. This combination balances relaxing tones with the sweet and boldness that is jam.

Name: Jess Sciubba
University/Course: Bath Spa, Graphic Communications
Description: This artwork is the front cover to my meditation themed publication 'ATMA'.  It is a visual response to the practice. This piece individually was inspired by the vibrations through the body whilst  practicing body scanning. 'Atma' is Sanskrit, translating to inner-self; soul or spirit. The publication is minimally designed and it's simplicity is a reminder that by taking time for ourselves and by being kind to our mind & body, it's always possible to stay calm and keep tranquility - even through these strange times during quarantine.

Name: Matilda Honeyford
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA (Hons) Textiles Design
Description: Based on the Scandinavian / Danish concept of Hygge, this piece represents being at peace surrounded by what brings us joy and comfort.

Name: James Adekitan
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Graphic Design
Description:
It is a (conceptual) edible vinyl record part of a typography-first campaign, seeking to voice tough social conditions that confront young black working-class in recent times – catering to the streetwise Shoreditch community to understand/taste the value brought by treating everyone equally. 

Through the primary use of blackberries and conscious hip-hop music, the deliciously crafted campaign serves two playful tastes complimenting each other about social inequality.

Name: Shamsa
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Photography BA
Description: A focus on British Muslim Women, their relationship with their faith, heritage, and culture through photography and hand embroidery. My work creates a new perspective, giving an insight to the beauty of the religion through portraits of the Muslim women that make up the diversity of Britain. This body of work is set out to be educational through the creativity of reality, but also for other women like myself to connect and relate to, giving them a sense of belonging to a community that accepts them.

Name: Harriet Gardiner
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, MA Graphic Design
Description: My project focuses on the expectations around a woman's appearance, in particular, being asked to smile. Smiling upon request can leave you feeling as though you've lost your autonomy, but is that better than coming across as cold and unlikable?

Name: K Blick
University/Course: MA Fine Art, Central Saint Matins, UAL
Description:
My practice is an allegory that creates a paradoxical mythology between humans and animals in the Baroque form. It is expressed through distortion, discontinuity and dynamic movement.

My paradoxical allegory is my fairy tale imagination of what the world would be like, under the assumption that Adam and Eve did not eat apples, but dinosaurs did. For example, an idea such as how the world could be different if humans did not exist as the dominant predators in the modern world, but rather, if information were freely exchanged between species and knowledge was transmitted naturally. On the other hand, it is my absurdist imagination regarding how the world would have been different if the dinosaurs, who were the rulers of the earth a long time ago, had continued to live.

Chapter I: The Guilty Pleasure  / 
A Conversation between Dinosaur and Eve in the Garden of Eden, Total 150 cm X 230 cm, Each panel 113 cm X 70.5 cm, Porcelain on the wooden board, Wooden table, Ceramic pigment, Cloth, Plaster, 2020

Name: Karina Nepali
University/Course: University o Dundee, Jewellery and Metal Design
Description:
My graduate collection is an exploration of how gender stereotypes are attached to physical objects. I centre my designs around dividing the signet ring, an heirloom traditionally worn by men. I aim to break down concepts of masculinity and femininity within my jewellery and create gender-neutral wearables. 

I incorporate a mixture of digital tools and handmade elements within my practice to create rings that interlock precisely.

Name: Esme Holland
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University Knitwear design and knitted textiles
Description: The need to engage girls in sport has never been more urgent. Teenage girls are facing more mental health problems and report being less confident, less happy and increasingly concerned with their appearance. Girls’ health and wellbeing is deteriorating, these negative issues will have a significant impact on them and the women they will become. Sport can be a powerful force to support girls on their journey to being happy, healthy and self-assured young women. My collection aims to challenge our thinking, to create solutions that will have a long-lasting and sustainable impact on girls’ lives.

Name: Jamie Leigh Totten
University/Course: Graphic Design & Illustration, University of Ulster
Description:
The design task at hand was to develop an A2 poster which invites the audience to enter into a conversation or interaction relating to power. The point is not to make a statement but to encourage thought and invite conversation. 


In essence, this design is asking how exactly are you going to feed the design student?

How creative can you be with your budget? are you feeling boujee or cautious?  can you handle the responsibility and competition?
…is there even a chance of loss?

Name: Aidan Wyldbore
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: The process of photography is cathartic for myself, ‘For The First Time’ is the result of an exploration between self and environment. Slowing down my approach to image making, I consider my subject and it's relationship in a body of work that is truly personal.

Name: Kimberley Laura Walker
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth, Ba (Hons) Illustration
Description: Whilst spending more time than ever imagined alone during lock-down, surrounding ourselves with plants and nature has never been more important. Nature inspires. It can push us forwards when we feel stationary. It promotes an endless stream of creativity.

Name: Alberto Sanchez
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Animation
Description: It depics hell.

Name: Si-zuo Chen
University/Course: UAL, Central Saint Martins; Ma Fine Art
Description: ‘Purple carve’ is a watercolor painting featuring gender less creature. And animation ‘Murmur’ present how this creature performs.

Name: Sizuo Chen
University/Course: UAL, Central Saint Martins; MA Fine Art
Description: ‘Ivory Ball’ is a watercolor paintings featuring a gender less creature, and animation ‘No’(https://vimeo.com/418864361 ) is a prove that this creature is alive in cyborg status, only use memes to perform.

Name: Ella Kenyon
University/Course: Kingston University, Graphic Design
Description:
For me, people are the most interesting subject to photograph as I believe so much can be read from the way someone interacts with the space and people around them.
However, in this digital age, we tend to only show perfectly posed versions of ourselves online. What I aim to capture is the moment people are at ease, in order to show a true reflection of who that person really is. I see it as documentation of those around me and, simultaneously, something for us to look back on in the future.

Name: Nina-Mae Bartron
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth. Ba (Hons) Textiles
Description: My FMP is called Dystopian Couture, and it's about a dystopian future where plants mutate and take over, causing an imbalance in nature. Inspired from my dissertation on the impacts that fast fashion has on the environment.

Name: Stefania Ruggeri
University/Course: Shillington Education - Graphic Design
Description: The Nonna Vanda packaging design is a story/concept based design that required the creation of the story, the product/brand name, a logo, associated graphics and imagery and all additional packaging/product content that would enable the product to be sold through a retail outlet.

Name: lily dean
University/Course: CSM FINE ART
Description: I started with the idea of Medusa turning herself to stone by her own reflection. As I researched the story further, I was drawn to the visual impact of the headless figure of Medusa. I also wanted to expand my sculptures to a full-size figure. I was very interested in Medusa, a bronze sculpture made by Benvenuto Cellini 1545–1554. I wanted to eliminate it but also subvert the misogyny and violence in it so Medusa is reclaiming her own power of her severed head, The idea of reflection plays an important part of the myth and I have cultivated it in my art pieces to create a sense of interaction, I replaced the face with a mirror - The idea is this makes it an interactive/performative element because you as the audience become the artwork.
