In the title I'm playing with what is perceived to be “real'' and what is ‘stone’ or sculpt. What is alive and what is dead. Though the casting process, I destroyed or killed the original ( clay version) and yet, it came back to me in a brilliant ghostly white as though it were an apparition. Both a reference to the Greek myth, where Medusa was beheaded, only to lose the life of her body whilst her head continued to be used as a weapon, but also a reference to a digital age, where because of VR and modern advancements both in art-making, but also in a wider context of technology -it is becoming only the brain that is used, the is body obsolete.

Name: Nanna Reseke
University/Course: Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp, master in Graphic Design
Description: In the making of my final project, I had two main goals. One was to reflect on and rethink my practice in order to build a foundation for its future, the other was to look for tactics that could help me navigate in this world which seems so excessively rich in (visual) information and possibilities. The title, Everything Is Interesting And Anything Is Possible, refers to  exactly this, this excess and abundance. Having realized the bountiful existences of interesting things and possibilities, has been about as terrifying as it has been motivating. As much as it might inspire or fuel any creation, it calls for a strategy, a direction, a narrowing down of things and for making choices. This has been the leading agenda for this project. By re-approaching my practice with critical thinking I have explored the possibilities as well as boundaries, which exist within the field of Graphic Design. This has called for a thorough exploration of design tools, of visual language, and the methods through which we approach both of these...

Name: Megan Hamilton
University/Course: Ulster University and BA [Hons] Ceramics, Jewellery and Silversmithing
Description:
I am a “sweet tooth silversmith” creating jewellery to help heal the world’s cavities. One area is single use plastics and overall plastic pollution. To combat this catastrophic effect on our environment, focusing on the ocean landscape, I developed an innovative bioplastic, utilising sweets. This material is completely biodegradable yet strong and versatile. Along with inspiration from the plastic crisis, I was inspired to create a circular design collection based on the idea of lost jewellery found lying on the ground. Being biodegradable, if my jewellery were to fall on the ground it would completely breakdown and return back into the earth, thus is assisting in contributing to solving the pollution problem.

Along with the “Sweet Bioplastic” I created, I was conscious of the material choices within the pieces. For the items that incorporated metal I used Eco-Silver, which is made from 100% recycled and scrap silver products thus environmentally friendly. By combining science and craftsmanship I wanted to create items to help, not hinder the world around us through the use and reuse of sustainable materials.

Name: Martha Waters
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University- Costume Design and Making
Description: These are two costumes I made for my concept of a TV series called 'Pink Rabbit'. 'Pink Rabbit' tells the story of Judith Kerr and her family escaping Nazi Germany in the 1930s. It combines imagery from Bauhaus and The Tiger Who Came to Tea.

Name: Jenni Cornall
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores, Illustration
Description:
Poppy and the Pangolin, a 32 page picture book.

Poppy wishes she was like her mum, saving animals from bad people. So one day, she goes on an adventure to find her own to save, but what does she find along the way? A picture book about an unusual friendship and discovery of animals we might not know much about.

Name: Leo Winter
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Animation
Description: This is my 4 minute thesis film, it's about two rivals being assigned a mission to rescue a prince from a tower. Chaos and shenanigans ensures. You can find animations of the film here https://leowinteranimation.weebly.com/

Name: Laura-Ana Ciobanu
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University BA Decorative Arts
Description: The unique smell of flowers is linked with emotions, and most of the times, the scents tell a story and become memories. The main ingredients in the process of making perfume are grasses, flowers and spices; that is why I want to create a series of patterns people can interact with, smell and associate with different feelings.

Name: Diane taylor
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College
Description: I want to tell the story behind the photographs of these people. With this in mind the muse of the look is more of a feeling and garments celebrate diversity, genderless fashion and reflects self indivuality.

Name: Penelope Clayton
University/Course: Hereford College of Arts. BA(hons) Illustration.
Description: I have been exploring what walking means to people. This image is one of the pages I'm making into a book about walking as part of my final major project.

Name: Kirsten Cronie
University/Course: DJCAD, Textile Design
Description: Coorie, the Scottish art of deriving comfort, wellbeing, and energy from wild landscapes and convivial interiors. As a Scottish designer, I hope to bring this sense of coorie, and the cosiness, warmth and security it entails, to the textiles world. I am using hand dyed, gradiented merino and mohair to create a range of textiles which captures the beautifully magnificent wildness that is the Scottish Highlands.

Name: Julie Atkinson
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: The Menopause and the sensational feeling of drowning within its clutches.
Website: I can give you more of my work. but I am still trying to design a website . But if u email me i can of course send you more work .
Instagram: lucindiathroughthelookinglass ( but my work on there is just things I see while walking my dog . I do not put any of my documentary work on there .i is just things that I see

Name: Hannah Kirkland
University/Course: Graphic Design at the University of Salford
Description: This work is an outcome from a competition brief set by HSBC. The brief was to create an illustration to be displayed in an airport that would excite travellers.

Name: Abigail Jones
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University studying BA(Hons) Artist Designer: Maker
Description: My practice focuses on the juxtaposition between forms and materials following architectural inspiration. Pattern and precision are often present within my work, the angular forms challenge the simplicity of the materials, and the relationship held between them. I work with a variety of materials that hold industrial qualities, mostly for their aesthetic and structural elements. Bold, clean architecture holds a presence within an environment, within my work I portray this through the design and composition of the forms.

Name: Sophie Nurse
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University- Artist Designer: Maker
Description: This piece is a multifunctional folding screen and plant storage shelf. It can be used either as a standard folding screen or as a shelving unit by folding three hinged pieces of one screen panel down to create shelves. The materials used are oak re-claimed oak and rattan, both chosen for their sustainibiity. Caning, the technique used to weave the flat rattan cane into a sheet, is also on the Heritage Crafts red list of endangered crafts, with no new furniture being made using the technique in the UK.  I want to keep this age-old technique alive in my work.

Name: Rachel Owen
University/Course: Ulster University, Belfast BA Hons Fine Art Painting
Description: This piece is called 9 Oxo 2 Decenoic.  My work is predominantly about the impact humans have on the environment and their lack of care for nature.  This piece highlights the working relationship between a queen bee and her colony within a productive beehive and how this relates to our work ethic and relationships in society.

Name: Tyso Steer
University/Course: University of Bristol, studying Msci Management with Innovation
Description: This is TIMERISE, an innovative product designed to help families unplug from phones by incentivising disuse.

Name: Emily
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton, Visual Communication
Description: This is a poster series using quotes relating to interstellar travel, the quotes show positive and negative ideas. They show different viewpoints, the people excited about the future and space travel, and people who believe it may be bad to leave earth. The idea is for the viewer to see both sides and decide if we should abandon earth or try to save it.

Name: Lottie Tugwell
University/Course: Plymouth University
Description: A mechanical flying Chaffinch , part of my Bird World collection.

Name: Georgie Gibbons
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan university, studying BA(hons) artist designer maker
Description: My practice focuses on functional homeware which explores the ideals of everyday mundane objects. My work places its central value on the human-object relationship within the home, and how we can form personal connections with objects. This is of specific significance when it comes to the objects we use for eating as it is one of our most intimate relationships with an object.  I use a variety of hand-building techniques combined with different mould making methods, with my hands being the most important tool for me as a maker. Gestural making allows me to work intuitively, using such an approach enables the realised form to come from sensory thought and material knowledge rather than a preconceived idea. This enables the forms to be embodiments of my thinking through making.

Name: Issy Sinclair & Lauren Stanton
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire. BA (Hons) Advertising.
Description: Music often puts our feelings into words better than we can. With many people struggling to know how to support a friend in need, this poster shows how sending a song could help start a conversation.

Name: Sandra McWilliams
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College HND Textiles
Description: I was exploring sustainability by restructuring and redesigning clothes by taking them apart and making them beautiful and precious with sashiko embroidery.

Name: Sophie Elliott
University/Course: Ulster University Belfast
Description: The O-App is a mobile app developed to open the conversation on woman's sexual health and wellness. Pleasure is a core reason why many of us have sex, making it a driving factor in all parts of our sexuality. The O-App developed a visual language  to work along side the app messaging system and on their roll-outs.

Name: Thomas Jones
University/Course: Chester University and from Product Design
Description: This project combines digital manufacturing with the authenticity of hand-crafted componentry in order to capture the “mark of the maker”. This enables the product to be replicated in batch quantities whilst maintaining a specific uniqueness to each piece. Supplying the owner with a piece of bespoke furniture utilising the capabilities of digital design to achieve high levels of accuracy and consistency, but complemented with the irregularities, passion and uniqueness of craftsmanship.

Name: Siobhan Armitage
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University Textile Design
Description: A collection of printed fabrics and wallpapers aimed at the high end contract interior market. The collection has the focus of creating a self-care space which is uplifting and calming, providing a much needed escape from hectic and busy environments we experience in our day to day lives. The collection draws on our innate bond and appreciation of nature to reconnecting us with our surroundings, creating a restorative and refreshing setting.

Name: Olivia Marshall
University/Course: Glasgow Clyde College HND Graphic Design
Description: The project was to create a unique design to advertise a hypothetical event which would be called 'Night At The Museum' for Kelvin Grove Museum in Glasgow. I took my inspiration of all the magical and amazing artefacts that could be found inside the museum.

Name: Ruth
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description:
Urban Futurism
 
On the surface, my project is simply a playful exploration on the endless possibilities the futuristic aesthetic provides for streetwear design. However, my work is embedded with a deeper yearning to reimagine the black identity. For so long black people have not been represented enough in the creative media and when represented, they are often portrayed in an unrealistic, monolithic light that dulls the perceived black experience.
My aim is to use my project to ignite our society’s imagination with much more positive and diverse images of Afrocentricity in the fashion and creative industries.

Name: Josh
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University
Description: a promotional poster for an animated tv show inspired by family tv shows growing up and other animated features that one would usually watch coming home from school

Name: Lauren Stanton & Issy Sinclair
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire. BA (Hons) Advertising
Description: During these unprecedented times the online pub-less quiz has become the default social activity. We created a poster to celebrate people staying safe and staying at home through socialising online.

Name: Nadia Hodges
University/Course: Fashion Design (Ba) at Nottingham Trent University
Description: This is a lineup of half of my final collection. It is inspired by the strength of women who wore suits in the Victorian times and the patterns of damage on the original photographs of these.

Name: Tabitha Miller
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University BA Photography
Description: Death is the 13th card of a Tarot Deck, exploring photography and tarot and their roles together. Death, as a card, is representative of a new beginning, a transformation, which is this distorted rose, showing growth in transformation.

Name: Vicki Sismore
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: A series of editorials about iconic women and their life stories to educate, inspire and empower young women and girls to fulfil their best potential.

Name: Ella Mackenzie
University/Course: Glasgow School Of Art
Description:
My sculptural practice stems from a curiosity of material and form explored through the making of vessels. Working with ceramics, I create the work by hand to illustrate the body’s relationship to object through the making process, I do this with the aim to understand emotive language that goes into the making process, as it reflects human movement and experience.  I am interested in the value of art by examining how objectification and the male gaze seek to reduce women to mere vessels, to exist for and be consumed by males for their pleasure.
 
The tube like vessels in my work question the hierarchy of mimesis which argues that all art is a re-presentation of nature and how a piece of artwork that is imitating a physical form makes it just as valuable as its counterpart.

Name: Katie Fogden
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, Graphic Design
Description: A conceptual digital platform dedicated to providing users with the tools to begin an easy and informed transition to using sustainable period products. The platform primarily focuses on introducing users to products and brands suited to their individual period needs, established within a 14-question quiz.

Name: Rhianna Stamps
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Textile Design BA
Description: My collection is called AURA, inspired by childhood memories exploring the countryside on family holidays. It is aimed at reducing anxiety by creating an area of calm within the home, a retreat from the stresses of everyday life.

Name: elianor oudjedi
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art
Description: Video maker with a dreamlike world, I combine the tools of cinema, theater and performing arts. My work focuses on the power of storytelling and resilience. I show stories of resilience through docu-fiction.

Name: Jasmine Bramble
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Photography
Description: My project is called Muse and is an exploration of how woman have been oppressed through dominant artistic practices. I have taken images of women by white male canonical photographers and have reinterpreted them using my own image. The aim is to resist social structures that are reproduced in the history of art such as the construct of the male 'genius', as they exist to control women. By naming my images after the women in the original photographs I am reclaiming a space for them in the history of photography.

Name: Tyler Royle
University/Course: De Montfort University, Graphic design and Illustration
Description: For my major negotiated project, I created and branded a company called 'Home Sauces', that offers recipes for condiments. With these recipe cards, families could personalise their meals with something they have made and re-use old jars and containers instead of buying new plastic bottles of branded condiments.

Name: Athenais Duriez
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Design Marketing (Creative and Cultural Industries)
Description: As part of one of my third-year projects I created a campaign for a hypothetical flea and tick treatment brand, Little Pricks. The concept was focused on my character, Spike, the balloon dog. He would do different things, then sit down and have a really good itch, leading him to pop. The art direction is inspired by Jeff Koons’ Balloon dog.

Name: kabo cheung
University/Course: De montfort university - graphic design and illustration
Description: branding for a start up bubble tea cafe

Name: Dexter Stokes-Mellor
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art
Description: I listen to Blue Monday every Monday is about club culture, about music and it's impact upon our everyday lives. It's about repetition, about growth and change.

Name: Craig Stanley
University/Course: University Of Portsmouth
Description: A New typeface family based around a rotational set of movements applied to a calligraphy pen

Name: Saskia Robinson
University/Course: The Glasgow School of Art, Sculpture and Environmental Art
Description: Saskia Robinson is a sculptor who lives and works in Scotland with a special interest in sculpting within neoclassical tradition.  A recent graduate of the Glasgow School of Art (2015 -2020) Their work focuses primarily on figurative and portrait sculpture, statues and low reliefs in clay and plaster.

Name: Sid
University/Course: University of Southampton, BA Games Design and Art
Description: We are currently developing Maive, a gorgeous, heartfelt tale about a red panda with a magic storybook returning to her home island after years away.

Name: Megan Mizon
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (HONS) Photography
Description: Exploring how the dangerous exposure of chemicals in dyes, specifically used to dye clothes, can be challenged by dyeing fabrics with natural foods found within the household instead.

Name: Sophie Walker
University/Course: Brighton University and Illustration BA (hons)
Description: Exploring a new album concept for Black Sands by Bonobo. Layering my Chinese brush paintings onto photo-collages made digitally.

Name: Ally Powell
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University studying Decorative Arts
Description:
Ally Powell is a ceramicist investigating the boundaries of porcelain through continual material innovation using traditional making skills. Through the development of specialist slip casting techniques, her pieces are an exploration into colour and translucency within ceramics.  

Ally’s work translates expressive marks into an aerial landscape of bold sculptural lighting in her signature tangled style, capturing a moment of spontaneity between maker and material. Within her practice, Ally prioritises form and function equally, to provide consumers with pieces of fine sculpture that embed themselves within daily life, bringing moments of joy to the user.

Name: Emily
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University Animation
Description:
This is a still of a scene from my short animated film 'Hope's Room'. 
'Hope's Room' is a short family film that highlights the impact that the earth and wildlife have on children's imaginations. The audience is taken on a geographical journey that emphasises the paramount importance of preserving our wildlife for our Grandchildren and future generations.

Name: Cara Wheeldon
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: ‘The Anthropocene’. Is visualised as a term loosely employed to depict the rising age of man in our augmenting society. Holding the idea that humanities impact on the planet has been so profound in such a short amount of time that it has therefore become necessary to remove ourselves from the current epoch and instead, plunging ourselves into the time of the Anthropocene, literally giving human existence its own recognised separation. My final project aims to expand upon this notion of the visualisation of the Anthropocene through less literal imagery. Staging photographs to purposely represent damage inflicted by our species. Intending to explore the diverse and deaerating world of which we live and expanding upon the notion mentioned in ‘Art in the Anthropocene’ claiming that: “Art is the vehicle of aesthetic, and central to thinking with and feeling through the Anthropocene”

Name: Gabriela Sokolowska
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts, Textile Design
Description: Renewable Tradition is the story about my traditional Polish Cracovian costume, which I used to wear during church and national celebrations in my childhood. Project focuses on the abundance of the colour in the waistcoat, skirt and head piece, heavy decorated with satin embroidery and beaded work inspired by flowers. The final outcome is a woven shawl created on the 8 shafts hand loom with hand dyed noble yarns- wool and corded silk. The idea is to create a unique, one-off product, which will last for longer than today’s disposable items and by purchasing it, the client will support craft people like me.

Name: Okocha Obasi
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: A poster manifesto which brings awareness to ways we should use and design technology so that it is more inclusive and caring towards all social groups.

Name: Kezie Todd
University/Course: Ulster University
Description:
The Arcadia Report is an immersive murder mystery experience, transforming your city into an escape room.

Travel to real world locations, unlock clues, and uncover the secrets of Arcadia as you delve into corrupted records of a failed startup with murderous consequences.

Name: Katie Stephenson
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - BA Hons Theatre Design
Description: This is a model box image for The Libertine by Stephen Jeffreys. It is a show about John Wilcot the Earl of Rochester. The show follows Rochester's downfall and demise. This image shows Scene 7. In this pivotal scene in a moment of rage Rochester breaks Charles II's sundial. Proclaiming 'Kings and Kingdoms tumble down and so shall thou!'

Name: Sofia Cianciulli
University/Course: MA Fine Art at UAL Central Saint Martins
Description: #digitalFeelings is an Instagram performance designed to explore the relationship between the female body and social media. The shadow behind the screen invites users to comment and define the limits of body objectivity, while the format and accessibility of the performance itself opens up a debate on our almost preferred forms of online communication and the social anxiety that derives from it.

Name: Shona Speres
University/Course: Falmouth University BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: A photography series with the format of prints. Investigating the inner mental state of individuals who suffer from anxiety. Shot against the backdrop of domesticity, taken where people are supposed to feel secure and safe, these images capture anxiety’s effects on the brain in a slightly morbid yet truthful way. Anxiety does not exist as a typical or customary entity, it is organised as a random collection of disguised unnecessary feelings that damage an individual’s own perception of themselves. It acts as an invisible obstacle affecting a person, even from the comfort of their own home.

Name: Victoria Smith
University/Course: Manchester School of Art, Photography
Description: In ‘Dust From The Darkroom’ Victoria Smith develops her ongoing research of employing dust within photographic-practice. Utilising over a decades worth of dust collected from her Universities darkroom enlargers, Smith revisits the space to create photograms; a method of fixing images through direct contact on sensitised surfaces. A portrait of the darkroom emerges by fixing and reducing the transience of the redundant, and mundane traces left by the inhabitants of the space, to a more cherished photographic-object.

Name: Keri Breen
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, studying Fashion Marketing and Branding
Description: Inspired by the current gender-neutral trend, Anything Goes was created as a retail space free of judgement where consumers feel empowered to break gender stereotypes and express their true and authentic selves through fashion.

Name: Megan Joy Barclay
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic Design
Description: This isn't my most researched, conceptual or valuable piece of work. But it is the one that encompasses everything that my practice sets out to be: thoughtful towards people and the earths resources, and communicating in a way that doesn't discriminate – inviting anyone to join the mission too.

Name: Nathan Barnard
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Ceramics Ba (Hons)
Description:
A most common ceramic object used on a daily basis and yet, rarely recognised as produced through ceramic processes, is the sink. The bathroom as a whole is a place in which we can feel both vulnerable and safe, the one room in the house that has a lock, where it is necessary to be naked; it demands a level of intimacy. 
This vulnerability can be explored through the sensorial capacity of clay, using cracking, peeling slip to evoke a shiver, a sense of unravelling, dissolving and cleansing so that alongside the objects function, our awareness of the activity of sensorial perception is brought to the fore.

Name: Dan Jackson
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Graphic Design
Description:
Star*Crossed is a double-sided poetry publication created in response to a science fiction research project. It is designed to be used hundreds of years in the future, when humans have colonised Mars. 
With 2 distinct sides, one collecting love poems evocative of Earth, and the other evocative of Mars, this poetry collection is for those whose loved one is on the other planet.

Name: june hill
University/Course: ulster university fine art
Description: my work explores architecture and how we interact with it, space, self awareness and self inspection in relation to others, by looking at self and others from a different view point.

Name: Sophie Gwilt
University/Course: The University of Central Lancashire
Description: This project was for Booths the North west supermarket. The brief they gave us was to create a double page spread showing booths products in a fresh and local way, taken in a photography studio.

Name: Violet Grace Wilson
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh
Description:
Approach
​
What?

A short film designed to encourage more households to eat together featuring 15 households from across the UK who regularly eat meals together.

 

How? 

I asked the households to answer four questions on why and how they eat together and what they’d say to other households to also eat together.

​

Why?

Sustainability isn’t just about the environment, it’s also about keeping to a balanced and healthy lifestyle. Sometimes we just need to slow down, take it all in, and savour the hours we have together.

Name: Adele Wilson
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, Textile Design
Description:
Nature meets technology in my degree show project, 'Psychedelic Savanna', a concept created for young girls textiles. 
Inspired by the growing awareness of endangered wild animals, yet exploring how the digital world is increasingly influencing all areas of life. Artificial colours are used to reimagine classic themes surrounding safari wildlife, creating fake realities that offer a sense of escapism during these difficult times.

This piece is one of my favourites from the collection, I think it would look lovely as a bedding print!

Name: Harry Hitchcock
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (Hons) Photography
Description: The intimate trust of friendship is at the heart of this project which captures Mental Health experiences of depression and anxiety. Tomorrow is a New Day focusses on a few close friends of the photographer whom are situated in the comfort of their own bedrooms. The surrounding of the bedroom can be viewed as a safe space, and how we decorate this escape can be all the more important in how we decorate ourselves.

Name: Rosie Wells
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Fashion Accessory Design
Description: My collection is inspired by different interpretations of armour, in buildings, nature and for protection. My research developed into the theme of exoskeletal, and looking at different areas of protection and barriers. Looking further into different elements of protection I researched into traditional knotting to make fenders to protect boats, and traditional leather braiding techniques. I took inspiration from gun and knife holsters to design accessory pieces on the body, as I wanted the pieces in my collection to act like a layer of protection to the wearer. From this research I gathered shapes, patterns and a colour pallet to take forward into my own designs. selecting complimentary neutral coloured leathers in my final collection, alongside a natural coloured rope for decorative details. I used orange edge paint to colour the ends of my rope to add a bold accent to my line up. This image is a materials mood board for my final collection.

Name: Olivia Mitchell
University/Course: Bath Spa University Graphic Communications
Description: Risograph style print for my project about aliens and Avebury.

Name: Eleanor McNally
University/Course: University of South Wales
Description: This project was a campaign for Amazon to help customers stay connected during lockdown. The project focuses on the premise of being able to share gifts with friends and loved ones no matter where they are

Name: Catie Porter
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Ba Hons Decorative Arts
Description: I create bespoke botanical wallpapers inspired by Victorian Floriography, the language of flowers. All flowers are hand drawn and composed into repeats myself.

Name: Harriet Exton
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Fashion Marketing and Branding
Description: It is a proposed business plan for an over 50's bespoke travel planning service

Name: Annabel Dowd
University/Course: UCLan Advertising
Description: A double page spread, promoting Booth's fresh produce through original photography.

Name: Mariana Leal
University/Course: I am graduating from the University of the Arts London and I studied Animation.
Description: This is a frame from my graduation film produced in a team of animators collaborating with sound students. Our film explores the idea of having our deepest problems and character flaws come out with our sweat when the heat rises. Our two main characters are forced to face their problems in a surrealist journey, while the sauna that they are stuck in shrinks and morphs according to their emotional states. Our film uses 2D animation as well as Riso printed environments.

Name: Kim Warren
University/Course: BA Photography Nottingham Trent University
Description: My project explores the use of personal items collected together and presented in a still life scene to represent the identity of who someone is. We use items to signal to ourselves, and others, who we want to be and where we want to belong. And long after we’re gone, they become our legacy. Some might even say our essence lives on in what once we made or owned.

Name: Clair
University/Course: Glasgow university hairdressing
Description: This is a sam villa creation of hair up   using a bubble technique.

Name: Sophie Gwilt & Annabel Dowd
University/Course: The University of Central Lancashire
Description: Every 3 seconds someone in the world develops dementia. More than 82% of people in the UK living with dementia are cared for by ‘informal carers’ who often have little or no training, and have no funding. Research has found that music therapy significantly reduces levels of stress and agitation as well as helping to recall lost memories. Using Spotify’s huge music library, we will re-position the brand to be a music therapy support service to help with dementia, and fight the disease through the love of music. These print adverts are to target informal carers letting them know about the service, whilst also with two of the OOH adverts creating awareness too!

Name: Lara Dent
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Decorative Arts
Description: Lara Dent is best known for her exploration of a wide range of mixed media, from textiles through to ceramics, to create large three-dimensional installations. Manipulating varying materials and their characteristics, with strong influences from the natural world, textural contrasts are deeply explored.   The resulting dreamy displays are targeted not only at interactive gallery spaces, where they will actively engage the viewer, but also at shop windows, to reach wider audiences and commercial viability; through their unique handcrafted experience they should cause the customer to forget negative notions of consumerism and focus on the wonder of the store. The displays also lend themselves to one off individual hand-crafted pieces to be sold as standalone pieces for the home. Through these multiple, different ways of exhibiting Lara will appeal to a vast range of audiences through magical child-like imagination.

Name: Abi Loquellano
University/Course: Birmingham City University
Description:
Referencing life, Abi documents how people use space in urban locations and utilises this to build the narrative in her work through poster design. Due to the nature of her work and the themes explored, the current crisis has allowed her to create works that depict how our current society mirrors an Orwellian reality. 

Her "Lo-Fi modern-retro poster design" is inspired by her surroundings and online culture.

Name: Michael Peters
University/Course: I study Graphic Design at Sheffield Hallam University
Description: Inspired my love for golf, I set out to create a campaign which got more young people active within the sport. Surveys I created showed that too many people didn't have enough time to play golf.So I created 14 Hole Golf. A kit box full of all the equipment and signage you need to turn your course into a quicker and easier 14 hole round.

Name: Chantelle G
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Belizean' is a personal project,  exploring dual nationality, culture heritage, family and archives. While considering maternal bond with perspective through different view points, in order to make a connection with identity.

Name: Lauren marsden
University/Course: Hull school of Art & Design - Illustration
Description: Cats of the wild is a self initiated project, with the final result being an educational children’s book - navigating two characters across the wild to seek out wildcats. The work is the complete storyboard panel layout. I created the character designs, compostions, storytelling and illustrations throughout

Name: Lewis Webster
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University & Graphic Design
Description: PUZZLE PLAY!'Creating a TV Motion Ident for ITV's creative initiative 'ITV Creates', inspired by ITV and it's channel contents, hinting towards play, fun as well as drama.

Name: Gillian McCormick
University/Course: Fashion Technology HND, Glasgow Clyde College
Description: My brief was to create a collection that would be suitable for a collaberation with the well known fashion brand 'Cos.' Using an earthy green colour palette and a triangle as my inspiration i created interesting structure and sihouttes by cutting, folding and sewing triangles in unique ways.

Name: Harry Wakefield
University/Course: Manchester School of Art
Description:
During this brief I was asked to create something that showed where my inspiration derives from. I have always loved making objects and looking at buildings that for some may be  ‘unattractive’.  Being heavily inspired by post war modernism, this typeface is inspired by some of my favourite brutalist buildings in London, my home.

'BRUTAL LONDON' follows a strict grid system in the form of harsh blocks and thin crevasses where windows would typically be found in these
buildings.

Name: Isobel Fiske
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth - BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description:
Faraway Fantasia celebrates the exciting relationship between migration and music through a vibrant brand and campaign for a new event.

The screenprinted pattern using the beautiful Arabic script demonstrates the dynamic nature of migration and how it is a part of everyone's lives in some definition.

Name: Helena Sõõro
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA (Hons) Photography
Description:
The importance of music in embracing feelings has been a widely discussed topic in various art forms, most frequently in films. This makes it a commonly thought idea: couples have “their” song. Some kind of a melody that defines them as a whole. 
My work is about various couples close to me and their relationship to music. I have a series of images of couples in different statuses, whether they're married and have children, are engaged, have moved in together, are a new relationship or have broken up/divorced. I have held conversations with them to find out their special song or a melody and if music plays a significant role in their lives or not. 
My project is called "Armastussongs" which is a hybrid word from Estonian and English language, simply meaning „love songs”, representing the couples from both cultures. Music crosses cultures, making it a potential universal language between people.

Name: Hannah Leabon
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Graphic Design
Description: A children's book on emotional intelligence - learning how to handle strong emotions through informative pages, activities in and out of the book and craft tutorials in the book.

Name: Brogan Smith
University/Course: Nottingham Trent university, Decorative Arts.
Description: Brogan Smith's hand coiled ceramic sculptures are a recollection of the culture, nature and people she met on her travels in Australia, New Zealand and Indonesia. Brogan explores fluidity and growth in her ceramics, as the large-scale form develop from the ground and transform into playful landscapes.

Name: Harriet
University/Course: University of the Arts London and BA Fine Art Photography
Description: This picture is part of my ongoing documentary project which seeks to make sense of the world of psychics, mediums and spirituality in general through photographs. This particular photograph shows crystals balancing on the edge of a table - which I think really speaks to how I've felt about this world all throughout the project, of course I am open minded and part of me wants to believe it is real and true, but I am also struggling with balancing being open minded and my own beliefs on the subject.

Name: Bryony Rogers
University/Course: University of Portsmouth (BA)Hons Graphic Design
Description: I designed an identity for a fashion accessories company using Monotype typefaces. Accent are a luxury and sustainable fashion boutique sourcing eco - friendly materials. I used different diacritical marks to denote the various countries where the materials are sourced from to make each product. I produced a selection of products, promotional materials, packaging, a lookbook and animations. The slogan 'Parlez vous la mode' reflects the international sourcing of the brand.

Name: Lauren McNeice
University/Course: Ulster University  BA (Hons) Photography with Video
Description: For this series, “Reconnect” portals are presented to show healing within a challenging world.  This photographic series is about recovery, focusing on the element of perspective. Connecting closely with the parable of the 'Blind Men and the Elephant'; reiterating the psychology of perspective.

Name: Georgia
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, studying Textile Design
Description: The trend forecast Power Play, is an energetic future trend forecast for 2021 that explores the relationship between sports aesthetic and the physical movement of fabrics. Aims to use the Power of Play through a strong drive on design responsibility; of designing to reconnect consumers with their clothing and products through emotional durable design, using a sports aesthetic visual.  Advanced yarn choice and high-tech knitted manufacturing, exploring circular knitted construction technology for ergonomic functional knits, architectonic padding and structured mobility advancing comfort and performance for the urban environment.

Name: Jordan Slater-Hall
University/Course: York St John University, Graphic Design
Description: Branding identity for a 'Think Beyond High-school' (TBH) Project that would allow informational access to students who are in-between collage and university. The aesthetics are designs to create an atmosphere of safety and reasurance to reflect that the brand is a students friend.

Name: Ellie Niblock
University/Course: Central Saint Martins, MA Fine Art
Description: The Birth Suit is a life size cast that explores the relationship between materiality and the body. It represents a shedded skin from the imagined year 3024. The skin protects the owner in unknown worlds, stretching with body movements and shielding them from the atmosphere.

Name: Ben Whitehurst
University/Course: University of Chester, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description:
This piece was created as part of a campaign which explored the question: Can music be associated with products and services?

My intention's for the project were to pay homage to the yellow pages and show that the art of music and printed matter is still truly alive.

The outcome saw the creation of a business directory like no other and illustrates what it would look like if the world's most notable bands and artists took alternative career directions.

Name: Ellen Gordon
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Animation BA
Description: A short animated film: Polaris. When Ursa Minor falls out of the sky, he must embark on an adventure to get back home - with the help of a new friend.

Name: Rowan Sophie Calvert
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description:
Kinetic Linearity is an AW womenswear collection, encompassing resortwear with a hint of sporty aesthetic. The collection is inspired by the movement and repetition of linear structures and the negative space that is in turn created by them. 

Taking inspiration from these elements, the collection is designed with layered garments expressing a level of sophistication and playfulness. With a focus on creating negative space through layering different silhouettes. Each outfit will consist of several garments exposing other layers and the body through cut outs and transparency, replicated lines and shapes that are complimentary of conceptual research.

With my technical knitting skills, there will be a huge variety of interesting and unique fabrics, along with garment silhouette that has been informed from primary and secondary research and developed through draping on the stand and body.

Name: Kate Warrington
University/Course: Ba(Hons) Fashion Knitwear Design & Knitted Textiles at Nottingham Trent University
Description: Specialising in Knitwear Design, ‘Hikari 523’ embodies the dramatic, terraced landscapes of Northern Vietnam, and contrasts the contours of the land with the ‘patchwork’ style architecture nestled within it. The collection has a multi layered aesthetic, incorporating rich colours, textures and stitches. The garments shown reflect the structural qualities witnessed within the architecture, with colour composition informed by the weathered and layered surface qualities of metals and wood. The collection endeavours to recreate the feeling of being encompassed by the immersive landscape.

Name: Sophie Sinnott
University/Course: Kingston School of Art Graphic Design
Description: Boy to Boy is a photographic series celebrating male friendships from an intimate stand point, with an objective to encourage emotional vulnerability within such friendships. It is time for emotional connect, affection and honesty between boys to be represented. Boys, because the example needs to be set for the boys who are working out how to become men.

Name: Jua O’Kane
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, BA Hons Illustration
Description: I’m an illustrator and comic artist. My graduate project is a pitch packet for a psychological horror graphic novel about a non-binary model whose body begins to shift to match the perceptions of onlookers. I’m inspired by colour, fashion and things which are simultaneously beautiful and grotesque.

Name: Goi Shinyee
University/Course: Cambridge School of Visual and Performing Arts, Graphics and Illustrations
Description: Sequential images/ a series of illustration about food waste issues, where the leftover food delivered to poorer people in an imaginative way.

Name: Sophie Sinnott
University/Course: Kingston School of Art Graphic Design
Description: Boy To Boy is a photographic series celebrating male friendships from an intimate stand point, with an objective to encourage emotional vulnerability within such friendships. It is time for emotional connect, affection and honesty between boys to be represented. Boys, because the example needs to be set for the boys who are working out how to become men.

Name: Sophie Sinnott
University/Course: Kingston University Graphic Design
Description: Boy to Boy is a photographic series celebrating male friendships from an intimate stand point, with an objective to encourage emotional vulnerability within such friendships. It is time for emotional connect, affection and honesty between boys to be represented. Boys, because the example needs to be set for the boys who are working out how to become men.

Name: Anna Page
University/Course: Nottingham Trent, Decorative Arts
Description: My work is driven by my passion to raise awareness of coral bleaching happening across the world. My work is tactile, beautiful and educational. It evokes strong feelings of responsibility and melancholy whilst living as beautiful installation art. My final collection will be an installation of 300 unique corals which can be displayed together or in isolation. This photo shows a few of my sample pieces displayed together to give an impression of how my final collection will look.

Name: Oskar Walin
University/Course: Manchester School of Art
Description: This project was made in support of the Save Ryebank Fields campaign. Ryebank is a plot of land owned by my university that they now want to sell to property devopers. Each of the trees represent a tree at risk at Ryebank and I got staff and students to help me assemble them and sign the petition. The trees are made out of recycled greyboard and screenprinted with existing petitions.

Name: Vicky Toma
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, studying Textile Design BA (Hons).
Description: IDENTITY is a collection working with Punk and Street Art influences to create an expressive and exciting collection. With a focus on mental well-being through the use of clothing for self-expression, it is a safe space for people to express themselves through their fashion choices.

Name: Loui Hewett
University/Course: Falmouth University BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: Illustration for Front cover book. 'In 1876, Abraham 'Abe' Barrow is contacted by his dying father to come back to his hometown in Bravuc, Romania, to finalise his will. What he encounters in his hometown are dangerous shadows from his past that reveal the sinister connection with the people of Bravuc and the long lost children abducted by the Pied Piper from Hamelin in 1284' Re-imagining of the classic legend 'The Pied Piper of Hamelin'.

Name: Michaela Winter
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Fashion Communication and Promotion
Description: Brain Dump is a student space for female students to connect, grow, create and network in a comfortable space away from the pressures of the online world and this is the cafe provided within the space

Name: Katie Upton-Roddy
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Artist, Designer: Maker
Description: In a world of limited resources, I feel it is crucial to consider the impact that our making processes will have on the environment. My chandelier design is made using a waste by-product of sheep farming and as a result is a completely biodegradable wool-based material. Sheep’s wool currently has a very low demand and farmers often end up sending it to landfill. My work creates a second life for the low value material, resulting in a high value product, which is environmentally friendly. The forms of my lighting also reflects our environment as they are derived from naturally weathered rocks from the welsh coast.

Name: Megan Barker
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University - BA (Hons) Artist; Designer Maker
Description: My body of work explores stacking and deconstructed forms with an emphasis upon interactivity and sharing between communities. The stacked forms not only allows for an element of tactility alongside a need for handling, but provides a new way of storing, transporting and interacting with tableware.

Name: Sophie
University/Course: Kingston University Graphic Design
Description: Private View is a photographic series providing insight into the isolated lives we are now living worldwide, due to Covid-19. Revealing our private views from our windows looking out, as well as our personal experiences, thoughts, and doubts at this time. A communal look at isolation.

Name: Richard calow
University/Course: Nottingham Trent
Description: Using intermediate alternative processes to explore the ambiguity caused by the presence of culture and nature with space.

Name: Alice Riley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent
Description: ‘Urban Jungle’ is a collection designed to illustrate an urban environment in a sustainable way, now focusing on upcycling elements of woven garments or off-cut fabrics into an innovative combination of fabric structures. As well as regenerating industrial materials such as rubber and plastic cording not only depicting the matt, shiny and waterproof surface qualities within the concept, but creating a new fabric purpose for garments or accessories. The contrast is not only found within the overall surface qualities but also through a play on silhouette combining fluidity and structure together, giving a collection focus on structural drape.

Name: Beth O'Boyle
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts / (BA) Hons  Fashion Communication and Promotion
Description:
Overview of project:

My final year project, 'BE MORE', is a marketing campaign imagined for the British Fashion Council. It aims to build a community of emerging designers and fashion creatives, and provide a platform for conversations around ethics, sustainability and attitudes in fashion. BE MORE stemmed from my desire to see change within the fashion industry and is a call to action for those who wish to do the same, and have their voices heard.
  
[Please credit: Photography . Ed Tervit / Creative Direction . Beth O'Boyle / MUA . Abi Mcbroom / Models . Wahiba Kafi/ Grace Morley/ Seth Milne]

Name: Elenor Hintz
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, BA Hons Decorative Art
Description: My initial inspiration came from reading a book of Greek Mythology. The interwoven narratives of the character and the diverse and sometimes illogical plots of the myths sparked my interest and after further investigation I was hooked. Visiting the British museum it was evident how rich ancient Greek culture was and how deeply mythology influenced people and was woven inseparably into their perception of reality this was expressed in various ways including craft.

Name: Goi Shinyee
University/Course: Cambridge School of Visual and Performing Arts, Graphics and Illustrations
Description: A civic engagement campaign about vehicles issues in the uk, to alerting people be considerate and 'leave space' during parking and driving in public.

Name: Hannah Daniel
University/Course: Illustration at Cambridge School of Art
Description: An illustration inspired by Oliver Sack's book 'The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat'. Focussing on the chapter 'A passage to India'. This image is based on the quote 'she would not lose consciousness, but she would look (and feel) 'dreamy'.

Name: Marc Dalla-Riva
University/Course: Shillington School of Graphic Design, Graphic Design
Description:
Apex predators are crucial for the biodiversity of our native forests. Introducing predators such as wolves and pine martins can help redress the balance and allow our forests to flourish.
I ran a campaign for the charity Trees for Life to dispel the myth that wolves are big, bad and scary.  By helping restore natural equilibrium, wolves will help our forests thrive and allow future generations to enjoy.

Who's afraid of the BIG BAD WOLF....not me!

Name: Alice Riley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: ‘Urban Jungle’ is a collection designed to illustrate an urban environment in a sustainable way, now focusing on upcycling elements of woven garments or off-cut fabrics into an innovative combination of fabric structures. As well as regenerating industrial materials such as rubber and plastic cording not only depicting the matt, shiny and waterproof surface qualities within the concept, but creating a new fabric purpose for garments or accessories. The contrast is not only found within the overall surface qualities but also through a play on silhouette combining fluidity and structure together, giving a collection focus on structural drape.

Name: Aaron Furman
University/Course: School of communication arts 2.0 – Advertising
Description: I have tried to reposition Savlon as the go-to brand for cuts and scrapes as it's proven to help reduce scarring. I feel this gave me a creative license to express the fearless sentiment. This encapsulates the feeling of going for that jump, dive, run, and pushing yourself beyond your perceived ability.  In the comfort that Savlon will heal my wounds.

Name: Imogen Crossland
University/Course: BA Hons Illustration University of Brighton
Description: This piece is from a project exploring the Italian's response to Covid-19 Quarantine

Name: Cindy Kurniawan
University/Course: Raffles Design Institute - Visual Communication Design
Description:
SPLIT \| Interactive Title Sequence

SPLIT is a 2016 American psychological-thriller movie by M. Night Shyamalan, which follows a man suffering from identity disorder, with 24 personalities identified. SPLIT heavily explores the nature of the distorted mind, on how an individual’s thought and action could be contradictive due to the conflict of many personalities.

Experimental is the new approach, exploring interactivity and pushing the boundaries away from the conventional method. This project allows the audience to experience the intense yet complex mind of the main character. There are 2 versions available, both interactive and conventional for the audience to explore the potential of this experimental approach. The title sequence is a glimpse of how these personalities intertwine with the real world as portrayed by M. Night Shamalan.

Name: Lee Van Camp
University/Course: I study a master in Art, Design and Image in an autonomous context at Sint Lucas Antwerp.
Description:
Self Defense Society:

Because Lee's name and appearance do not match the prevailing Western expectations, Lee faces challenges every day. Although "100% Belgian", his origin has been questioned all his life. In order to avoid comments, questions and/or uncomfortable situations, Lee felt obliged to adjust his appearance for a long time, be it consciously or unconsciously. Lee often feels like he is in a movie or a performance, because of the banal and downright rude reproaches he has heard over time. Here, Lee portrays faces that he often experiences in public of Western people.

One could argue that Lee admires and obsesses over the self and society, to compensate for the reproachful messages he received.

Name: Erin roche-winson
University/Course: University East London
Description: Erin's work captures the jurney of her experience beeing a female boxing in the male run environment. The solo gloves on the floor depicts the isolating feeling that can come beeing it that situation.

Name: Denny
University/Course: Teesside University, Graphic Design
Description: City Branding for Medan, Indonesia. A long overdue rebranding for the city of Medan. It is the fourth largest city in Indonesia but yet almost non-existent on the international tourism map due to lack of initiatives from the city council. This project aims to introduce and attract visitors either local and international to visit Medan.

Name: Heather Rashbrook
University/Course: Graphic Design at Leeds Arts University
Description: These are a selection of cards from a full deck of tarot cards which have been designed for children ages 8 - 12., the deck features a custom type face as well as original illustrations. The imagery references Ancient Babylon as it is the birthplace of astrology as well as symbols from the zodiacs and uses a colour palette inspired by healing crystals to encompass other astrological aspects. The deck has been designed so that it can be used as a game, as it was originally designed to be used for, or alternatively to read the cards and potentially predict the future.

Name: Klaus Mann
University/Course: Ravensbourne
Description: This is the cover to the magazine I have created.  YNGSTR features young artists and showcases how these artists spread optimism in this increasingly pessimistic world

Name: Marieke Evans
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone, College of Art and Design, Dundee. I am graduating in Interior and Environmental Design
Description: ‘Ashore’ is an intercultural community hub in an abandoned public Edwardian baths which celebrates cultural diversity by bringing people of different ethnic and age groups together through providing skill and story sharing, food, workshops, education and performance. My project aims to challenge the negative connotations of immigration within the most culturally diverse area of Scotland and an area of urban deprivation by encouraging conversation on their journeys and heritage. A narrative of sail and sea crossings is used to influence the design. As well as this metaphor fitting the context and nature of the bathhouse, crossing seas is a shared experience of those who have migrated to Glasgow. People who could previously not imagine belonging together, may now discover their stories are not so different after all. Finally, the narrative aims to honour the bravery of refugees who have crossed dangerous seas.

Name: Jen Liu
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art Illustration MFA
Description:
Farewell— Impressions of Edinburgh
Due to the COVID-19, the city has been placed on lockdown. Although I may not be able to see this lively scene again before I leave, I hope the city will be as vigorous as in the past.

Name: Peter Phobia
University/Course: School Of Visual Arts, MFA Illustration As Visual Essay
Description:
Inspired by Peter Phobia’s teenage years as a skateboarder, Balance and Kickflips reflects on a creative mind-set about freedom, friendship and adrenaline. Exploring the city’s concrete obstacles with friends, the series depicts a romantic idea of a community based on shared passion.

Skateboarding has given Peter chances to connect with people regardless of their origin, social status, age and gender. It led up to a career in illustration and showed him being creative has the power to break barriers and push boundaries.

Name: Olga Motema
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Textile Design
Description: Vibrant Geometrics is a contemporary high end print collection for womenswear fashion and accessories. The collection is a fusion of vibrant, crisp shapes and textures, interlocking and overlapping to form a faceted pattern made up of abstract interpretations of natural forms and nature’s underrated objects. The collection’s vibrant and energetic colour palette is inspired by African, Dutch WAX print material infusing it’s exciting and edgy aesthetic to the collection.

Name: Trena Hollands
University/Course: University of Edinburgh, MFA Illustration
Description: Daydreams of a haunting, preternatural landscape and a house that calls to the curious adventurer...

Name: Hannah Bryce
University/Course: Griffith University, studying a Bachelor of Graphic and Communication Design
Description: This is a cover page spread from an A5 booklet I am designing honouring and encouraging Australian Aboriginal teenagers to travel outside their remote communities and pursue further education. The booklet records the stories of three aboriginal teenagers who have done this for others to be inspired by. The bee and the flower in aboriginal culture metaphorically refers to the acquiring of knowledge. I used natural textures to reference native Australian land.

Name: Aleksandra Legiec
University/Course: Bath Spa University, BA (Hons) Graphic Communication
Description: These illustrations is a part of my project which raises the awareness of body shaming. Each illustration is created out of thousands of dots drawn by hand.

Name: Anete Bihanova
University/Course: University for the Creative Arts and Graphic Design
Description: My work is a visual representation of Dante's journey through Paradise / Heaven.  It was heavily inspired by the Voyager Golden Record, which was sent out in space by NASA. Through my work I tried to find a way which would allow me to communicate Dante's journey to extraterrestrials.  Each symbol symbolises a different stage of the pilgrimage.

Name: Sarah Cantor
University/Course: University of Florida - Graphic Design
Description: Based on my interpretation of the album, Church of Scars is about a cyclical relationship that's toxic at its core, but impossible to stay away from. The album tells a story of someone who fights to understand their own worth and stand up to the person who keeps putting them down. In the end, it seems like Bishop Briggs learns how to be strong on her own, but she falls right back into old patterns. My goal for this redesign was to capture the energy and emotions of Bishop Briggs through bold photography and a cohesive visual system. The album packaging includes a double-sided vinyl, a laser cut sleeve, and a lyric book complete with commentary from the artist herself.

Name: Henry Marcel White
University/Course: Loughborough University, Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: As one of my final year design projects I branded Spotlight Sounds, an East London based youth music label and artist development programme. Within this project I created a visual identity including album artwork, responsive logo, apparel design, AR Instagram filter and more. See the full project here: https://www.behance.net/gallery/90028559/Spotlight-Sounds-Visual-Identity

Name: Rachel Kolb
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth - BA (Hons) Commercial Photography
Description: Hung up' is a piece that celebrates the female relationship with the telephone. Inspired by the "Hello girls" who worked for the British GPO manning the switchboards for decades in order to connect the world, even during the most trying of times such as the second world war. I set out to commemorate their efforts and to make a feminine, glamourous 60s styled image to reflect this.

Name: Beth Cockcroft
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan University
Description: I decided to centre my final project initially on mental health/wellbeing, and ended up focussing on how our relationship with inanimate objects can provide reassurance and comfort. A lot of us form sentimental or intimate bonds with our things, and I wanted to explore how perhaps this could ease feelings of anxiety/stress; e.g. comfort objects, sentimental objects, how some of us find ourselves talking to our things

Name: Alice Wortley
University/Course: Leeds Art University
Description: This family of typefaces is inspired by three different common dream scenarios. It is an expressionist approach at emoting the feelings caused by the individual dreams through letterforms.

Name: Kevin Rooi
University/Course: Academy Minerva, Design
Description: "Typomento" (Type + Papiamento= Typomento) by taking my native language Papiamento and the goal to try to make it visually understandable for everyone. It was also a way to present where I come from and my culture because I believe that where you come from influences how you think, create, and live.

Name: Cavan Rigby
University/Course: BA (Hons) Graphic Communication, Bath Spa University
Description: A still from a website landing animation, promoting a conceptual amateur radio system designed to bring people together through music, evading the limiting circles and cliques of new/social media.

Name: Laura Taylor
University/Course: Chelsea College of Art, Textile Design
Description: Normally, I would have been creating large scale ceramic pieces, around 1-2m in height for my final project. Because this is not possible, I have had to visualise the colours of shapes of my pots and this is a selection of them. I would have hoped to have create huge versions of these, hopefully one day I will be able to.

Name: Mary-Anne Calora
University/Course: University of the Arts and Advertising
Description: Print ad for a maximalist makeup brand, showing diversity within makeup and advertising, race and gender

Name: Ali
University/Course: Loughborough University, Visual Communication
Description: After contemplating the current pandemic I decided to draw humans, animals, insects and plants as one collective form of consciousness, using both digital and traditional skills.

Name: Aya Galgani
University/Course: Otis College of Art & Design, Communication Arts emphasis Graphic Design
Description:
Eight Million Gods in LA is a 10-signature book exploring a more contemporary and Western existence of 八百万の神 (Yao Yorozu No Kami), the Japanese belief that there are an infinite amount of spirits/energy attached to all things, even inanimate objects. ‘Eight Million Gods’ is the direct translation, where 8 symbolizes infinity. I interviewed and collected items from eight Japanese Americans in their 20s (including myself) living in Los Angeles. 

Using this concept as context, Eight Million Gods in LA visually conveys the emotional and nostalgic value attached to the eight individuals’ objects and pieces of ephemera. Cyanotype sun prints and vector image traces help show these objects in a way that is removed from their given function and abstracted in form.

Name: Ernest Wereko
University/Course: Falmouth University - Graphic Design
Description: Poster work for a student portfolio review (Falmouth University+Design Museum). The visual idea is based on the concept of reveal from a Graphic Design context.

Name: Mackenzie Miller
University/Course: University of San Francisco, Major: Design, Minor:Fine Art/Social Justice
Description: War on Warming chronicles the events of the national mobilization towards climate justice beginning in the year 2024. After an iceberg, roughly the size of Belgium, broke off from Antarctica, irreversible waves were sent around the world that forever changed the way we collectively live our lives. This project highlights the speculative aftermath of this event and the societal shift in mindset, values, and possibilities for the future of mankind. In a digitally housed archive, this piece offers original remixed images, downloadable media, and interactive documents to capture the authenticity of this time period during the race to fight the common enemy of global warming. The site exhibits key moments of this movement, such as powerful protest graphics and informative lifestyle pamphlets, all through a futuristic lens. With credible and creative solutions, the goal is to persuade the audience in believing the realistic nature of an alternate vision for the future and what we can do to make it happen. To view the live site, please visit www.thewaronwarming.com

Name: Beth Davies
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, BA Illustration
Description: Island Paradise is a Sleepwear collection inspired by an idyllic Island surrounded by the Sea. The collection's message is subversive, as it tells the story of an Island Utopia but the design also hints towards darker themes of oil and plastic pollution and it's effect on sealife.

Name: Toby Michael Shepherd
University/Course: Falmouth University. Graphic Design.
Description: The Sonosynthesiser is a hand-held immersive experience, able to locate and amplify fragments of sound from as far back as 1907.

Name: Emily Hallows
University/Course: University of Brighton & Design for digital media
Description: My work is a fully finalised picture book for children called Tia and her telescope. Available to read

Name: Danielle Tonge
University/Course: University of Ulster - Textile Art, Design and Fashion
Description: My collection is based on my childhood memories and all the fun I had growing up along the Moray Coast. I was always fascinated with the colours in the skies, so I abstracted colours from my own photography of the sunsets and northern lights seen from Burghead beach, to create a bright and lively colour palette. Combining this with the textures found along the beach, I have created a girl's knitwear collection using natural, renewable fibres such as merino and lambswool.

Name: Jessica Kirkpatrick
University/Course: University of central Lancashire
Description:
"My lifelong passion for botanical's and living creatures inspired me to create a body of work dedicated to them, that can also make a difference. I focused on endangered species and the habitats they live in. I wanted to create designs that can educate people on species they may never have heard of before. My designs should capture people’s attention and help to start conversations, 
whether it’s asking what 
unusual creature is climbing 
through the branches or, how 
the print would look as a whole 
in their home."

Name: Cara Rooney
University/Course: University of Dundee / DJCAD, Illustration
Description:
My illustration and design work takes the form of activity and picture books intended to encourage nature connection. 
Through bold compositions, painterly textures and contrasting colour palettes, I encourage empathy for the littlest and biggest of creatures.

Name: Tyler Van der Berg
University/Course: Brighton University, studying Design for Digital Media
Description: I am redesigning passports, this one is for South Africa. I am also doing some for the UK, America and China. For the South Africa one, I am focusing on the heritage of the country and designing them in vibrant colours.

Name: Bartek Marzec
University/Course: Loughborough University
Description:
Clique - BMX Bike Hire Scheme

The purpose of Clique is to provide an outlet to those in limited opportunity areas of Birmingham, where youth centres are no longer or rare. This would be done through the use of a city-wide BMX bike hire scheme aimed at young teens.

The slogan of Clique is to Break out of the cycle. This can be seen as an informal line that persuades to get cycling. However, the underlining purpose and a deeper-rooted cause is, to break the cycle of youths spiralling into crime.

Marketing material would engage with viewers through the use of AR. As viewers scan, these posters videos come to life and the Clique App becomes available for download.

Name: Carter Brown
University/Course: Brunel University London: Digital Design
Description: vibe is a new wellbeing companion for students. My final year project consists of the branding, user experience and marketing of this friendly character-based wellness journey!

Name: Sarah Ellis
University/Course: Ulster University - (BA Hons) Photography and Video
Description: Gym Candy' is series of self-portraits which reclaim the use of gym derogatory terms and slurs, often in reference to women. The inspiration comes from my wanting to compete in a bodybuilding show this Autumn. Within the sub-culture of bodybuilding, there are conversations about gender, race and the use of drugs which are still failing to make progress. People are quick to assume an opinion about any number of these topics when speaking on the topic of bodybuilding. This series is a starting point and a way to open up the floor to have these discussions.

Name: Taylor Dewar
University/Course: University of Dundee
Description: A still from my piece "What Do You Call It", an exploration of what we call female masturbation. To normalise the idea of sexual pleasure as a human right; my idea was simple, involve normal people in the campaign’s creation.

Name: Jack Brodie
University/Course: Edinburgh Napier, MSc Creative Advertising
Description: 50% of the population in Gaza are children. The bombing continues yet coverage has declined. The work shines a light on the difficulties of being a child within the region. "It's hard to be a kid when your playground's a war zone."

Name: Ava
University/Course: University of Brighton Graphic Design
Description: research, creative direction and design

Name: Ethan McGowan
University/Course: University of Wisconsin - Stout, BFA Graphic Design & Interactive Media
Description: "____ RULES EVERYTHING AROUND ME" is a project examining how five different films explore money and the actions characters take because of it. We buy things that will help us feel belonging and establish our identity. The things we would do and the lengths we go for money is sometimes unimaginable, yet we do them anyway.

Name: Mollie Browne
University/Course: Ulster University - Foundation Art and Design
Description: Long story short- The meaning behind this installation/ sculpture is abandonment. It’s based on photographs I took in a deserted children’s home. The baby clothes/night dress were bought in charity shops and dipped in wax. The paper beneath are pages ripped from a used child’s colouring book. I also named the piece “The Wolf and Seven Kids” as this was one of the stories in the back of the children’s book, I thought it was quite fitting!!

Name: William Marshall
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Graphic Design
Description: Advertisement for a campaign ran by Vans, which encourages skaters to hunt for QR codes which are located at skate spots in their areas. Skaters then will scan and upload a video of their trick in the found area for the chance to win a pair of the Vans Pro Classics.

Name: Justice Southwell
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description: My project aims to encourage young people to get involved in activism and protest, by tackling the barriers people believe to be preventing their participation. The zine posters are based on specific student led protests and designed to reference their visual language - whilst utilising low-fi print methods reflecting the underground publishing methods of the 1960s.

Name: Jin Su
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description:
This illustration is based on a part of Jorge Luis Borges ’s short story Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius.
“The sun and the water on a swimmer's chest, the vague tremulous rose colour we see with our eyes closed, the sensation of being carried along by a river and also by sleep.”

Name: Godfrey
University/Course: Graphic Design
Description: Redesign David Bowie Six Vinyl Albums' Cover

Name: Sophia Brown
University/Course: University of Derby - Textile Design, Weave.
Description: ‘Nature’s Autograph’, explores the natural form and growth of Earth’s creations through an abstract lens.

Name: Brylle Vistal
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA Graphic Design
Description:
As the whole world is in the midst of the global COVID-19 pandemic, some minority communities worldwide are  seeing drastic rise in microaggressions and racial discrimination. 

'Hidden Behind the Mask' is a publication which explores how and why face masks have become stigmatised and racialised in Western culture, and its effects towards Asian people.

Name: Chloe Tunnicliffe
University/Course: Staffordshire University, Graphic Design
Description:
A Stitch in Time is an exhibition showcasing the social significance of cross stitch samplers throughout the centuries. 

The main poster for the exhibition was my own cross stitch sampler that explores the different ways samplers have been used. These uses were cataloguing stitch techniques, education and decoration.

Name: Sean Morgan
University/Course: BA(Hons) Illustration, Plymouth College of Art
Description: I love to make work that is bold, full of texture and quirk. This is a speculative book cover design for an imaginary chef about the joy of Chinese cooking.

Name: Sarah Richardson
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone
Description:
This collection celebrates a terrible, dark beauty in uniqueness. Inspired  by the plants ruthless yet successful survival techniques, I have created a collection of repeat prints to portray a sense of continuous growth. The printed textiles have been developed digitally while retaining hand-drawn qualities within bold compositions to create visual impact and mirror the endearing qualities of the visual source. Additionally, this collection builds upon the printed designs creating dynamic textures through embroidery and embellishment, to produce a striking aesthetic. 

The collection is designed for couture inspired, high fashion womenswear. Brands like Delpozo and Richard Quinn are key influences with relation to their use of artisan hand processes and expressive prints.  The collection is digitally printed onto a range of materials, from thick linens to delicate satins, to achieve unique statement prints. The use of contrasting textural fabrics creates a tactile experience much like the plants dangerous and intelligently designed surfaces. This collection captures the devious personality of some of nature’s most intriguing plants and evokes it through bold and dramatic fashion textiles.

Name: Corrina Mark
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: As a designer who loves to explore outside for inspiration, this collage captures the feeling of freedom and wanting to be free post lockdown.

Name: Ryan Waddon
