University/Course: University for the Creative Arts (Farnham) - Illustration
Description: This is an illustration from my 40-page wordless narrative titled "The Devil's Playground". The story explores ideas of greed and the lengths some people will go to in search of fame and fortune.

Name: Georgia Latham
University/Course: Shillington College, Graphic Design
Description: Even before lockdown, I was acutely aware how rubbish I was about calling my grandparents and I felt that this was a common guilt among my generation. Grand Tales is a fictitious campaign for Age UK (although I haven't included their logo for copyright reasons) encouraging us to see our grandparents as fun-loving humans who have led rich lives and have stories to tell. Give them a call!

Name: Ann Naskidashvili
University/Course: Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp, graphic design
Description: work is simply about looking in the mirror into yourself

Name: Jess Holloway
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art
Description: This is the front cover of a fashion magazine made by my character Lipstick Tiger. Fashion is his hobby, and he has been known to have hand-made two fashion lines so far and has started producing these magazines to model his own work. The magazine is featured in the comic I've made, and will exist as a physical object too. I wanted to delve into meta-narrative as part of my final major project.

Name: Stephanie Dowd
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University, Graphic Design
Description: Nourish is an earth conscious brand, stocking plant based mylk drinks in reusable glass bottles. The drinks can be ordered through the app. The vision is to reduce the impacts of climate change by swapping plastic for reusable glass bottles and dairy milk to plant-based mylk. Nourish’s motto of Drink, Return and Reuse is our three easy (and tasty) steps to helping reduce plastic pollution in the drinks industry. With every bottle returned, the consumer earns a stamp towards a free bottle of Nourish through the app. All of the brand touch points have the consideration of environmental impacts, ensuring we are nourishing the planet.

Name: Laura Murdy
University/Course: University of Ulster Belfast, Fine Art Print
Description: Movement of the bird flying

Name: Aimee Somerville
University/Course: Ulster University - Photography with Video
Description: My work is self-portraits using makeup to create a mask. This image is very performative, I am crying in the photograph but because it is staged I do not feel vulnerable .

Name: Curtis
University/Course: Ulster University - Photography
Description: Our communities have embraced the power of social distancing and in reponse I have set out to reveal the impact by showing the two dimentional barriers that are supposed to control our movement but indeed have warped the physical distance into an emotional one.

Name: Rhiannon Victoria Rouch
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University - BA Product Design
Description:
To Create a series of Baking Utensils for those diagnosed with Rheumatoid Arthritis. The product range must give support and ease the load of baking  whilst being stylish and medically viable. 

Oberlo- This range of products keeps the wrist in a neutral position throughout each stage of baking. Achieved by the angled bowl and the specialised utensil handles.

Name: Sinuo Guo
University/Course: University of the Arts London, BA Graphic and Media Design
Description: This campaign aims to raise awareness of the racial prejudice and xenophobia against the Asian community during the Covid-19 pandemic. Using the words and phrases that we have been associating with the virus, juxtaposed with the racial issues that I wanted to highlight. The campaign would be distributed physically through sticker forms in place of the social distancing stickers, and through social media during the times of social distancing.

Name: Claudia Pezzini
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA ILLUSTRATION
Description:
Illustration for the short story SLEEP by Haruki Murakami.
Murakami writes from the perspective of a woman with insomnia: one night she has an unsettling nightmare and she cannot sleep any longer.

Name: Jade Newlin
University/Course: Falmouth University BA(Hons) Illustration
Description: An album cover for record called:  Als. Tanzen Verboden War which consists of music forbidden in the dance halls during WW2 in Nazi occupied Germany.

Name: Mansi Katta
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts – Graphic Communication
Description: For a D&AD Brief on how to tackle the lack of female sexual pleasure; the creative solution uses ambiguous images to show the similarities of lips and the labia (outer lips); giving women the confidence to talk about what they want sexually.

Name: Emma Shakeshaft
University/Course: BA(Hons) Textile Design at Leeds Arts University
Description:
My personal passion for sport has inspired my recent design collections
My work is inspired by sporting heroes of the now. For my final collection I have used Olympic athletes as my trend inspiration including Adam Peaty and Max Whitlock. 
I follow and record the athlete's movement through drawing then work digitally to create patterns and achieve my desired aesthetic.

Name: Laura Neal
University/Course: I am graduating from the University of Southampton and have studied Games Design & Art
Description:
There are few things in life I love more than the American frontier, or 'Wild West', as it is commonly known. 
For my final major project, I created an American frontier-themed card game, which details the vastly different backstories of six archetypal Western characters. Players assume the roles of at least one of these characters, and are required to complete a series of 'missions'. The first person to complete all of their missions is the winner.
My game, 'Last Chance Saloon', is more than just a project. It is my personal love letter to the 'Western', and embodies everything I love about it in its design.

Name: Xanthe Bonsall
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA Textile Design
Description:
A digital drawing from my main collection of textile prints, using Modernist architecture as a theme and exploring the concept of 'retro futurism.'

This is part of a series of drawings of the Barbican Estate which formed my initial research, to be developed in to repeat prints for my graduate textile collection, aimed at the sportswear market.

Name: Alice Campion
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description: DOUCE fragranced laundry detergent, a luxury subscription box of custom scented laundry detergent capsules, tailored for specific garments.

Name: Kristine Kokina
University/Course: I am graduating from Advertising and Brand Design course at Ravensbourne University London.
Description: “For the People” is a collaboration project with disco/funk DJ Dan and Out. It aims to tell a cultural narrative and expose the artist’s personality to a broader audience. This is a storyboard of the two videos that explore both sides of Dan and Out’s practise: him and his audience.

Name: James Feeley
University/Course: Robert Gordon University (Gray's School of Art) - Communication Design (Photography)
Description: Struggling to finish up my main projects to complete the course due to COVID I pivoted and chose to explore life in lockdown Britain. This image is to show the new normal - a tongue and cheek ode to the British Drinking culture and a wink to the missed out graduation celebrations.

Name: Joshua Jones
University/Course: UAL London college of fashion - Fashion Photography
Description: CONTROL & POWER

Name: Anna Ballard
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University BSc Product Design
Description: Introducing Postool a unique chair that enhances natural human interaction without the need for complicated technology. A large part of how we communicate with each other is nonverbal. What you say to people with your eyes or your body language is just as powerful as what you say with words. The Postool is stemmed from an exercise ball the idea being that your abdominal/back muscles are constantly engaged and active in order to maintain proper posture thus forth making you more open. If somebody looks engaged, is learning forwards and attentive and looks approachable it is more than likely others will want to talk them than if they are closed off and are constantly on a laptop or phone.

Name: Irina Cobzas
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description: Advertising design for Pets at home, the largest pet supplies retailer in the UK. Inspired by the pets tails and including the creation of a unique typeface.

Name: Nav Sihra
University/Course: Graphic Design, Leeds Beckett University.
Description: The piece is a representation of how race and skin colour shouldn't be a judgement of a persons character and that relationships are not bound by something as insignificant as the colour of someones skin. Although the subject is deep, i chose to portray the piece through a friendly and wholesome cartoon illustration. The piece started as a small sketch, which was then painted as a mural in the centre of Leeds City, and has since made its way onto merchandise and clothing fuelled by the student founded brand "Kayoh Design".

Name: Hannah Lim
University/Course: University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh College of Art, BA Sculpture
Description:
My work has become a way of physically representing my cultural identity. As a person of Singaporean and British heritage my practice engages with the colonial connotations of the relationship between the East and West. This is most evident in themes such as Orientalism and the Chinoiserie in which elements of Chinese design were re-imagined in relation to European aesthetics and tastes. My practice touches upon this collision of cultures, both on a personal and political level. 
This year I have been creating furniture-like structures. Combining motifs and imagery from Chinese and European furniture design, I attempt to somewhat re-imagine and reclaim these practices that have had problematic colonial undertones. Cultural designs are shared as opposed to appropriated. These objects are composed of a combination brightly coloured MDF and light reflecting materials such as acrylic, often strung with silky fabrics. 
An important element of my practice relates to the functionality of these objects, experimenting with functional flat-pack design has become quite a playful process. This experimentation results in peculiar yet dynamic transformations of seemingly simple furniture structures. Playing with light and shadow enables each structure to be seen in a new way, the cut out design of each furniture piece lends itself to this kind of experimentation, where the shadows created by a setting sun or coloured light often complete the work.

Name: Layla Mencarini
University/Course: University of Plymouth, Illustration
Description: Being lost in the woods, with the thought something might be following

Name: Regina Jambor
University/Course: Falmouth University, Illustration BA
Description: This is an illustration inspired byEmpire of Sand, a fantasy novel by Tasha Suri. It is a mystical story of desert nomads, sleeping gods and dance rites.

Name: Gracie
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth
Description: This piece is from my final collection palm springs poolside. Palm Springs Poolside is a Collection of young womenswear prints inspired by synchronised swimmers and vintage swimwear, based within Palm Springs. Capturing the vintage aspect and updating this with a 21st century twist taking a fun, innovative, modern approach. I have explored synchronised swimming taking a playful approach adapting to my graphic playful style of working.

Name: Alex Navarrete
University/Course: Birmingham City University
Description:
In this series of landscape photographs, I have documented the twisted roads within the natural landscapes. These photographs were shot on medium format colour film and the photographs were captured in the Lake District, New Forest and Snowdonia National Park. 

Embracing what a landscape has in the present and what to look for when documenting the areas that surround us.  

Shooting on film has always been my preference, it is the medium I love to play with and feel most comfortable using.

Name: Amy Levoir Spencer
University/Course: University of Brighton and BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: This piece is a double page spread, from a book that I created about a message in a bottle travelling through time. This particular page showed a modern day chaotic English Channel.

Name: Frida Skoglie
University/Course: Kingston University. Creative and Cultural Industries: Design Marketing
Description:
Memoria is an interactive installation built up by a big kaleidoscope and videos being reflected. It reflects your most precious and forgotten memories creating an immersive experience. 

We often focus on the stresses of the now, rather than looking at the good things that surround us. Therefore Memoria triggers the memories that you will look back on later in life. You will remember the sunny day at the beach and not the one dress that didn't fit in high-school. Taking you on a journey of laughs and love. Even if just for a moment.

Name: Colette Hillcoat-Searle
University/Course: Loughborough University with BA Honours in Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: Design for a poster-zine. Promotional material for a brand concept entitled Con Artists, an anonymous online platform - a space for creatives to learn about Imposter Syndrome & instigate discussions about mental health in the workplace.

Name: Celina Atkins
University/Course: Arts university Bournemouth
Description: This design is a tufted wood tile inspired by a woodland walk surrounded by landscapes. it has a interesting tactile surface that has a calming aesthetic. the  sample is designed using laser cut wood with tufted yarn infills using a tufting gun.

Name: Alycia Boyle
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Printed Textiles & Surface Pattern Design
Description: The title of this project, that this print is from, is called 'Magnified Mundane'; aiming to encourage people to pay attention and explore their surroundings. Doing so, recognising the  beauty of everyday life that is usually overlooked and dismissed. Unnoticed textures, patterns and colours have been taken from seeing hidden gems whilst on daily walks and translated into a naive and playful graphic print leading viewers to question what it is their looking at and perhaps influencing them to notice the beauty of what's around them.

Name: Josie Hales
University/Course: Loughborough University - Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: For this project, my aim was to increase the public’s awareness of autism to ensure that all autistic people are suitably supported, understood and appreciated for who they are.  To make my poster campaign interactive I have used a red filter effect with red filter glasses. This technique allows the viewers to sympathise with how an autistic person may be feeling, with the idea of the overwhelming and overloaded composition, but as soon as the glasses are put on the powerful message appears, explaining briefly the difficulties someone with autism goes through each day.

Name: Tamesha
University/Course: Nottingham Trent, Graphic Design
Description: The brief was to choose an item from a given list and create a body of work around it. I chose a paperclip and created a typeface by bending paperclips and pushing them into slots cut into paper. The typeface retains the form and imperfections from the process as a way to celebrate individuality and uniqueness.

Name: Jamie Baldrick
University/Course: BA Hons Textile Art, Design and Fashion at Ulster University.
Description:
My work usually derives from my admiration for other women and the narrative of the female voice. I am obsessed with the roles women have had historically in the world of knitwear. 

My graduate collection was originally inspired by the pen pal letters I have shared over the years with the women in my life. This is reflected through my palette and my methods of embracing the mistakes in my pieces. When it comes to colour, I prefer a maximalist approach and have combined this with rich textiles to create the basis of my knitted collection.

Name: Konstantinos Panagiotopoulos
University/Course: University of Brighton,  Graphic Design BAHons
Description:
Last summer I did an exhibition entitled ‘OXYMORON’.
The name of the exhibition came from my attempt to combine neoclassical art with street art in my works. For my independent project, I decided to apply the logic and design of  ‘OXYMORON’ to fashion, and more specifically to street fashion. 

I worked with Mortasia, who is a fashion designer and she designed a shirt, a trench coat and two dungrees.

We  chose to design these particular pieces because we wanted to incorporate elements of street art into more classic clothing, rather than a t-shirt or hoodie. 

The image that i sent you is the Trench Coat.

Name: Emma Coleman
University/Course: Ravensbourne Uni
Description: The campaign focused on showing drag's infectiousness being shown through 3 universal values of expression, creativity and confidence.

Name: Owen Mountstevens
University/Course: University of Plymouth
Description: This piece is in support of the NHS and the staff fighting the COVID19 outbreak

Name: Joseph Giltrap
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University, Graphic Arts & Design.
Description:
A Graphic score or graphic notation is the representation of music through the use of visual symbols outside the realm of traditional music notation. For this project I have aimed to represent forms of electronic dance music visually, through abstract elements. 

If you require different pictures please let me know.

Name: Shivani Chugh
University/Course: Coventry University, BA(hons) Graphic Design
Description:
How often do you get to design a brand identity for a Meteorologist? 

Presenting to you, The Weather Jam hosted by David Jones, giving you regular updates on the weather, letting you plan your day better.
The incentive was to create an interesting package by fusing the traits of a Meteorologist with something completely unexpected, a Disc Jockey. 
The concept has been elevated by combining elements which draw inspiration from the profession, communicated with the help of some catchy captions.

Definitely a party you don’t wanna miss, tune in to The Weather Jam now.

Name: Gareth James
University/Course: University of South Wales, BA Advertising Design
Description: For my self directed FMP, I chose to create an experiential marketing event to launch giffgaff's 5G network. I chose to create a 5-a-side football tournament, played on a 5G pitch, in 5 locations across the UK. I targeted Gen Z and this piece was used for the social media campaign. I released details of the event at regular intervals through Instagram and TikTok, to build excitement towards the tournaments.

Name: Jazz Ireland
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University - Graphic Communication
Description:
“Throughout history beauty ideals and perceptions of beauty have been forever changing, no one knows what tomorrows perfect will look like.”

My project is designed to take you on a journey through time to experience the different ideals of beauty, and perceptions of beauty, you can experience how drastically and often that the trends change. How ten years can make a world of difference in respect of what we would see on the cover of magazines.

I am hoping to educate people and bring you the reality of body image and how it’s affecting everyday health, not just in women, or a younger audience but everyone. My campaigns main goal is to address the forever growing mental health issues that have been associated with body image, we aim to do this by showing past and present examples of ideals and beauty this is used to emphasise that beauty if forever changing - perfection is ever changing.

Name: Hershila Parmar
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts and studying Graphic Designer
Description: Golden Spice is a Turmeric Infused Vodka drink, a brand inspired by the Indian Culture. The intensely golden spice turmeric, adds the perfect balance to your alcohol beverage.

Name: Abby Sowerby
University/Course: Textile Design at Leeds Arts University
Description: This piece is from my Safari Explorers collection intended for a children's market. It follows a zebra themed print in which  other animal prints are used to disguise the real zebra to encourage and help children learn what animals look like.

Name: Abigail Talbot
University/Course: Loughborough University - Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: I have created an in-store and digital collaborative campaign between Monki and Rainforest Alliance, whereby 10% of the profits from #monkicares ethical clothing range will be donated to the charity, encouraging the consumer to 'feel good, shop good' and 'love ethical garms'.  The campaign includes environmental store graphics (guiding the user to the product range in-store), an interactive selfie wall, till-point posters and a branded in-store Photo Booth, as well as social media content.

Name: Duibheasa Ní Dhomhnaill
University/Course: Ulster University, Textile Art, Design and Fashion
Description: My graduate collection is inspired by classic horror and vintage Halloween aesthetics. Influenced by anxiety and the feeling of being watched or stared at.

Name: Lucy
University/Course: Bath Spa University, Graphic Communication
Description: There is a rising awareness of Air Pollution and the detrimental effects it is having on the climate and health; and furthermore, a rising demand for businesses to be transparent about their impacts on the environment to consumers without the use of hard statistics. The concept of the BreathMark began as a localised response to the introduction of the Clean air Zone in Bath, and has grown to be a guerrilla-influenced climate campaign.

Name: Sinead Taylor
University/Course: University of Ulster - Graphic Design & Illustration
Description: A Nike Plus digital asset for all teenage girls aged 14 -19 in London, aiming to motivate and bring innovation through a collaboration between the PE sports hall, girls leisure time and social media.

Name: Laura Foster
University/Course: Birmingham City University Fine Art
Description: Nature taking over the human form to cause disruption.

Name: Natascha E Russell
University/Course: Robert Gordon University - Communication Design BA (Hons)
Description: I have designed an Editorial magazine based on the findings of fast fashion and it's issues. I took the photographs in a style that matches current trends to attract the attention of young people. I then created quotes on following pages to shock the viewers on the actual impact that fast fashion has on the environment and our people. The campaign editorial is essentially to stop fast fashion.

Name: Abigail Talbot
University/Course: Loughborough University  - Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description: I have created a typographic brand identity for a local jewellery brand looking to transition to a larger, more sustainable business. Amongst sustainable brand collateral, I have designed a custom typeface, influenced by the modular style and shapes of the jewellery. Romy Studio is moving forward with the times as the business is growing and needed a typeface to reflect the and feel futuristic.

Name: Marius Trinkunas
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: The billboard proposal showcases three of my projects that I have done throughout my last year at Falmouth university. It is a combination of various outcomes from separate projects that all together demonstrates my creative practice.

Name: Delphi Campbell
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Fine Art
Description: This triptych of soft sculptures focuses on my life as a disabled woman. Clotho, the larger pink one is an expression of my chronic illnesses. The repetitive stitching all over the piece reflects the daily, life-long pain I deal with, both my physical, bodily pain, and the wider impacts of my conditions; changes to my social life, the way I am perceived, interactions with strangers and difficulties I face using mobility aids. Lachesis, the black piece, is chronic depression another experience I deal with on a daily basis. They are sisters to me, each one having the capacity to worsen each other, often coming hand in hand. This work bears down upon the room, weighing on your shoulders as it suspends from a bar across the ceiling. Finally, Atropos addresses a not-much-discussed phenomena - the existence of disabled people as sexual entities. In most regards I am like any other 21-year-old woman, including my sexuality. Yet I am still met with shock and confusion when I speak about enjoying sex, every Tinder date I go on leads to; "so... why do you need a wheelchair?". I am seen as a useless, sexless lump, discarded on the floor. The opportunity to be sexual or vulnerable only seems the same when I leave my disability at the door, swapping my wheelchair or cane to walking unaided, concealing my struggle and identity to pretend I am "normal" - see, ablebodied - for a night. So my choice of sheer voile reflects that vulnerability, parodies my deception, or privacy, depending on how you see it, and reveals the same lumpy pink flesh we all have inside, coated by a seminal veil.

Name: Daisy Tortuga
University/Course: kingston university, illustration
Description:
Daisy Tortuga is A multi-disciplinary artist with a body of work centred around craft and creation. Using found objects and making to communicate complex emotions and statements, while pushing the perceptions of traditional illustration. She takes an intuitive approach to making with a process both emotional and cathartic, expressing this in a range of mediums such as quilt, furniture, clothing, wax sculpture, writing and sound. 
There is a nostalgic element to the work, bringing domestic spaces into the gallery and distorting them so they can be viewed with new meaning. Using the clinical setting of the gallery space in this way, allows the work to be analysed truly objectively. Craft historically was not considered art or illustration, Daisy Tortuga uses these techniques to discuss difficult topics, while challenging the way we view craft in the artistic world.

Name: Mark Andresen
University/Course: Pratt Institute, fine arts
Description: This so-called pandemic

Name: Youmna Hazzaa
University/Course: Edinburgh Napier University - MSc Creative Advertising
Description:
Bread consumption has fallen steadily over the last few decades.
Average consumption now equates to only around 2-3 slices of bread a day.
But what would our favourite sandwiches even be without bread?
It’s time to fall in love with bread again, by remembering how much it means to us.

Name: Eva Martin
University/Course: I am graduating from TU Dublin School of Creative Arts. I studied Visual Communications.
Description:
It's Not Me, It's You'
Relationships are hard. They start off with the best intentions. Excitement, attraction, and convenience lure you in. As time goes by some relationships
can become toxic, on both sides. But old habits are comfortable and despite the long term implications, you often stay in the relationship.
This campaign capitalises on the language of break ups and uses intimate relationships as a metaphor for consumerist culture. It aims to encourage young people to take action by ‘breaking up’ with old habits and ‘move on’ to a more sustainable lifestyle.
Breakups are never easy, but sometimes they’re for all the right reasons.

Name: Hazel Shorney
University/Course: Loughborough University — BA(Hons) Graphic Communication & Illustration
Description: The Night Manager is an espionage novel like no other. Through the book cover design I illustrate the new world that Pine finds himself in where no one is as they seem. Haunted by the ghosts of his past Pine becomes trapped, drowning within this new distorted world.

Name: Grace Johnston
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, Textile Design
Description: Inspired by the wildflowers within the Yorkshire Dales. Using texture, loose painting techniques and bright colours to capture the wildness that is within the Dales.

Name: Edward.Hongyi.JIA
University/Course: Chelsea college of art / UAL / Fine art
Description:
Artwork Description
This project is based on the experience of tropical fish farming that I have spent for 14 years. My first-round tropical fish breeder in northern China. I specialize in artificial breeding and disease control of tropical fish for Pterophyllum. I am eager to extend the meaning of the influence of spiritual support on individuals. In the works, I tried to combine the linear expression of Chinese traditional painting techniques with the mechanical form, hoping to convey surrealism with oriental characteristics through the works. I hope that these "fishes" accompanying me can form an eternal form like machinery. So, I gave the fish a semi- mechanized half-life form and let them live in a space full of hope and light. I want to pass this project to the public. In today's fast-growing technology and economy, people's "spiritual sustenance" is also an important part of building a non-material level of society. 

In this work, I use the sci- fi concept and traditional Chinese aesthetics to explore the ultimate expression of life with the uncertainty of fish and ink. Many people think that the end of life may leave with the demise of the flesh. However, I think in the future, the form of existence of life may leave the flesh and exist in the form of semi-mechanized and semi-life, but it will eventually be completely separated from any form of support. To reach eternal life in space

Name: Alex
University/Course: Hochschule der Künste Bern
Description:
My work revolves about the everyday problem of any creative person. The moment, when you just can't figure how to continue your work because your brain is stuck. Or something else just won't let you work, you are blocked in your creativity. 

My animated short film will deal with this topic from a certain distance. The problem is metaphorized by a machine (the creative flow) and figures which look like little monsters. Those symbolize three facts which influence the (or at least my) creativity: reflecting, decision making and patience. 

The final clip will be something around four minutes long.

Name: Emily Wye
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Fine Art & Art History
Description: Engaging with painting in the expanded field, I use it as a source of metaphorical reference which develops into formal yet chaotic compositions. My fascination with bodies and the visceral nature of flesh lies in how I process acrylic and oil mediums on to stretched linen. Fluctuating between the importance of the making process and deeper personal meanings, I aim to encapsulate a glimpse at fleeting narratives which feed into my daily life. These narratives are revealed through a figurative language built from colour, form and subtle text. I tend to use collage, introducing old recycled paintings which have since been peeled off their frames, resulting in the new canvases becoming busy and saturated. Creating and removing layers has become fundamental to how my paintings evolve as-well as introducing a three-dimensional exterior to the work.

Name: Youmna Hazzaa
University/Course: Edinburgh Napier University - MSc Creative Advertising
Description:
The daily commute has a huge impact on our mental health and contributes to feelings of anxiety.
However, research shows that those who use their travel time more effectively feel more positive about their commutes.

Love Audible, Love Traffic is a campaign aimed at showing people how Audible can improve their traffic time, making it more meaningful and productive.
Posters use popular book titles with a witty twist, celebrating the new-found love for commuting.
The ads will be specific to each city and the way people commute there.

It’s time we learned to love traffic.
Love Audible. Love Traffic.

Creative Team: Youmna Hazzaa & Daniel Finn

Name: Barbara Wei
University/Course: Norwich University Of the Arts/Design for publishing
Description: A spread design feature for magazine showcasing the vibrant of Norwich city.

Name: Emily Wye
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Fine Art & Art History
Description: Engaging with painting in the expanded field, I use it as a source of metaphorical reference which develops into formal yet chaotic compositions. My fascination with bodies and the visceral nature of flesh lies in how I process acrylic and oil mediums on to stretched linen. Fluctuating between the importance of the making process and deeper personal meanings, I aim to encapsulate a glimpse at fleeting narratives which feed into my daily life. These narratives are revealed through a figurative language built from colour, form and subtle text. I tend to use collage, introducing old recycled paintings which have since been peeled off their frames, resulting in the new canvases becoming busy and saturated. Creating and removing layers has become fundamental to how my paintings evolve as-well as introducing a three-dimensional exterior to the work.

Name: Michal Kedourie
University/Course: UAL - Camberwell, Graphic Design
Description: This is a record cover for a single that was written to raise awareness for the special needs community. I designed the typeface to have a playful, approachable feel, but also to give the message that we can stretch ourselves to learn new ideas.

Name: Freya Umataliev
University/Course: BA (Hons) Graphic Design, Falmouth University
Description: This book is a visual representation of my personal experience in discovering my heritage. This narrative tells the tale of the hidden, rural beauty of Central Asia, expressed through intricate paper craft including embossing and paper cutting. The story unfolds by contrasting this beauty with the city lifestyle and the challenges that were faced, indicated through typographic play.

Name: Beth McGlynn
University/Course: Loughborough University
Description: You is the first campaign of its kind with regards to male body image and it aims to break the stigma of men not talking about their bodies. It has been designed with GQ+ as an article series with the aim of raising awareness of body dissatisfaction in men as a result of media used in magazines which promotes an idealised image of the male form.

Name: Alysha Harvey
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University, Graphic Design
Description: The work is part of 'The Printworks' project. I have created lino printed wallpaper based on the history of Sheffield and how it is recognised as a "Steel City". I have also created metal keycards and do not disturb signs out of stainless steel to go with this theme.

Name: Marc Craig
University/Course: University of Strathclyde - MSci Product Design Innovation
Description: Float is a device that uses sensory stimulation to rekindle memories, in the aim of sparking endorphin enducing nostalgia.

Name: Gina McDowall & Isobel Griffiths
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: Part of a campaign for British Heart Foundation we created targeted adverts for people that had suffered a heart attack to avoid a second one that can affect 1/5 people after their first. We did this through touching on personal notes, and what they have to lose.

Name: Milena
University/Course: Universidad Jorge Tadeo Lozano Bogotá Colombia. Graphic Design
Description: It is Orbe's typography I tried to figure out how sphere could be move and show some letters. Orbe has some similaritys with Armillary sphere. Letters is like stars because these make you see another world.

Name: Shivani Chugh
University/Course: Coventry University, BA(hons) Graphic Design
Description:
How often do you get to design a brand identity for a Meteorologist? 
Presenting to you, The Weather Jam hosted by David Jones, giving you regular updates on the weather, letting you plan your day better.

The incentive was to create an interesting package by fusing the traits of a Meteorologist with something completely unexpected, a Disc Jockey. 
The concept has been elevated by pairing up elements that draw inspiration from the profession, with some catchy captions.

Definitely a party you don’t wanna miss, tune in to The Weather Jam now.

Name: Lucas Hesse
University/Course: University of Applied Sciences Mainz,  Communication Design
Description:
Although design is a very visual discipline and the emphasis is on making communication vis-
ible, it’s difficult to get a quick overview of the graduation projects from the design deparment.

Especially the external perception of the indivi-
dual universities suffers: What is the orientation or focus of an university? Is the work there more artistic or applied? Are there analogue workshops or is the focus more on digital media? Do
the focal points of the university overlap with my own? Without extensive research, it is rather difficult to compare the university landscape.

»Call for Creatives« is an archive platform for graduation projects in the field of design, where graduates can register and upload their bachelor, master or diploma project. The individual entries can be filtered and sorted according 
to city/university, final year and focus, in order to get an easier overview of the universities.

Name: Georgia Barrell
University/Course: Leeds Art University BA(Hons) Textile Design
Description: This design was made for my women's wear collection called  'Futuristic Florals',  exploring the relationship between the beauty of nature and synthetics through shape and colour.

Name: Katharine Alldritt
University/Course: Graphic Communication at Birmingham City University
Description: A set of posters for the recent D&AD submission, these posters promote a series of workshops that encourage women to speak openly about their sexual experiences to help break the stigmas surrounding female pleasure.

Name: Megan Freeman
University/Course: Falmouth University Graphic Design
Description: Editorial work is an aspect of design which I love. I very much enjoy it and think it's my strongest design skill. Therefore I've collaborated some of my favourite projects in a 'portfolio in progress' which I think represents me as a designer.

Name: Sarah Larby
University/Course: University of Leeds, (BA) Fine Art with Contemporary Cultural Theory, International
Description: "Untitled: Lollipops" is a work depicting an imagined space based off a sculpture I made this last month. My practice is primarily sculptural and focuses on materiality, for this piece I was exploring the use of wool roving and felting in my work. However, there is another side to my practice, where I like to keep my sculptures a little bit absurd and whimsical, bringing a smile to people's faces. Due to lockdown I was unable to get the materials needed to make multiple editions of the work, so I wanted to recreate the space I live in and reimagine it as an area of whimsy and fun, filled with my fluffy sculptures blowing in the wind.

Name: Rebecca Green
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA Graphic Design
Description:
Named after the 7th Duchess of Bedford, 7th Duchess is a luxury cold tea brand, with just a splash of scandal in every bottle. 

The 7th Duchess of Bedford, Anna Russell (1783–1857) was a lady-in-waiting and lifelong friend to Queen Victoria. More significantly, she is credited with the advent of the afternoon tea which she first took while visiting Belvoir Castle. It quickly became a socially acceptable way for women to meet up and gossip.

Name: Amy Greenfield
University/Course: Leeds arts university - textile design
Description:
Textural conversational prints bring a Halloween theme to the everyday. Using blues and purples to create a feeling of depth mimicking a dark night under the moonlight. 

Bright white contrasts against the colours of the scene to draw focus to the characters going about their every day lives away from being scary on the 31st October.

Large crayon marks replicate child-like illustration methods to imitate a child’s drawing to create a playful bond between character and child. 

What do ghosts and monsters get up to the other 364 days of the year?

Name: Livia Carpineto
University/Course: Camberwell College of Arts, Illustration
Description: This illustration is part of my final personal project in which I am exploring themes surrounding female identity and metamorphosis. I call metamorphoses the radical changes which involve the body and mind of women at different stages of their lives. My illustrative practice is driven by the potential of delving into a kind of collective imagination, resonating with both our personal and shared stories. Therefore, I try to visually translate the significance of my own experience into something more expansive and universal.  I am interested in the symbology behind transformation in myth and folkloristic tales, which can be the manifestation of an individual’s inner conflict, as well as signify the process of transition from an immature form to an adult one, or the passage into a more or less spiritual state. Besides, my intention is to question the literary tropes of the female shapeshifter, historically permeated by controversial gender and sexual implications.

Name: Hazel McIntosh
University/Course: UWE Bristol, BA Hons Illustration
Description: Our lives are like a fairgrounds. What goes up must come back down.

Name: Timothy Stewart
University/Course: University of Cumbria, Ba(hons) Graphic Design
Description: To highlight the importance of making sure that a laptop or PC has an Intel 10th Gen Processor, we created a multimedia campaign utilising copywriting and photography to show how absurd something is, when you take something necessary out of an object or situation. Like buying a house with no roof or throwing a party with no people.

Name: Holly Cullip
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Graphic Design
Description: Free Flo is a campaign that encourages an open conversation about menstruation, free from judgment. In an aim to remove the stigma and the view of menstruation as a taboo topic.

Name: Skye Williams
University/Course: Lancaster University, BA(Hons) Fine Art
Description:
Curisoty & Conversation'
This installation work takes on the form of interactive and participatory art as a means to spark curiosity and conversations. Childhood and play are the work's main focus', contemplating how creativity is often inhibited from an early age due to societal expectations of how children should behave. My installation of the television, an everyday household object, invites the public to interact with it through the mediums of drawing and writing, in a manner that would typically be disciplined in childhood; set up in a public area, passers-by were able to stop and consider each other's scrawls, taking inspiration from one another and forming unspoken conversations between each other. There is a sense of transformation that takes place through this; both the object into an artwork and the adult back into the child. This work encouraged the participants to explore their creativity, via the installation, which is all too often suppressed in adult life.

Name: Sasha Hare
University/Course: University of Plymouth, Documentary Photography
Description:
‘A Man After Midnight’ is an exploration of the chaotic rituals of Youth in the UK party scene; focussing on the infatuating and subconscious sensory experiences they have in order to let go. 

Today, the project has responded to a narrative of isolation and distortion; here the venues are closed, the innate need to party carries on.

Name: James Lloyd
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: I created a publication housing an interview with Cosmic Disco pioneer, Daniele Baldelli. Along with the graphic design of the book I created supporting artwork to exist alongside the text. Here is an alien-esque image which communicates the hush hush nature of one of the well known clubs, Cosmic, prior to it being shut down in 1984.

Name: Chris Stones
University/Course: University of Chester, BA Hons Fine Art
Description:
I find collage an exciting and expeditious medium in which to work. One of my most vivid childhood memories is of my mother, making flour and water paste, so I could collage chocolate biscuit wrappers. 

Recognising that my strengths lie in the analogue, collage enables me to take a playful and diverse approach to making work which is therefore eclectic, often conceptual. Influenced by Surrealism, Dada and Pop Art, I combine collage with elements of appropriated paintings and readymade objects. As I mature past the age of 50, I am acutely aware of the value of recycling and the satisfaction of giving a ‘thing’ a second life, a reflection perhaps of my own reinvention as a student.

Adjusting to life in lockdown in response to the Coronavirus pandemic, I am fortunate to be able to continue making work. These five second-hand wall hangings came from a reclamation company, and I suspect, originally from a restaurant or a hotel. In reality each board measures 141 cm wide x 26 cm high x 6 cm deep and they stack to form a combined work inspired by the Surrealist game of exquisite corpse.

I would welcome the opportunity to see the work reproduced larger than life on a billboard. Not just because Covid-19 has robbed us of our degree shows but because the location of said billboard would affect the reading of the work in interesting ways. For instance, outside the British Museum the work reads as a classical frieze, yet outside Harvey Nichols it reads more as a glossy fashion advert.

Name: Tanatchai Mukem
University/Course: I graduated from bachelor of technology from Rajamangala University of Technology Thanyaburi
Description: This Thesis studied about the production of Sci-Fi fantasy 3D animation “Lunoseum” (the story was adapted from aesop's fables, The Hare and The Tortoise )

Name: Reanne Brine
University/Course: Plymouth University, Graphic Communication.
Description: St Petrock's is a homeless charity based in Exeter. I created a new campaign for them to show the public how the charity help rough-sleepers to get back on their feet. The designs are inspired by Maslow's hierarchy of needs to offer a simplistic design that communicates to any audience. To accompany this trio of posters, I also created an animation. The video shows the blocks falling, showing the journey of homelessness, and then rebuilding again, showing how St Petrock's really make a difference.

Name: Henry
University/Course: brighton, illustration
Description: A stream of consciousness, that turned into what this piece became

Name: Violet Nys
University/Course: Sint Lucas School Of Arts Antwerp, master in visual arts in an applied context
Description:
in october of last year my grandmother had a stroke and suddenly suffered from aphasia. Aphasia is the inability to understand or produce speech, as a result of brain damage. With this project I made all sorts of games to activate the words she lost. 

This specific game/tool is to be made in different materials. The touch of the different structures and shapes activate a different sense than the 'normal' exercises in speech therapy. Senses can make someone remember something they did not know anymore. It has both abstract as recognizable shapes so you can compare them to one another, try to find out if they recognize the shapes and so on. 

There are exercises/questions prepared in a manual explaining how to use it, but you can work with it in your own way as well.

Name: Coralie Wells
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University, Graphic Design BA (Hons)
Description: Le Monde Café is a space to learn about different cultures, festivals, and languages. For this work, I created a multi-lingual 'Happy Families' to encourage language learning, as well as producing a book about World Festivals. I also created everything that a café might need; branding, mugs, plates, menu, decor, and much more.

Name: John Renhard
University/Course: Wolverhampton School of Art, BA (Hons) Fine Art.
Description:
My work plays with the idea of implied danger and the restrictions faced when trying to produce art under the ever watchful eye of the health and safety team.
This piece takes the often ignored,  hidden away and generally boring extension lead and turns it into not only an installation piece but also a threat to the very rules and regulations that tried to stop it from ever existing.

Name: Hannah Yates
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan University and Graphic Design
Description: Covid-19 massively impacted my final year and final projects. Instead of celebrating in Manchester I moved home and finished my degree there. I decided to alter one of my projects to focus on the effects of lockdown on my family and our routines.

Name: CHOSH
University/Course: University for the Creative Arts - Advertising
Description: A mockup print advert for Durex

Name: Becky Sidwell
University/Course: Staffordshire University
Description:
Gaia is a new sustainable typeface. Each character has a reduced amount of pixels (half the normal amount) therefore when printing, electricity and ink is being saved. The name Gaia derives from Dr James Lovelock. The Gaia theory deposits that the organic and inorganic components of plant earth have evolved as a sustainable system.

Gaia’s pixel amount is 50% smaller than a normal typeface. Therefore, the amount of electricity and ink is around 50% less too. With this in mind it means that each ink cartridge will last twice as long due to the reduced amount of ink being used.

Name: Alexandra Borghino
University/Course: Edinburgh College HND Illustration
Description: Children’s illustration-wildlife scenery

Name: Pippa Healy
University/Course: UAL Camberwell MA Printmaking
Description: This work was made during the first week of lockdown. You could hear and see crows everywhere. The streets became silent. I could not make work in the print studio at uni so I started to make work on my phone.

Name: Megan Fry
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: A range of products for a Lavender farm in North East Somerset. This project involved a rebrand which shifted their focus towards supporting rural communities by aiming to elevate loneliness throughout the UK. With their passion for Lavender, The Lavender Co.'s mission is to bring people together by sharing tips, projects/campaigns and workshops to help create the products. Each product tells a different story from those who helped make it due to its hand made and collaborative process.

Name: Xiao Niu
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA(Hons) Illustration
Description: This is an experimental piece inspired by a video game called 'NO THING'.

Name: Rithika Pandey
University/Course: Coleg sir gar ; BA (Hons) Painting, drawing & printmaking
Description: My work is about the surreality of displacement.  It explores the constant push and pull of intangible forces existing at the threshold of mental life and lived experiences through an interdisciplinary lens of inquiry.

Name: Alexandra Simmons
University/Course: Ravensbourne University London
Description: I was inspired by the formation of waves. I aimed to communicate qualities of the ocean through different printing process. The foil aims to capture the reflection of the sun and mimic the sea foam. Where as litho and scoring have been used to define the structure and the movements of the swell.

Name: Aimée Merola
University/Course: Camberwell College of Arts, Graphic Design
Description: This image, and the others which form a larger archive, captures time through the constant changing state of nature around us. As often looked past, the photograph and archive aims to document as much as possible the presence of flowers and other plants, to heighten their existence in our everyday lives.

Name: Tammy McBain
University/Course: Falmouth University, studying BA(Hons) Photography
Description:
Dance is beyond pure entertainment.
As someone who is unable to dance but has always had a fascination with the medium - and the way that it can make you feel - I wanted to find a way to involve myself with dance by incorporating it into my photography. I use long exposure to try to create an ethereal image which captures the movement of the performers but also brings a novel aspect to the photographic image itself, for both creator and viewer, evoking in the latter something of the emotion invested in the dance.

Name: Nigel Edwards
University/Course: Cardiff Met.
Description:
My work considers the beauty of the environment where I was raised, using clay bodies and mimetic glazes to convey the raw energy and dynamism of the coast. I have employed various techniques and involved different genres, exploring functional forms through the language of sculpture, to the development of glazes to encourage and engage with thoughts of rural coastlines and marine life. 
 	The result is a balance held between two forces, the power of the ocean and man’s relationship and impact on it through geometric and technical interventions.

Name: Jacobo Cobián Sánchez
University/Course: IED Madrid, Graphic Design
Description: My work is very conceptual. These posters are the same as humans. Are we equal? Are we different? Being different is not an equality? Are we the same?

Name: Rhiann Bull
University/Course: Solent Southampton University
Description: graphic structure; squares showcasing an argument

Name: Lydia Ahmed
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan University, Fine Art
Description: My exploration of art concerns the saturated nature of the image in the age of the internet and mass culture as well as questioning the divisions between high art and pop culture and the confines of gallery environments.

Name: Esther Blair
University/Course: Ulster University
Description: The significance of The Number 3' - A typographic publication, showcasing the significance of the No. 3, throughout all areas and aspects of our lives. The publication is made up of 9 (3x3=9) different observations about the No.3. All the design rationale, typographic, and print choices are built around the concept of the rule of 3, as the rule of 3 is a guideline which applies to the process of composing visual images and stunning designs.​​​​​​​

Name: Abi Wakeling and Rebecca Konteh
University/Course: University of Gloucestershire- BA Advertising
Description: With The North Face adventure route extension on Google Maps, explorers can find new adventures that are nearer than they think. If people use The North Face gear they are set up to adventure whenever and wherever. Adventure really is just around the corner.

Name: Ella Barrow
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, BA Fashion (Final year)
Description:
My FMP celebrates my family's roots by utilising only second-hand materials, alongside serving a reminder to look to the past and challenge our constant consumption of the new. My concept aimed to use no new materials when it began in October 2019, instead using purely found materials, a theme which I, and most fashion students, have had to commit to given the current circumstances. Yet, my FMP is fulfilling the message it set out to tell; that we should utilise the materials, objects and stories already available to us rather than contributing to society's overconsumption of everything.

The 'Bias Tablecloth Dress' (photographed) is the product of nine vintage tablecloths and low-waste pattern cutting. The colourful checks & patterns are an ode to the influence a travelling circus has on my family in the early 1900s. The materials' sun-faded hue combined with experimental, eco-conscious pattern cutting has resulted in a garment blurring the line between old and new.

Name: Shelley Niu
University/Course: Chelsea College of Art, Graphic Design Communication
Description:
What is maximum joy?
Joy is intangible and is different for each person, but when it comes to food, no one can say no to their favs. Every one has their favourite meal/snack/drink. So I asked people what their most memorable food was growing up. They answered. I art directed. And *bam* a most enjoyable memory, exaggerated.
The uploaded photograph is one out of a series of three.

Name: Jake Naparstek
University/Course: Ravensbourne University London, studying Graphic Design
Description:
Opportuni-TEA! aims to tackle unpaid internships, which affect many young people looking to get into creative industries. This project tackles the issue in a lighthearted way, by playing on the stereotype that the intern is only there to make the tea.

These boxes of tea would be sent to offices that were guilty of hiring unpaid interns. Through sarcastic comments on the box and teabags, the aim is to try and persuade and initiate change through somewhat playful means.

Name: Meghna Saji
University/Course: Coventry University, Ba Hons Graphic Design
Description:
They say dogs are a man's best friend, Waggo is an online food delivery brand that provides freshly cooked for your lovely canines. 
These tailor-made recipes come straight from nature and right into your beloved doggos bowl, serving up a bowl of happiness!

Name: Charlie
University/Course: Leeds Beckett
Description: Primary research into photography - how audience perception may be manipulated through art direction

Name: Kuang Mei Wen
University/Course: I will be graduating from University of Chester and I am studying Graphic Design
Description: My work is about my hometown, Sabah which is one of the states in Malaysia and a beautiful place rich of natural resources. I found only a few people know about it therefore, I decided to introduce Sabah to the public by creating a magazine. It is my final project and I will be presenting it in my university degree show.

Name: Emma Hannaway
University/Course: Norwich University, Graphic Design
Description: Rebranding Old Spice to celebrate the beauty in ageing. Proving that ageing doesn't mean loosing the spirit of youth at all.

Name: Chloe Newman
University/Course: University for the Creative Arts, Fashion Design BA (Hons)
Description: My concept is inspired by the series and real life events of the Chernobyl nuclear disaster, that occurred in 1986.

Name: Megan Didcock
University/Course: University of Brighton
Description: This piece celebrates the life of my late aunt. Ive drawn on the significance that subculture had on her life in the 1970s to create this mixed media, leather tapestry.

Name: Laura Spence
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Graphic Design
Description: Pause is a mural design to evoke joy. I wanted to use bright  colour and eye-catching illustrations to create something unique that not only looks good, but servers a greater purpose too.  It is proven by researchers that exposure to bright colours can boost mood, mental clarity and stress levels. This mural aims to add vibrancy too dull, urban areas whilst emitting joy to passersby.

Name: Balázs Hirth
University/Course: Edinburgh College / HND Graphic Design
Description: It is a logo & branding design project for an interior decor blog, called Crisp Décor. The blog focusing mainly on recently released minimal home décor products. The goal is to inspire anyone interested in interior design or planning to redecorate there home. This brief was selected from a 30 days daily logo design challenge, that I completed not a long time ago.

Name: Grace Crossley
University/Course: University of the arts London
Description: My piece is a monoprint made form memory of my baking process. Featuring loose and emotive line work the piece is a reflection of my memory.

Name: Alessandro Castorino
University/Course: University of Arts London, Graphic Design
Description: This the identity I developed for my first Service Design project. The purpose of this service was to allow creative users and students to have their projects developed in a safe environment that remained open even during extraordinary conditions, such as the Covid-19 outbreak.

Name: Isobel Edwards
University/Course: University of Brighton with BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: My work depicts my feelings  of  being overwhelmed and trapped living in a city during isolation. This piece is part of a body of work called "That time when all I did was Knit" which tracks my journey of compulsive knitting and crying and attempts to show a bright world I created for myself to counteract the dark one outside.

Name: Leonie Kaltenegger
University/Course: Information Design, University of Applied Sciences Graz
Description:
The discipline of visual communication, similar to many others, underlies a great deal of pressure, as it involves a high need for surprising, unconventional ideas: creative solutions. ‚A Shift in Perspective: An Investigation into Creativity from Constraint’ examines not only whether or how one can influence creativity but also whether constraints can promote the creative process. Furthermore, since creation is often associated with freedom, this thesis intends to change how the creative process is perceived.
While several psychologists and philosophers have widely studied creativity, much uncertainty regarding the correlation between creativity and constraint still exists. Divided into two parts, the thesis addresses the framework behind creativity from theoretical and empirical perspectives. The project shown is one result of the 6-month study about creativity and constraint.

Name: Alice Pool
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art, Sculpture and Enviromental Art
Description: These images are stills from an animation I have made. Recently I have been digitally creating memories, and then presenting them in the virtual realm. Memories, like dreams, only exist as visual traces in the individual’s conscious minds. The rendered images are a way of adding to the memory, recording it and sharing it. I want the work to show that people’s memories have value and the things that stick in your mind may be stuck for a reason.

Name: Giorgia Ziliani
University/Course: University of the Arts London from Fashion Styling and Production
Description: My work aims to explore the human body in its ominous form, through a series of visual distortions that will guide the viewer to discover distressing feelings.

Name: Amani Ridd
University/Course: Exeter College (Plymouth University partner) - Graphic Communication
Description: This is a re-brand of Shaul's Bakery. The bakery was established in 1961 by my great uncle. I felt that the brand was in need of an update to compete with the current market, so I took inspiration from 60s graphic design. Whilst my branding has a modern look, there are elements such as the colours and repeat patterns that refer to the company origin.

Name: Daniella Devita
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam
Description: The work is for a festival that helps to educate about censorship, get censored speakers to find their audience and a place for people to speak freely and be a community. It also thrives to use our western societal privilege to help give people from countries who could be killed for speaking their truth.

Name: Larna Pantrey-Mayer
University/Course: University of Brighton
Description:
The work explores a connection of text and imagery  and subjectivity. 

Using the dreams of selected women of the 1930s, who participated in a Mass Observation dream study, alongside found portraits of women, I created digital collages of symbolic imagery within the dream or the portrait sitter’s life.

I researched each woman and paired them with someone who had similarities. The intention was for each woman to help the other regain their subjectivity – to give a voice to the face and a face to the voice. 

The orchids are used as a symbol of hybridity and beauty.

Name: Callan Norton
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts
Description: This image is part of a series of images which explore fashion in a post apocalyptic future.

Name: Hannah Rendell + Lara Hallam
University/Course: University of Lincoln, BA (Hons) Creative Advertising
Description: This piece was a tactical ad for Lastminute.com for holiday goers at Christmas time. We did a take on the Christmas story, having the overall message of "There's always room at the inn".

Name: Nella Piatek
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art, Product Design
Description: This project draws attention to how our environment influences our behavioural habits and makes a statement that wellbeing and future thinking should no longer be a luxury. This speculative system is placed in a preferable future where an area between the urban and the rural becomes a 'Sustainable Belt' and is dedicated to educating the population on how to live with the health of all of Earth’s occupants in mind. By designing this ultimate self-sufficient sustainable habitat and creating a government-funded organisation that would give each citizen the chance to devote a stage of their lifetime to the Sustainable Belt, this project aims to shows how an environmentally conscious mindset could spread across society.

Name: Inga Hamilton
University/Course: Ulster University. Ceramics, Jewellery & Silversmithing.
Description: Through the use of readily-dismissed, low-value natural materials, such as seaweed and salt, I endeavour to produce desirable, high-value, wearable adornment. By instigating comparative discussion around my work with that of non-human-animal makers employing the same materials and techniques, such as decorator crabs or dolphins, I hope to challenge the viewer’s concepts of value and adornment within the natural world.

Name: Billy Spendlove
University/Course: WSA - University of Southampton. BA Games Design and Art
Description: Portage is a minimalist experience that encourages a mindful attitude whilst canoeing and hiking through the landscape. We are a team of 3 game design students developing a game that we want to invoke a particular experience within the players.

Name: Oliver Potter
University/Course: Falmouth University, Graphic Design
Description: This was part of my submission to the Bulletproof Fresh Meat competition. It's a whiskey brand inspired by the Gold Rush. Instead of a glass bottle, the whiskey has been packaged into a kerosene can. This is the same can that would of been used to hold oil,  used to fuel gas lanterns when mining for gold.

Name: EvinLiu
University/Course: The university of edinburgh illustration
Description: The reflection of inner world during self isolation

Name: Hamish Symonds
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan
Description:
I create functional pottery, drawing inspiration from Devonshire slipware traditions. I limit myself, as far as I can, to the same materials that would have been used 200 years ago, connecting my colour palette to the geology of Britain. Pictured here is a tea-set decorated with gestural mark making, finished with a traditional honey glaze, that I hope imbues a sense of autumnal warmth people will want to welcome into their homes.

This push and pull between committing myself to traditional working methods yet trying to create work that holds more modern aesthetic sensibilities and works on its own terms is something I often reflect upon in my making.

Name: Danielle Blackledge
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan University: Graphic Design
Description: FlipSide is more than a virtual degree show. We aim to celebrate third year graphic design students from Manchester School of Art whilst  encouraging positive change within the creative industry through a series of podcasts, workshops and live talks. We hope to make a difference and educate our online visitors on themes such as diversity within the design community and the responsibilities we have as designers.

Name: Lauren Bradley
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University BA Hons Illustration
Description: I have created illustrated responses to feminine social issues like FGM, period poverty and Chhaupadi, intended to be printed onto underwear to sell. I chose underwear as it is one of the most economical and therefore environmentally friendly items of clothing and it ties into the topics I am approaching. A portion of profits would go towards helping communities via charities like The Pad Project and ActionAid.

Name: Courtney Cato
University/Course: Cambridge School of Visual and Performing Arts
Description: We all get lost in something we can't control, but for some, it's our outlet, our way to flourish through the negative.

Name: Brad
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh product design
Description: YouPod is an autonomous vehicle transport system, that allows users to change their emotions, or express them. It does this through light colour and movement, sound and haptic feedback. It also features something called adaptive speed which uses GPS and accelerometers to make the users feel like they are travelling faster or slower.

Name: Hazel Howat
University/Course: University of Strathclyde, BSc Product Design and Innovation
Description:
“Restoring elderly adults’ confidence in their balance.”

My final year project focused on the design of an at-home balance-improving solution to help adults aged 65+ overcome the fear of falling. This is a large health problem, experienced by 50% of community dwelling elderly, and can cause many to unnecessarily restrict their daily activity; this in turn can lead to a range of physical and psychological adverse health implications.

Tilt has been designed to help long-term balance improvement be more achievable and attainable. It comprises of two products which work in harmony with one another – the user practices their balance exercises by standing on pressure-sensitive foot soles; this data is sent to a speaker which gives live feedback to the user, telling them how to improve their balance and redistribute their weight. The emotive voice and personified wobbling movement of the speaker is intended to make the interaction engaging and stimulating; the goal is that it will make their practice enjoyable and increase the likelihood of the activity being integrated into their daily routine. With its consistent use, the solution has the potential to improve leaning balance, build self-confidence and contribute towards an increased quality of life.

Name: Joanna Penney
University/Course: University of Ulster
Description:
When Youth and I Lived Together

As I get older, I forget that everyone around me is ageing alongside me. I was jolted into
reality by my aging father and the life changing event that occurred to him. When Youth and
I Lived Together examines the impact of my father’s forced retirement on him but also on
my family.

In early 2001, my father was diagnosed with fibromyalgia and was prescribed strong
medication to manage the pain of the condition. Over the past 19 years, the medication’s
effectiveness has subsided to the point that my father was not able to work any longer due
to excruciating pain.

To document this change, I capture the evidence of changes within the household and the
gaps that aging presents to my entire family. These gaps come in the form of the negative
financial impact of the loss of income as well as the emotional effects of losing the ability to
work. I am also looking at the domestic space which is now filled with someone who was
absent while working most of his life. This added figure, who is now constant within the
domestic setting changes the balance significantly. While this is an autobiographical story
about my family, ageing and the feeling of being isolated when becoming retired is a
universal reality that touches everyone.

Name: Hugo Starns, Mitchell Barton
University/Course: University of Lincoln, Creative Advertising
Description:
The Brief - Increase subscriptions to LinkedIN Premium
The Idea - Find the best candidate for the job with LinkedIN Premium

Name: Rory Cowan
University/Course: Loughborough University, Graphic Communication and Illustration
Description:
The beer designed for designers.
When you hit a creative block, it can leave you frustrated, overwhelmed and in need of a breakthrough.
Breakthrough is a beer to jumpstart your creativity - alcohol has been proven to help with creative problem-solving and so we have grasped that bull by the horns.
Use the bottle top to scratch off the label whilst you drink, taking your eyes away from your work for a moment and allowing your mind to recharge for a real breakthrough.

Name: Hugo Starns, Mitchell Barton
University/Course: University of Lincoln, Creative Advertising
Description:
The Brief - Increase Pipers sales.
The Idea - Pipers goes above and beyond to find the best flavour.

Name: Jazz Holwill
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts. Graphic Design
Description: Outcider is an alcohol brand based on the town of Newmarket, which is considered the birthplace and global centre of thoroughbred horse racing.
Website: I can send a full portfolio

Name: Luke Wilding
University/Course: University of Brighton, BA Graphic Design
Description: This work represents the covering of identity, being able to make someone anonymous simply through covering up their features through a mixture of analog and digital processes.

Name: Gvidas Pakarklis
University/Course: Falmouth University, Illustration (BA)
Description:
The illustration is a personal interpretation of the essay 'Striptease', taken from the book 'Mythologies', written by Roland Barthes. 
The image was printed using a risograph together with the essay on the other side of the page.

Name: Josh Dallolio
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University,  Artist Designer: maker
Description:
Distortion, the Organic World 
‘Distortion, the organic world’ is a series of sculptural furniture pieces for contemporary domestic interiors. The pieces were designed by merging the inherent beauty of the organic world with geometric forms. Here, natural structures are distorted and seemingly absorbed by the functionality of geometric shapes.  While radically simplifying the natural form, it also mimics the contours found in the organic object.  
 This project aims to unite and blur the lines between formalist sculpture and functional design, bringing schematic visual language from two separate genres together to create domestic sculptural objects.  
 Similarly, the production process merges the realms of digital and physical, as well as traditional and contemporary making and manufacturing processes.  This collection brings together digital fabrication processes such as 3d scanning, computer aided design, digital manipulation and CNC router cutting with traditional wood working joinery techniques.

Name: Hugo Starns, Mitchell Barton
University/Course: University of Lincoln, Creative Advertising
Description:
The Brief - Encourage people to sign up to Rosetta Stone
The Idea - Learn the language, not just the words

Name: Imogen Hawgood
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts- Illustration
Description: This gouache painting is part of a collection of work exploring the idealised American Dream of the 1960s and the allure of the West; ideas which are embodied by the city of Los Angeles. My work seeks to break down the façade of beauty and Hollywood glamour to reveal a grittier undertone that quietly consumes the city of Angels. This image is based on my own experiences of a rainstorm on Venice Beach which offered an unusual view of Los Angeles revealing a very different reality to the picture-perfect dream of LA. Film style light leaks are used to further the incongruency and distortion of the composition.

Name: Alice Smith
University/Course: University of Brighton and Graphic Design BA Hons
Description: This poster is part of a campaign which aims to give insight into female genital mutilation (FGM), a controversial tradition, that affects girls and women all over the world. The intention of the campaign is to empower girls and women, to show support and to give the affected individuals a voice.

Name: Meredith Mason
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan School of Art and Design: Artist Designer:Maker
Description: My practice focuses on hand built ceramic sculptures that are uniquely different and personal to my sensory relationship with the process and materiality. Each hand-built abstract sculpture is unique and exclusive as no two are the same, celebrating the imperfections. There is an element of personification in each form as they appear to grow and shows movement through the branches and roots, inviting individuals in as a tactile sculpture.

Name: Hugo Starns, Mitchell Barton
University/Course: University of Lincoln, Creative Advertising
Description:
The Brief - Increase sales of Rimmel waterproof mascara. 
Idea - So waterproof it 'repels'.

Name: Hannah Ford
University/Course: York St John University- Graphic Design
Description: This competition project was held by York St John University to design a cover for the Beyond the Walls anthology. My entry explores the themes of contemporary change and personal development, which is further demonstrated by the collection of poems in the book.

Name: Gregory FitzeHorswell
University/Course: Falmouth University, Graphic Design
Description: Identity is a book about, well, identity. It is a photographic exploration into how people choose to be portrayed in photographs

Name: Harvey Jones
University/Course: Bath Spa University, Graphic Communications
Description: This was part of a live brief were I had to create a logo and album cover for a music artist called SÅKÅ. The two donut shapes are based on the original logo where to the two accents above the "Å" are a pastel blue and pink as the artist wanted these colours to appear as a form of his identity. I played on the idea that these two accents make up the brands identity and so created 3D forms of these on MeshMixer, then editing them in photoshop to become the image you see now.

Name: Niamh Magee
University/Course: Ulster University studying Photography with Video
Description: My work explores the psychological factors and impact a space can have on the way we feel through colour, light, shape and pattern.

Name: Molly Overstall Khan
University/Course: Illustration at the University of Brighton
Description: I aim to make nostalgic, humorous and dreamy imagery. This photograph is from a book of self portraits, focussed on styling and displaying the benefits of staying inside.

Name: Jessica Ghil
University/Course: Graphics & Illustration
Description: Visualisation of sound

Name: Megan Slade
University/Course: University of Brighton, Graphic Design
Description: "What makes you feel like a Bad Bitch?" I have created a film based campaign that uplifts, inspires and connects womxn. The campaign is now an online platform too; @bad.b.tch_ on Instagram.

Name: Laura Spence
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Graphic Design
Description: An info-graphic inspired illustrated campaign, highlighting HSBC's brand promise 'Together We Thrive' and depicting communities that have thrived through HSBCs sponsorship. The designs rely heavily on a grid structure, influenced by HSBC's role in networking, which HSBC lies central too.

Name: Nikki Nikolaeva
University/Course: BA Illustration, Falmouth University
