Description: This illustration is the second image in a series of three, inspired by  the Greek myth of the abdication of the Persephone, the goddess of vegetation by the god of the dead and the king of the underworld - Hades. In this image, the abducted goddess is about to make the decision of eating the pomegranate seeds, offered to her by Hades, that will break her bound with the living world forever.

Name: Ethan Powell
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan Univeristy
Description: My work aims to inspire contemplation. I use locally gathered materials in my glazes and draw abstract landscapes on my pots.

Name: Bart D'Angelo
University/Course: Falmouth University, BA Illustration
Description: One from a series of illustrations for Cameron Robert’s new novella License to Desire soon published both in physical and Ebook format. The story is like walking into a dark familiar room, everything feels recognized yet disorientating and obscure.

Name: Ffion Morgan
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University
Description:
‘Palms off my Palm Oil’ is an educational campaign that highlights the devastating effects associated with palm oil production in Indonesia, in particular Borneo and Sumatra.  
Together with neighbouring Malaysia, Indonesia supplies over 85% of the world’s palm oil, which is the main cause of deforestation in these areas, destroying habitats of many critically endangered species. It has been estimated that if deforestation continues at its current rate, the Indonesian rainforests will be gone by 2022. 
My main aim is to educate children and parents on this subject, as this issue will only become more urgent for this generation. I have incorporated bright and bold colours, interesting characters and interactive elements to encourage curiosity and learning in a fun and visually engaging way. Hopefully, getting the message across to children will encourage them to ask questions of their parents and teachers, which in turn will help spread the message more widely.

Name: Helen Trevaskis
University/Course: Falmouth
Description: Humans are a part of the physical world and yet we have developed a peculiar capacity to feel separate and apart, as if looking at ourselves looking out onto into a strange land. This  denial of how deeply we are embedded in the wider landscape creates dissonance with and disconnection from our sense of self.

Name: Lili Cox
University/Course: Manchester School of Art, Graphic Design
Description:
Response to @flipside.mcr brief 'What Does FlipSide Mean To You?'
FlipSide to me is curiosity: to question all as a designer, to deconstruct and define all that is around me.

Name: Neav Ingram
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University
Description: This is a spread from my ISTD submission on the theme of Migration. It was a personal project about Migrating from my father's family to my step father's family, following my father's death. The book is split into two parts, the first part is all about my life, through my childhood and having to deal with grief. The second part begins with meeting my stepfather and my thought process of whether I should change my name to my step father's or not.

Name: Jennifer Lynch
University/Course: Ulster University, Belfast School of Art  BA Hons in Textile Art Design and Fashion and Placement
Description:
I am an Embroidery Textile Designer/Sampler that specializes in creating bespoke designs with structural and abstract elements suitable for high-end interiors and/or industrial spaces. 

I have always been fascinated in finding patterns within the shapes and structures found in urban landscapes and in everyday life which I then capture through the lens of my camera, searching for the finer details that others may disregard. To creating both simple and complex designs, with a diverse range of ideas making each piece unique with a personal touch.

Name: Claudia Melton
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University, Illustration & Animation
Description: Nowt Queer As Folk is an animated short about a northern family being documented, and a cameraman struggling to break through. It explores being an outsider, and fearing judgement from outsiders.

Name: Ellie Neal
University/Course: Brighton University
Description: My work often experiments with the engagement of  society, trying to encourage interactions through physical experiences. This project sought question the colourless passivity of digital activism whereby I created a series of calico banners using online jargon, this particular piece stated a subtle message "CLICK THIS LINK" lacking visibility due to materiality being calico on calico. A comment on the low impact of online activism.

Name: Emma Cook
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University - Interior Architecture and Design
Description: WAKAGAERI, is a gesamtkunstwerk of architecture, nature and the art of movement; all the while producing a spatial journey to promote the work of local artists.

Name: Hattie May
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, Ba (hons) Interior Architecture & Design
Description: A sustainable gin bar & distillery experience, situated Inside the National Trust, to encourage the millennial generation to visit the parks across the country. In this space, Copper pipe work connects the bar to the adjacent gin distillery, creating a unique inclusive drinking experience.

Name: Olivia McEwan-Hill
University/Course: Leeds Arts University, BA Hons Illustration
Description: This image comes from a collection of work exploring the use of narrative through symbol, colour and pattern. Lots of my research for this project explored the importance of folklore and fables in creating culturally rich experiences through story telling; promoting a sense of community and an intrinsic connection with the Earth.

Name: Jasmine Forbes
University/Course: Leeds Beckett university, Graphic Arts and Design
Description:
I use systems of objects to make pictures and
type. This is The Four Horsemen Of The Apocalypse using watch parts.

Name: Jody Woodhouse
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan University
Description: I have been producing a series of spreads for a children's picture book based on Manchester Museum and their Entomology Collection. This spread shows a scene where an Atlas beetle ventures into the vivarium, and comes across some of the creatures inside. Producing picture books is a dream career of mine, and I love creating engaging visuals for audiences of all ages to enjoy.

Name: Kirsty McKinlay
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Communication
Description: Inspired by the phrase ‘talk dirty to me’, the Durex campaign #talkdisabilitytome was created. Playing with provocative language, Durex aims to talk about the stigma around disability and sex with attitude, using dirty talk to catch eyes and provoke the minds of society.

Name: Callum O'Neill
University/Course: University of Dundee (DJCAD)
Description: Lingua has been my passion project since August after taking the opportunity of an Erasmus in Wrocław. Coming from the word ‘tongue’ and ‘language’ in Latin, Lingua confronts the issue that 80% of us can only communicate in one language in the UK and Ireland. In a playful and social spirit, the brand encourages a more open attitude to the public surrounding foreign languages with use of bold colours and an adaptable and diverse graphic language. Bringing a lively alternative to language learning rather than another app.

Name: Bethan Gorvett
University/Course: Brighton university - illustration and visual communication
Description: My explores a fantasy jungle world portraying peculiar creatures and interactions. Created for a university project around branding and designs for a tobacco rolling paper brand.
Website: I do not have a public link as of yet however would be happy to send a portfolio pdf over if requested
Instagram: beffy_g (however my Instagram is currently being improved)

Name: Julia Azureen
University/Course: Goldsmiths, University of London. Media, Communication and Cultural Studies - Animation
Description: This is a still from an animated my short-film, 'Atuk' (Malay for 'grandfather'). It touches on the life my grandfather had as a tailor, cook, as well as a family man and how my perspective of him changed as I grew older. As a kid, I was unable to fully comprehend what was actually going on in my family.

Name: Fingas Art
University/Course: BA Fine Art Brighton Metropolitan college
Description: Work based on nature our use of natural minerals, Ecology

Name: Jaisy Davies
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University
Description: This brief is set to create a modern, sustainable and feasible way of living that will adhere with the currently eco-nominal challenges facing the world such as global warming. These spaces must fit a range of lifestyles and be shown to ‘last a lifetime’. They must include all of the modern comforts that as people we are used to in the 21st Century, but not allow this to be the focus, also adaptable modern homes to fit the ageing population.

Name: Brandon Jones
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, BSc Product Design
Description: My project is working towards re-designing the conventional compression sleeve used to treat varicose veins. My product incorporates a hot and cold treatment to help the blood flow through the veins in any environment. The product also slides on easily and tightens easily due to the use of the BOA lace systems

Name: Hannah Peachey-Thacker
University/Course: University of Brighton, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description: The Morbid Urge to Gaze, an exploration of voyeurism through an un-gendered gaze.

Name: Patryk Fingas
University/Course: BA Fine Art Brighton Metropolitan College
Description: My work embraces the importance of natural minerals, ecology and natural environment

Name: Harry Warman
University/Course: Kingston University, Graphic Design
Description: Inflatable London is a project that aims to put wasted roofspaces to good use. By using the hot air expelled from rooftop airconditioning units, fabric windsocks become giant inflatable wayfinding for the capital. From directions to the circle line to where to find your nearest pharmacy, this project aims to revolutionize how we navigate the city.

Name: Bill Hards
University/Course: University for the Creative Arts
Description: Screen printed typographic poster – communicating the positives of AI in our lives.

Name: Alicia Portillo Vazquez
University/Course: Heriot-Watt University, BA Fashion Communication
Description: My work explores contemporary culture and the society we live in. I have explored male stereotypes where I have questioned the traditions of the transition from boy to man and if they are and if they should still be relevant in our changing society today. My project aim was to change the traditional outlook of what a man can be.

Name: Mackenzie Hall
University/Course: Camberwell College of Arts
Description: This illustration was created for a record sleeve competition entry for Secret 7" for the track 'Come Over' by The Internet. ‘Come Over’ is a track that has this great underlying sense of softness and feeling of wanting to be with someone without expectations. Inspired by this feeling, I wanted these characters, cat and dog (“puppy love”), to take up space, wind round each other and embrace in a way that was warm, balanced and gentle.

Name: Giovanna Scozzari
University/Course: Kingston School of Art
Description:
LOOM~
A weaving craft device that you can attach to the back of your phone so that you can have a phone-detox without going cold turkey.
Thanks to this craft, you can still use your phone- but not the screen.

Name: Charlotte Carter
University/Course: Wolverhampton University and Fashion and Textiles
Description: My work is all about designing vibrant pieces that could be used for bar/nightclub interior. Creating designs that look fresh but unique. The sort of thing that makes people look and wonder how it was made. The whole purpose to  this  Distorted Lights collection.

Name: Chloe Hunt
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Artist Designer: Maker
Description:
‘An Exploration of Geometric Forms’ begins its journey with a series of cylindrical vessels. Through a series of deconstruction and reconstruction I have explored the formal potentials of a simple thrown cylinder. Using cut lines to reveal and transform negative space and exterior form, while additions can create an intersect between planes and volumes. 

The series has been informed by various influencing factors, these include: Architecture, Suprematism, Constructivism, Concrete Art and Formalism. These objects aim to convey the formal values of these influences, albeit in an accessible domestic scale.
 
The series is made up of wheel thrown, unglazed Ash White Stoneware.

Name: Esther Peacey
University/Course: University of Chester
Description: I have always been passionate about trying to reduce plastic waste, which is what led me to my final project. I have created a manufacturing process where carrier bags can be repurposed into a valuable material. The material can be used for numerous applications, from home furnishings to being used in different industrial sectors, for example the catering industry.

Name: Freya Harvey
University/Course: Falmouth University - Graphic Design
Description: Penguin Pick Up Lines is an online service that aims to heighten the reading experience by removing covers, reviews and trends; instead providing the first lines of books. It allows readers to discover the writing that they connect with, and fall in love with something new and unexpected.

Name: Emil Dibble-Chwistek
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description: European colonialism of the Sahara desert forced the Tuareg people to change their culture and daily lives, resulting in oppression and resource exploitation. After fighting many rebellions they channelled their frustration and suffering through a different form of rebellion - music. Trading a rifle for a guitar, they create poetry of resistance.

Name: Bianca Winberg
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art, BA (Hons) Communication Design, specialism Graphic Design
Description: Templeton is an uppercase-only typeface inspired by Glasgow’s historical past in carpet design. The main source of inspiration is the ‘T’ which can be seen in the company Templeton’s old logo and the Arts and Crafts movement. It is a new take on a Glaswegian typeface, with sharp edges and decorative swashes.

Name: Anna Lura
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description: It's a poster set from a self initiated project called the ugly exhibition which explores the concept of ugly design. This is explored visually through abstract and experimental illustrations in order to convey a deeper meaning.

Name: Alex Douglas
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan university, Product Design
Description: As flights get longer and longer, the age old problem of sleeping sat upright in an economy class seat remains. This project looked at combining noise cancelling headphones and an eye mask to help passengers at the back of the plane get better quality sleep

Name: Charlie Wallace
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description:
Problem: Ambrosia has become a forgotten brand. A carton of the custard seems to be in everyone’s kitchen cupboard, but the love for the brand by families has become absent.  

Insight: Ambrosia custard reminds you of home and makes you feel warm and fuzzy inside.

Solution: We want to remind people of how custard makes you feel and bring those feelings back into their lives.

Name: Becky Hollis
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art, MFA Performance Costume
Description: Mary’s costume for my interpretation of ‘Mary Queen of Scots Got Her Head Chopped Off’ by Liz Lochhead. Written in 1987 and examining its titular figure, the play encourages a cross-examination of our past and present. I chose to combine two distinct time periods; 16th century and 1980s. Here, the 16th-century gown and 80s shell suit are combined.

Name: Claire Mills
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University
Description: This piece is a page from my illustrated children's story 'Uma'. Made through a combination of child's toys and colourfully lit silhouettes.

Name: Rachel Grosova
University/Course: Edinburgh College, HND Computer Arts & Design
Description: This piece is a part of an environmental propaganda series inspired by young innovators, such as Boyan Slat, Felix Finkbeiner or Hannah Herbst. The goal was to create a series informative of the innovators' achievements, visually influenced by modern and war propaganda.

Name: Connor Parker
University/Course: University of Central Lancashire, BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: This image is a part of my personal project module, where I have decided to create a booklet that shows prospective students what university is like. Through illustrations such as this, you can imagine the kinds of scenarios that may occur through your time at university and it will hopefully inspire more people to not just go to uni, but to experience it.

Name: Holly
University/Course: University for the Creative Arts, Graphic Design
Description: For my designed dissertation I wrote about the responsibility that the wealthy have when it comes to tackling climate change. Capitalism was a key theme in this however I decided to zoom in on the role of celebrities. This particular piece was designed for the merchandise of a campaign idea I developed on how celebrities can use their privilege for better - the merchandise comes alongside a “privilege pack” which educates them on what makes them privileged and offers suggestions of how they can use it. This idea stemmed from influencer culture we see on Instagram.

Name: Eleanor Wass
University/Course: Leeds Beckett, Graphic Arts and Design
Description: An exploration into abstract macro photography. This piece is focusing on the organic movements of ink.

Name: Sophie
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University and Interior Architecture and Design
Description: The project brief is named Reimagined, and is about bringing Gen Z into national trust sites. Using an existing, disused paddocks house, I have formed a creative co working space with an artist in residence, a workshop space for  visitors and a gallery space. There are then private and public areas of the site that allow artists to be in their own studio whilst allowing for visitors to peek a glimpse while they work. The backdrop of this site is beautiful woodland and trees so the artists are able to be freely inspired by their surroundings. Heavy and light spaces are conveyed through materiality which then link to the public and private ethos.

Name: Lauren Churchill
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan
Description: My work is about the empowerment of women, the exhibiting and painting of the female form from the perspective of another woman who is attracted to women.

Name: Jack Fitzhugh
University/Course: Uclan, Illustration
Description: It is a poster for the children’s picture book I have been working on as part of my two final projects on the course.

Name: Becca Fuller
University/Course: Leeds Art University Graphic Design
Description:
This campaign is based on instructions that demonstrate how to perform surgeries 
demonstrating a low budget option of healthcare if it was to become privatised. Styled as IKEA instructions as IKEA is the low budget of furniture. These instructions are supported by posters which explains how you can stop the instructions becoming a reality.

Name: Nia Jacobs
University/Course: I studied BA Photography at Canterbury Christ Church University
Description: I was interested in photographing the human traces that had been left behind within a private setting; along the way, the project became a cross over with the current coronavirus pandemic and it soon became about living everyday life in lockdown.

Name: Dion Thomas
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, Illustration
Description: This image is a response to an article by Digital Journal, "Does City Life Affect Mental Health?".

Name: Menuka De Silva
University/Course: Shillington Design School, studying Graphic Design
Description:
Colourism is bias against darker skin individuals, particularly within their own communities. It’s noticeable in South Asian communities, as well as others, that fairer skin is seen as something to be desired and valued over darker tones.
The use of unamused animals and curated statements in this awareness campaign aim to highlight just how ridiculous this is.

Name: Anisha Rapal
University/Course: Goldsmiths, University of London. Studied BA Media & Communications
Description: “Wakeful Dreaming” consists of a series of images, which blur the lines between fantasy and reality. Tapping into hypnagogic experiences, the series questions ones understanding of warehouse spaces at night. Why are we not willing to question this reality we seem to accept?

Name: Loren Puopolo
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University, School of Art and Design / Ba(Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Cope is supplying workplaces, schools, colleges and universities in the UK with a mental health coping mechanisms care package. Which everyone will easily have access to this resource which will PREVENT, HELP AND RECOVER mental illness conditions including depression, anxiety and stress. Also providing an easy access offline app that anyone can use which will reach people in all different areas of life and situations to cater for all.

Name: Jordan Matthews
University/Course: Ravensbourne - BA (hons) Graphic Design
Description: Online Catfish - I have manipulated imagery to distort peoples true identity, similar to the acts of a catfish. They hide who they really are and pretend to be someone they are not. The type is also concealed, revealing only what people want them to see.

Name: Thomas McElroy
University/Course: Birmingham City University
Description:
This is a colour swatch saved from an interactive colour picker tool developed in Processing. The tool combines colour and a tone generator making the colour picking process more engaging. 

The idea came from the understanding that colour and sound can effect a persons mood.

Name: Ailish Beadle
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts - Illustration
Description: I created an alphabet with 3 constraints (same colours, isometric drawing and to tell a story about the character). I had to do one letter a day throughout March which was challenging to come up with new ideas so quickly.

Name: Olivia Hardman
University/Course: Manchester Metropolitan
Description: Dog conference call on Zoom

Name: Euphemia Franklin
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description: Playful Kimono asks, what would you kimono look like? Using a simple template, everyone is invited to design their unique kimono and be featured on the @playfyl_kimono Instagram feed.

Name: Isobel Thomas
University/Course: University of Plymouth, Graphic Communication with Typography
Description: This project is a rebrand of the Faroe Islands. It focuses on their self sufficiency and traditional craft, encouraging a unique form of 'craft tourism' to the Islands.

Name: Phoebe Martin
University/Course: Falmouth University. BA(Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Creating an alcohol brand with a unique sense of place. I chose Nunney Village as my location and Nunney Castle as my anchor for the project. The alcohol brand consists of a line of 4 ciders, each cider telling a key story about Nunney Castle.

Name: Lucy Rushton
University/Course: Ravensbourne University London
Description:
“Snakes & Career Ladders - play the game and see if YOU can be a successful working mother!”

By the time their first child has turned 20, working mothers earn on average 30% less than fathers with the same level of education.

A satirical board game, which aims to shed light on the issues working mothers have to face when juggling a career and family life.

Name: Anastasia Beedham
University/Course: Ravensbourne University, BA Graphic Design
Description: Ditch The Free Pitch: Explores the negativity surrounding free pitching in the design industry. It consists of a box containing an information booklet, stickers and a scratch card asking 'Do you want to win a free pitch?', the catch is that you can never win.

Name: Raquel Soares Freitas
University/Course: BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Line x Time explores individuals thought processes with time constraints using dotted grids and pens.

Name: Tania Afonso Pereira
University/Course: Ravensbourne University - Graphic Design Ba (Hons)
Description: The design is inspired by Waldo Nell's microscopic peacock feathers photography and the opening and closing movement of peacock feathers, using layering and repetition of Colorplan paper in Tabriz Blue and Forest to showcase the way a simple three-dimensional paper object can open into a complex symmetrical shape. Demonstrating careful consideration of dimensionality and how the piece will look once open, the design incorporates gold foil blocking through the middle of the design to highlight detailed areas and add gravity
Website: currently making a website portfolio - not finsihed yet would be happy to share it at a later stage

Name: Izzy Copley
University/Course: Shillington College of Graphic Design, Graphic Design
Description:
Around the world adults and teenagers are
becoming more aware of the negative effects
excessive amounts of technology can have on
our physical and mental health. Despite this,
parents are still resorting to technology as a
means of occupying their children when times
are difficult. The Digital Detots campaign is
designed to be a fun way of reminding parents that children also need to switch off sometimes and relax.

Name: Mim Chadwick
University/Course: Shillington College - Graphic Design
Description: Promotional material created for the album Psychodrama by Dave. The album covers a variety of heavyweight topics including gang violence, mental health, domestic abuse and racial inequality. This hand-made project portrays some of the social problems faced by a lot of young people - mainly men - today. The hand-stitched newspaper headlines cover the faces of the boys on the album cover and symbolise the lack of an effective voice for some of the most vulnerable among us.

Name: George Davis-Ansted
University/Course: Winchester School of Art
Description: Tendencies in Form is an interactive publication and sculpture set educating university students in Brighton the local challenges set by geographical restrictions on architects as well as developers to accommodate the growing student population in the city.

Name: Lily Rainbow O’Connell
University/Course: Cardiff Metropolitan University, Fine Art BA (Hons)
Description: This work is about perception and interaction. I use printmaking to create repeat patterns that explore optical effects and push the limits of vision, in order to engage with the viewer. Optical art can affect the eyes and mind, giving a more physical experience.

Name: Jaz Virgo
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description:
Disabled people face so much stigma. But even more so on the topic of sex. Durex is putting an end to misinformation with ‘Talking Taboos’. Posters are used to mock archaic myths, encouraging people to ‘talk about their taboo’ and share their
disabled sex life to liberate others. On social media Durex posts genuine role models creating disabled diversity.
Finally, launching their podcast featuring special guests. A place to go for
humorous yet informative content all about disability and sex.Quashing myths, creating open chats and providing a place to share their disabled
sex life triumphs.
Durex,
EveryBODY deserves sex.

Name: Daniel Swainson
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University
Description: Seoul Smile is a bike hire scheme that promotes positivity and happiness in a city where over twenty-per cent of the population is depressed. The identity is based on the rooftops of South Korean temples and how a journalist believed the curvature of the roofs made them look as though they were smiling. I have turned these roofs into a series of smiles, emphasising how it doesn't matter how you smile as long as you do.

Name: Inez Tully
University/Course: University of Brighton BA Illustration
Description: This piece of work is a page from my book Stone Walls that documents my feelings of being inside the Kipling Gardens, Rottingdean.

Name: Jaqueline Almagro Chiavarine
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University - BA Graphic Arts and Design
Description:
Coronavirus design was a troubling idea to start with, I tried not to represent or use anything that could be interpreted as inflammatory, discriminatory or stigmatising. 
I had been debating with some friends and family about what's appropriate and what isn’t, not everyone is in the same situation economically, not everyone is lucky enough to have a full fridge every week, some people are not living in houses, some families have lost some relatives….
I tried avoiding the idea of death and negativity within my design and these were some factors that I took into consideration. I also tried maintaining my work from my personal experiences given that all my designs tell my story this past year.
My first three illustrations show Mercedes, Claudia and myself at different airports travelling back home wearing the masks.
I then decided to represent myself working from home, using a screenshot of my Instagram page within my illustration.
I looked carefully at the information shown on the hand's sanitisers at home, looked for free PNGs to use on my bottles and added color. The information on my bottles is in Spanish, which makes it more relevant to me as an international student combining English and my first language in my work.
This design is different from the rest because I worked harder on giving the right information to my audience by adding type.
Some of the type is in red to make the titles stand out on a yellow background to portray the message of danger and how important it is to follow the rules.
I used the same technique on the illustration of my mum driving wearing a mask and gloves. The information provided in this design, are the only reasons why people should be using their cars during the outbreak.
I also thought that I would draw my friends and I having a google hangout video call playing a scape room online. I worked harder on the icons of the call instead of on the people I was representing. 
Some of the feedback obtained was that this design was interesting due to the tension and bleakness of the subject and strangely disturbing because of how different to the 'joie-de-vivre' that inform my other images.

Name: Raquel Soares Freitas
University/Course: BA (Hons) Graphics Design at Ravensbourne University
Description: Line x Time explores individuals thought processes with time constraints using dotted grids and pens.

Name: Jaqueline Almagro Chiavarine
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University - BA Graphic Art and Design
Description:
Ke bar is my seventh collage, its made of 6 illustrations. 
Compared to the other collages of Spain, ke bar is a design during the night time whereas I had only previously worked with day and afternoon designs.
Another difference is that on this occasion this design was during winter, where I had to work more on the clothing. 
While working on ke bar I concluded that during winter, the majority of people stick to greys, blacks, and dark tones instead of bright colours.
In this design I decided to work harder on the facial expressions, hair, on the detail in the leaves, the Christmas lights on the roof of the bar, ice cubes and other smaller details.
I felt it was challenging to work with such dark tones for the clothing having already so much black to represent the night. I changed a few of the original tones to lighter colours to have some more variety and not cause the clothing to blend with the background.
This occasion was a special gathering after months of not being together as a group because we all study and work in different locations, we had been planning and looking forward to this event not only cause we were a few days off Christmas Eve, but because we were going to play secret Santa during dinner, make an effort to look smart and then go out to have a few drinks and catch up face to face.
I thought that my designs were too summery and I was sending the wrong idea to people who had never been to Spain and believed that it was always sunny and hot. This was the perfect opportunity to demonstrate that we also have winter back at home.

Name: Tink Munro
University/Course: Shillington, Graphic Design
Description:
This poster is from the campaign 'Stop Taking the Piss'. Its goal is to alarm the punters of Glastonbury festival of the severe damage the ammonia in their pee is causing, encouraging them to use the loo's provided and respect the land.
If the people continue to pee where they please, they are not only poisoning the wildlife, they are also threatening the festivals own existence.

Name: Jaqueline Almagro Chiavarine
University/Course: Leeds Beckett - BA Graphic Art and Design
Description:
I decided to represent one of the Off Soto events I worked for at Trocadero a beach club at Sotogrande.
This collage is made of seven illustrations.
When I began this collage, I decided I would add speech bubbles to some of my drawings, I had to make the decision of who and what they would be saying. My intention was to make it as personal, relevant, and significant to the specific day, the personality of my friend, and give an appropriate message to communicate throughout my work.
Trocadero is probably one of my favourites designs, not only I enjoyed making it, but it also made me work harder on exploring typography, thinking about perspective, different ways of adding ornaments to the piece and playing with pattern making. The cocktails and the boat were changed from the realistic versions, after printing it once I decided it was also missing a few seagulls considering we were at the beach.
I worked hard on the composition of the flamingo shirt, the small iPhone details in white and some of the other clothing details.
The typeface used was Bradley hand bold 12pt. sharp.

Name: Eden Sinclair
University/Course: University of Reading: Typography and Graphic Communication
Description: This is dipmag, an independent design magazine created. A streamlined design briefing, created for individuals who hate the over-complication of today's newspapers and magazines. Dip in, dip out, access the information you need in an instant, and leave satisfied. Good enough for a double dip.

Name: Ollie Turner
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: A book series workshop with book designer, David Pearson. The purpose of the exercise was to develop three covers that were related by a particular theme. I decided to use one of my favourite artists, Travis Scott and three of his best songs. Pearson really encouraged us to use a more tactile approach to the work, using traditional hand making techniques instead of digital.

Name: Sarah Twelves
University/Course: Sheffield Hallam University, BA Hons Graphic Design
Description: Starting with the word 'polarisation' from Richard Serra’s verb list, I began to think of inventive ways to create a format and grid influenced from the definitions of this word in order to create a typographic only outcome. I was interested in the idea of a polarised Britain after Brexit as a political definition and the opposite of this being the scientific definition – the polarisation of light. This created lots of visual ideas of opposites, size, division, folds, repairing and more. The Typeface used was inspired by Jeremy Deller's "Strong and stable my arse" political poster – it gave me a sense of horizontal and vertical lines from the serifs which referred back to the polarisation of light definition.

Name: Jaqueline Almagro Chiavarine
University/Course: Leeds Beckett University - BA Graphic Art and Design
Description:
Haute Dolci is a luxurious restaurant with delicious creations, where the aesthetics of the restaurant is a mixture between beauty and the beast because of all the roses and decorations but also combined with the coffee shop in grease the movie.
In my design, I kept the logo on the wall the same, kept the marble wall tones but didn’t follow the realistic version by not adding the repetition of octagons on the walls.
Used Dolci logo on small chocolate decorations on the desserts. Every illustration in the collage has the Dolci name somehow.
Roses in the background, the same flower used in a repetitive way but used 6 different tones to create a pattern.
Soft creamy grey and white tones for tables, plates, candles, tea sets… pure white for the napkins, glaze overlay coating on waffle created with some transparency.

Name: Kevin
University/Course: Kingston University Graphic Design
Description:
Homeless people do not have an address which hinders them from accessing the services they need.

In London, 700,000 trees have been given an address in the form of longitude and latitude. By using What.3.Words, an application that translates coordinates to 3-word addresses, it enables trees to have addresses.

Birdposts are attached to these trees and give the homeless a temporary address to receive mail.

Name: Matt Ranson
University/Course: University of Suffolk, studying graphic design
Description: This is an outcome for my final personal project. The brief for this was to choose a problem that is not currently being visually represented well. I chose political correctness and I decided to approach this issue from a neutral standpoint. My concept was to create a conference which sparked discussion about the issues surround political correctness. The outcome you see is a rulebook for this conference, it folds up into an 8 page zine, and the aim of it is to craft the perfect discussion.

Name: Rosie Bebber
University/Course: NUA, Graphic Design
Description: Hit is a low alcohol, low calorie, vegan beer that contains CBD protein, that provides the perfect refreshment for gymgoers. Making it the ‘reward without compromise’. Hit, believes you shouldn't have to sacrifice your ability to be healthy, active, and at your best to enjoy great beer.

Name: Harsheena
University/Course: Leeds Beckett, Graphic Arts and Design
Description: A1 Screen print exploring the world of drag queens. The illustration was originally drawn in pen then photocopied and blown up for screen printing. I wanted to showcase the world of drag from my perspective.

Name: Junita Minhas
University/Course: Falmouth University
Description:
Royal Opera House Campaign:
Influenced by Duane Michals - imagery with text that results in more questions rather than giving 
answers. Capturing the essence of the 
fun of performing, the joy of watching and the overall experience of mystery, laughter and curiosity.

Name: Alice Quinn
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Design for Publishing
Description: A photographic narrative of the work of Oscar Wilde's, Dorian Gray. Challenging the traditional portrait and exploring themes of extraordinary youth and beauty and contrasting this with the idea of decay. Inspiration for this narrative taken from the deliberately destroyed art movement. Starting with the 'perfect' photo and manipulating it to, therefore, destroy it in the process.

Name: Catherine Jakob
University/Course: Falmouth University studying Illustration
Description: This was a speculative editorial piece for an article titled “The Tiger Next Door” which spoke about how there are more tigers being kept as pets in the USA than there are tigers left in the wild. They are a dangerous and uncontrollable pet to keep and usually end up causing havoc and damage to the people and environment around them.

Name: Findlay MacDonald
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art, Product Design
Description: This project, titled Vibrio, looks to a speculative future where our relationships with our smart assistants become symbiotic, viewing them no longer as smart assistants but as household digital companions, thus, creating a relationship much like we have with our pets. Creating this symbiotic relationship relies on the user “feeding” the pets in the form of data, in return for full functionality and a hyper-personalised way of living. This leaves the user in a paradoxical situation, questioning whether keeping their pets alive and functioning warrants pushing the boundaries of their data privacy.

Name: Lily Beer-Doblon
University/Course: UWTSD, Visual Communication MA
Description: Afro-indigenous cultures and history have been largely erased by barrage of colonial waves that Nicaragua has faced. My work acts as an exploration of my cultural heritage and is a homage to my forgotten ancestors.

Name: Manda Comisari
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art, MFA Illustration
Description: This is a piece from my project 'My Favorite Toy'. It showcased different dogs paired with their favorite toys and sought to tell a story in just two juxtaposed images. In this example, Elvis the dog's toy of choice was his stuffed doppelgänger.

Name: Quah Phaik Hoon
University/Course: Birmingham City University, BA (Hon) Graphic Communication
Description:
Bubble Popped is a semester project that intends
to highlight microaggression that happens in the United Kingdom. Although microaggression can be viewed as subtle and having no effect, it is actually scientifically proven that it can have lasting mental and emotional health effects. By creating conversations and raising awareness on the issue, we can progress as a society where microaggression doesn’t exist.

Name: Alex Mpankuli
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University - BA Fashion Design
Description: This project focuses on exploring the arrangement of and relations between the parts or elements of something complex, by looking at two series of work (Seven Decades and The Park Avenue series) by sculptural artist Antony Caro. The aim of my FMP is to produce a six-piece womenswear garment collection with 3d printed accessories such as shoes and bags to match.

Name: Jasmine Pert
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone studying Textile Design
Description: I want to bring the joy and positive impact plants provide into the home environment through a series of digital prints for home interiors inspired by the playful, vibrant colours, pattern and textures found within plant life. Keeping house plants has had a revival in recent years and I would love to see my designs combined with real plants to create healthy spaces that bring the outdoors in and help people reconnect with nature.

Name: Kelsey travis
University/Course: Fine art at university of Chester
Description: This piece of work is part of a digital drawing series that I have created for my university graduation show, it is meant to represent one aspect of my memories and experiences in life. This one in particular represents a hard time in my life that has made me stronger.

Name: Alice Prentice
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design,  Illustration
Description: Conceptual illustrations to accompany love poems for the House of Illustration Competition 2020. Designed to look as though they would be printed on a Risograph duplicator.

Name: Bianca Schmittmann
University/Course: Winchester School of Art, BA Fine Art
Description: My paintings explore my childhood experiences and memories, compressing them into narratives filled with awkward self-portraits. Even though the subject can seem negative, the manner in which the figures are created, adopt a certain language that plays with the atmosphere of the subject, making it comedic.

Name: Thea Bryant
University/Course: Graphic Design at the University of Edinburgh
Description:
Together United F.C. was born out of the human need for community feeling and unity, in a time of unprecedented isolation and uncertainty. 

By returning to what really matters in football - the people involved and the space for togetherness - and matching this with its common visual language, I have produced a collection of memorabilia to offer people a sense of belonging and communal identity.

Name: Layla Green
University/Course: UCLan, BA Fine Art
Description: By interpreting my everyday into paintings, I highlight the challenging lifestyles people face in response to modern day technology. My work emphasises how mobile phones and our commitment to social media has influenced our personal relationships and daily function. I want my paintings to depict this without there being an obvious visual thread and intend to challenge the viewers own concerns regarding their attitude and opinions on this matter.

Name: Lucy Marriott
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores, Fashion Communication
Description:
bimble' is a conceptual multi-sensory retail respite space  in which shoppers can pause, relax and unwind to escape the frenetic pace of the retail world.                         

Part of the multi-sensory experience includes taste, this menu card illustrates what is available to stimulate your taste buds within your bimble pod.

Name: Lucy Marriott
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores, Fashion Communication
Description:
bimble' is a conceptual multi-sensory retail respite space  in which shoppers can pause, relax and unwind to escape the frenetic pace of the retail world.                         

Still life images present the interiors and colour palette of 'bimbles' brand concept.

Name: Lucy Marriott
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University, Fashion Communication
Description:
bimble' is a conceptual multi-sensory retail respite space in which shoppers can pause, relax and unwind to escape the frenetic pace of the retail world.                         

This shoot represents the 'feeling' of bimble and how it would feel to be immersed in a multi-sensory experience.

Name: Lucy Marriott
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University, Fashion Communication
Description:
bimble' is a conceptual multi-sensory retail respite space  in which shoppers can pause, relax and unwind to escape the frenetic pace of the retail world.              

Hand rendered collages using fabric and stitch to develop the interior, ‘mood’ and style of each 'bimble pod'

Name: Alberto Gonzalez
University/Course: University of Chester
Description: This photograph is part of a series which aims to provide visual imagery to blind people's real narratives of their dreams previously collected by scientific psychology researchers. This picture revolves around blind people's fears of not being able to communicate with others and feeling helpless and vulnerable as a consequence of this. The photograph relies on surrealist symbols previously used by painters such as Dali.

Name: Charlotte Tatlow
University/Course: I studied Product Design at the University of Chester.
Description:
Sustainability and designing for a greener future is something I feel passionate about. The inspiration behind my major project was reducing food scarcity within an ever-growing population.
The Community Tree will provide the resources for users to grow their own fresh produce in an urban environment. Additionally at night, ambient dusk lighting transforms it into a safe social space, encouraging a greater sense of community. Each branch allows the user to plant and harvest crops, which can  be accessed by lowering with a unique crank handle. The growing process is called aeroponics, which uses an air and mist environment without the need for soil.

Name: Ella d'Aguilar
University/Course: London College of Fashion, Fashion Styling and Production
Description: My project 'Hiding in Plain Sight' is a zine containing a series of self-portraits which stem from my personal experience and exploration of Body Dysmorphic Disorder. More specifically, the work aims to show the conflicting feelings of wanting to stand out from the crowd, versus the anxiety from being looked at by others causing the need to hide.

Name: Nika Smirnova
University/Course: University of Westminster, BA(Hons) Contemporary Media Practice
Description: UN/Mask The Future is the environmental campaign for Londoners. The aim to raise awareness about air pollution levels and start a conversation. As part of the campaign, Nika developed an iOS app, that uses AR to unveil air pollution in London. The app combines daily air pollution reports, AR camera view and educational articles.

Name: Grace Burke-Whyte
University/Course: University of Chester BA Fine Art
Description: Over the last year I have been exploring abandoned places, I travelled to Chernobyl to capture nature reclaiming the zone. I draw the main subject of the photograph and place the photograph over. By combining the two together it makes the subject matter appear as though it is fading away.

Name: Luca Pellegrini
University/Course: Shillington College - Graphic Design
Description:
L'Arche, (The Ark, in English), is a Venue, based in Marrakesh, Morocco.
The name originates from the fact that Morocco being a very religious and predominantly Muslim country, people wanted a sanctuary, not unlike the Ark in the biblical sense and to combine it with an identity that captures the spirit of Marrakesh.
This Venue aims to involve as many people as possible regardless of age and gender. As most of the venues in Marrakesh are very expensive and rather touristy and mainly target a young or wealthy audience, this Venue has the sole aim of involving both everyone.

Name: Helen Tong
University/Course: I graduated from Shillington College and studied Graphic Design
Description: This is a packaging design for an Italian olive oil brand aimed at families with young children. The inspiration behind the design was taken from the small island of Burano and its colourful houses and terrazzo pavements. The brand has a fictional story behind it which is all about how the colourful houses of Burano came about.

Name: Heather Brown
University/Course: University of Chester, Graphic Design.
Description: You've got to put your self out there when coming out of university, what better way than to create a piece of work you love, combined with your passion. The figures in my work were drawn with my eyes closed as research for my study into educating society how to interact with the hard of hearing and visually impaired. The background is my own interpritation of William Morris' work. The art's and craft movement is a true inspiration to myself and my work, it seemed almost ridiculous not to run with that.

Name: Zoe Beckett
University/Course: University of Dundee, and I studied graphic design
Description: This is my response to the Chrysalis Brand Opus brief, creating a drinks brand and packaging design with a functional benefit. Bloomin’ Gin uses seed embedded paper as packaging so you can grow your own botanicals.

Name: Amie Shannon
University/Course: University of Chester
Description: A World That No Longer Exists

Name: Francesca Rea
University/Course: Textile Design at University of Dundee
Description: Textiles hold great significance across cultures and throughout history, and what one wears in the grave is a meaningful decision for many people. My project aims to open the discussion around death and the rituals and practices that surround it. Using the slow and thoughtful process of hand embroidery, I have designed textiles for burial-wear made from animal and plant-based fabrics and natural dyes that are 100% decomposable. I have drawn from disintegrated leaves as a reminder of our place in the environment, one that we must look after for the next generations in the cycle of life.

Name: Kelda Young
University/Course: Jewellery and Metalwork at Duncan of Jordanstone, Dundee
Description: My work is inspired by recollected fragmented memories that have been condensed into abstract shapes and translated into bold designs in the workshop. Inspiration is also drawn from rare moments of serenity and details that might often go unnoticed. These pieces are intended to be wearable mini sculptures, allowing interpretation by the user. My collection brings structure to memories, allowing them to be preserved through materialisation. The fabrication of these pieces creates a place for them in my physical world.

Name: Amy
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores University - BA Fashion (Communication)
Description: My image is an illustration I created based on primary photography from my Baltic Youth project. Baltic Youth was a collaborative project with the Baltic Triangle's SEVENSTORE, exploring the people that live, work and play in the infamous creative quarter of Liverpool.

Name: Kyla Wilkinson
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth
Description: I created this graphic as part of a menu design, for a women's empowerment pop-up event. I chose to illustrate a heroine in the style of a vintage comic book, symbolising strength, and to break down stereotypical gender roles. The heroine is depicted breaking through the glass ceiling, in the effort to achieve occupational gender equality.

Name: Diana Branzan
University/Course: Pratt Institute, illustration
Description:
I started out this year thinking about all of the past homes I have lived in, and questioning and thinking about the idea of home as a “constant” in all of our lives. By drawing different fragmented vignettes of nine to ten past personal living spaces and focusing on the displacement that can come from this constant shifting, I will be addressing a lack of consistent grounding, not only to myself but to others who have had similar trajectories. Where is home, really? Will we ever get there? Are we there right now without knowing it, and will we ever? By piecing together details of homes past through painting, drawing, collage and playing with transparencies, my end goal was to create a larger animated piece, stringing memories from these living spaces together that can speak to other immigrants or anyone that has ever questioned where home is. 
My family’s current apartment was always a stopping point between where we used to be and where we once will be, never a final point or final destination, there never was a feeling of fully “settling down.” New York is particular to this experience in terms of its shifting permanence, and further made me want to address the occurrence of feeling like a foreigner in your own home. I’m hoping one day everybody can find comfort in their drifting states, no matter where they may be.

Name: Irvin Tam
University/Course: Kingston School of Art
Description: Ceres is a speculative device that connects people with nature in response to contemporary society's technology addiction and detachment from reality. The users' health-related habits, including their amount of time spent on mobile devices, step count and hydration, are connected to the necessities of the plant provided by the device.

Name: Mariana Soares Goldsmith
University/Course: Goldsmiths University: Media and Communication Specialisation in Photography
Description: My Deepest Blue' is a body of work printed manually through an old darkroom process called Cyanotype. A portrayal of loneliness as in being a problem within solitude, of learning to love the imperfect and acknowledging that the quested Blue was a reflection from deep inside of me. This project is very much about stepping out of my comfort zone as an artist. Rather than pointing the camera towards others, for the first time, I now became the subject. Completion of 4 images, each taking  3 weeks to print.

Name: Roshi Rouzbehani
University/Course: University of Hertfordshire (IDI), BA (Hons) in Illustration
Description:
This is a mocked-up page from my upcoming book "50 Inspiring Iranian Women" which portrays and celebrates 50 extraordinary Iranian women, who have broken new grounds in their professional lives. 
This is a portrait illustration of Forough Farrokhzad, a controversial modernist poet.

Name: Aga Skulicz
University/Course: Edinburgh College, Computer Arts and Design
Description: "Goodnight Irene" is the illustration utilizing themes of nature, harmony and dreams. Hornbills have a significant meaning in Dayak mythology, as they are viewed as messengers of the spirits and also symbolize virility. It is a portrayal of Mother Nature's strength, a collage of humans and nature.

Name: Morys Davies
University/Course: University of Salford- Graphic Design
Description: The challenge for this project was to find a genre, song or musical movement that best represents a cause and use typography as the main creative expression to bring it to life. Choosing the environment as my cause, linking it to specific lyrics, I made a statement on planned obsolescence & throwaway culture. My chosen demographic was Gen Z and Millennials as these are the generations that grew up alongside the development of technology and where the response to my work can have the greatest impact on wastage. Through countless iterations and experimentation, I discovered a song that my demographic would be familiar with worldwide and highlights how the culture that developed alongside the growth of technology is damaging the planet. My work aims to encourage positive change.

Name: Leonie Cameron
University/Course: Fine Art Sculpture, University of Brighton
Description: My work is currently based around my central working phrase 'Every Woman is a Deity in Her Own Right' which aims to elevate the worth of the every day woman as a feminist action. In this work, I appropriate religious banners and altar textiles aesthetics combined with images of my two grandmothers, my mother and myself as an ode to the women who raised me. I use hand plant dyed fabric and screen prints of medium format film portraits to communicate the tangibility and sensitivity of my work.

Name: Eliza woolley
University/Course: Liverpool John Moores, fashion communications
Description: It’s an app- moving image on how to become untrackable from data

Name: Emily Hewitt
University/Course: LJMU fashion design
Description: My collection was inspired by the work of Edward  Burtynsky and how landscapes have been damaged by human activity. A huge focus was quarries and I wanted to replicate the structures, patterns and rigid lines they form through my passion of pattern cutting. Alongside this, I was also inspired by the construction and manufacture of traditional denim garments! For example the experiments of lapped felled seams also became a focal point.

Name: Elisabeth Barrett
University/Course: University of Kent
Description: "Present.": It is a website prototype for improving accessibility in the digital mindfulness and wellbeing space.

Name: Isabella Richardson
University/Course: Cambridge School of Art, Illustration BA
Description: This is an editorial illustration in response to an article in the British Psychological Society Research Digest about the prevalence of Imposter Syndrome amongst BAME female university students who are undertaking STEM degree courses. I used the nesting doll as a metaphor to represent the feeling of having to conceal one's feelings of inadequacy and insecurity.

Name: Ashley Coull
University/Course: The University of Dundee, Textile Design
Description: My  work investigates how pattern can change and shape an interior environment, giving it an identity and a personality that creates a relationship between the space and the people within. Informed by the Arts and Crafts movement and its belief in craftsmanship, my project strives to showcase the handmade marks and shapes from my visual research through the medium of digital print. Visually I was inspired by technology, looking at various elements found in a telephone exchange.

Name: George Finley Inwards
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University, BA Illustration
Description: During the lockdown of COVID-19 I wanted to come up with something to put a smile on people's faces. This was one of a series of four images that I designed to help people relate to one another. Boredom was a feeling that I think almost everyone felt at one point, so this seemed appropriate.

Name: Maisie Miller
University/Course: Textile Design BA(Hons) at Norwich University of the Arts
Description: This design comes from a collection where I wanted to capture the beauty of the Peak District through my drawings. I then wanted to put these drawings into a print design for home and interiors so that I can share the awe I feel for the idyllic landscapes with others.

Name: Christopher Neal
University/Course: The Ruskin School of Art - BFA Fine Art
Description: My artistic practice investigates the architecture of sacred spaces, and the way that light is used to illuminate the space and to convey a sense of the sacred. This sculpture is part of an extended research project investigating 'Tin Tabernacles', 19th century churches made from corrugated iron, that were designed and assembled in a flatpack form. This work is a model of the spire of one of these churches, St Saviour's Church, Faversham, Kent. The sculpture is itself an IKEA-style flatpack, constructed from MDF and assembled using wooden dowels. It investigates the conflict between the permanence and solidity of traditional sacred spaces, and the furniture and structures of our contemporary society.

Name: Charlotte Scott
University/Course: York St. John University studying Graphic Design BA (Hons)
Description: I created the design for the popular fiction novel, Good Night Mister Tom. The brief required a fresh, unique design for the book. The book is set during WWII so the design is inspired by the posters and propaganda distributed at the time. I created the typeface for 'GOOD NIGHT' from scratch, to resemble the type used on the WWII posters, and decided to letterpress the cover to link to the method of printing used during WWII linking to the book closely. The novel has a tree-theme throughout and the two main character's have surnames of two different trees which links to their contrasting personalities. I chose the typeface for 'MISTER TOM' to contrast against 'GOOD NIGHT' linking to their contrasting personalities. I have a passion for type which propelled the idea of using purely type for the cover.

Name: Aaron Atkinson
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - BA(Hons)Graphic Design
Description:
The poster series was part of campaign that focuses on the awareness of and the active conversation of mens mental health. 

The poster series uses a modular gird system to represent order and guidance in receiving help, contrasting serif and sans-serif typography demonstrating the idea of confusion sufferers may feel and three different colour gradients that play on the idea of colour theory and emotional responses and perception humans have to colour.

Name: Ellen-Mae Parker
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University/Cambridge School of Art, BA Illustration
Description: Just before the lockdown was announced I moved back home with my parents because I was afraid I would be trapped in university halls alone. I had to suddenly face that I would never return to uni, experience my degree show or graduate as I had imagined since the beginning of my Illustration degree. I was overwhelmed by the bigger picture of the world, so I turned to reportage work and focussed on my day-to-day, documenting  small moments. I intentionally used a bright colour palette to share something positive on social media, hoping it may lift spirits. It was important for me to seek comfort in making this work whilst I was processing so much change. These drawings were originally part of a sequential comic, but here I have montaged a handful together into one composition.

Name: Eleanor Beale
University/Course: University of Edinburgh, Fine Art MAFA
Description:
Cocooned within large artificial earth mounds, my sound piece, Found Across Other Ebbs, resonates through speakers, vibrating the surrounding earth.
Large artificial earth mounds sing their lament, as sites of grittiness and sources of life, places of burial and regrowth. Their tragedy as phoneys
mirrors the short falls of rose-tinted recollection. From these mounds I watered and nurtured small seedlings uprooted from home, encouraging their growth from this site of artificiality, to eventually then rot and decay. Woven from personal sounds, such as mum’s breath through the clarinet and microphones inside my mouth, the sound piece creates perspective with distant foghorns, tram track sounds and birds such as the turtledove- a declining species in Britain. Deflecting trepidation of growing up and wilting - like plants, I harboured nostalgia, reminiscing and idolising childhood. These memories, shaped by their sounds, are both distant and intimate. This piece reflects my continued exploration into sounds as metaphors, expressing the chasm between reality and reflection, prompted by Wordsworth's The Prelude. It questions what’s natural and what’s artificial about memory. Wide, impersonal landscapes devoid of human presence cast against sounds created by intimate moments ebb and flow, repeating the rhythm of memory recall that’s further echoed by the mounds' sinuous folds.

Name: Olivia Jordan
University/Course: University of Brighton - Product Design with Professional Experience
Description: New World Explorer - A hybrid board game, aimed at helping parents pick up the signs of dyslexia in their children and supporting them with the next steps.

Name: Miriam Hancill
University/Course: MFA Contemporary Art Practice at Edinburgh College of Art, University of Edinburgh
Description:
‘Workshop Wipe’, monotype on inkjet print on paper, 118.9x84.1cm, 2020. 

This image is a byproduct of my practice as a printmaker, using imagery, surface marks and textures that have coalesced during my time at ECA. My interest in the processes used when making work, as well as the spaces the subsequent work inhabits, has allowed for cross pollination and expansion between practice and studio, studio and workshop and so on, with the works being informed as much by their materiality as their subject matter. By working in this reactive, accumulative manner, the processes at the heart of this practice are pushed to their limits, resulting in works that both question and contribute to the nature of contemporary printmaking.

Name: Nancy Root
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description:
A concept… Bump is a new arrival to the world of alcohol-free drinking, benefitting those pregnant or breastfeeding. Containing anti-nausea ginger and hormone stabilizing passion flower for mum, alongside iron and vitamin D for baby.

The identity is inspired by baby scans, using hidden details such as the dots and gradient bars on scan pictures. There are subtle hints to the baby world through copy lines “a teeny tiny hint of strawberry and a gentle kick of ginger”. 

Bump is not a ‘mumsy’ drink, it is a sophisticated, alcohol free alternative, that also contains benefits for both mum and baby. “A little of what you fancy, benefitting you AND bump”.

Name: Libby Scott
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University Illustration
Description: An alternative approach to the fairy tale ‘Princess and the Pea’ by Hans Christian Anderson, using gouache, pencil and digital media.

Name: Anne Morgan
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art
Description: A quilt collection 'Lines of Desire' inspired by abstract landscape painting. Using reclaimed resources and craft skills; print and stitch.

Name: Jaz Stanford
University/Course: Goldsmiths fine Art BA
Description: My practice stems from research of fasciation within plants, it also involves continually introducing new materials. I question the use of ‘good’ and ‘bad’ materials, while remaining open to incorporating both into my work as part of its interior discourse. I enjoying the shininess within my work and the colours and materials that have certain toxic connotations, and their relationship with industrial processes. I carry ongoing motifs from past anecdotes, including representations of natural elements to affect the temperature of the space.

Name: Steffi Wallace
University/Course: Leeds Arts University BA Creative Advertising
Description: #Always campaign shows that regardless of menstruation women are always working hard and putting their all in, it has nothing to do with what time of the month it is.

Name: Steffi Wallace
University/Course: Leeds Arts University BA Creative Advertising
Description: BIG IDEA - Instinctively distinctive. Shows that the independent jewellers are different from the rest of the crowd. They have a history that goes back to Kenya.

Name: Steffi Wallace
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: The adshel shows that you can do your normal but better in another city in the world.

Name: Shannen Tioniwar
University/Course: University of Edinburgh, Product Design
Description: Incognito is an interactive intermediary device that can be used in the presence of an AI gadget, allowing users to customise their boundaries with regard to the data collection processes.  This is done by creating decisional qualification, meaning that users can decide to share their data solely on their own discretion, that reuses current technologies to instigate a positive change for the future society and maintain human-machine interactions. Incognito  invites each user to determine whether they would like to expose their data towards “always listening devices” given the consequences.

Name: Amy Elena Nash
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: As a British/ Romanian creative, I am exploring and using my Eastern European heritage to introduce ideas of my culture into the mainstream British culture. I am exploring how culture continuously inspires modern fashion; taking key cultural elements like the shape of the garments, colour scheme and stitching techniques to then marry them together and create a modern silhouette, illustrating Romania’s rich history.

Name: Piers Thorley
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University Ba (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Miller Genuine Draft ‘Made for you’ is a package design led campaign which celebrates diversity and cultures, The 6 M’s represent different personalities and so do the colours used on the Bottles. The colours specifically represent Hispanic and African American cultures as aimed for in the target market of 24-34 year olds. The colourful designs bring a fresh new feel to MGD modernising the look and provides a role for MGD in the Miller portfolio with a fresh new look, changing trends and bringing more energy to the brand to make it more relevant.

Name: Basil
University/Course: The Northern School Of Art
Description: A book illustration for a personal project about modernised dinosaurs and humans living together

Name: Callum Ritchie
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts - MA Communication Design, BA Illustration
Description: It is an editorial image I decided to illustrate from the absurdist but real headline reading ‘Suspected wildfire discovered to be 600,000 ducks’.  It aims show a comedic look at environmental headlines in the news which can so often be doom and gloom.

Name: Beth Ashley
University/Course: Leeds Arts University and Illustration
Description: Utilising juicy, joyful, wonderful pockets of expression language has to offer our imagination fuels my intent as an imagemaker. My work is rooted within the employment of textual charm, ridiculous utterance and pure indulgent word play. It centers on the import placed upon a linguistic occurrence because it is deemed worthy of inspection. Random they may be, welcome they are and sourced from just about everywhere.

Name: Rebecca Bennett
University/Course: The Northern School of Art - Illustration for commercial application
Description: My illustration was for a mock game I made based on cyberpunk and yokai and this piece was to bring together the characters I designed for it

Name: sophie townsend
University/Course: the northern school of art illustration for commercial application
Description: my work is about design, showing a story and narrative through the visual of a character or scene. Through final narrative pieces, I hope to tell a story and create intrigue, to have the viewer or client want to know what the rest of the world is like, want to see more. I want people to fall in love and want to learn about the things I build, I want to design curiosity.

Name: Rui
University/Course: Central Saint Martins, ual.
Description: Inspired by Sigmund Freud’s personality structures, I decided to use three distinctive characters to represent each personality. I divided those three characters into, the id: fear/timid/ chaotic/ impulsive/instinctive self within my body, the ego: the reality self in my living environment, the superego: the ideal version of myself, the perfectionist and the player of my whole consciousness. Then I transform them into surreal visual scenarios — a series of dynamic photography with engaging and immersive sound effects. In a total of 6, each personality has a certain environment which symbolically representing their identity, personalities and their relationship between each other and the surroundings.

Name: Fleur
University/Course: Greater Brighton Metropolitan College
Description: This piece of artwork is from my collection called 'Changing Perceptions'. It is all about focusing on how people view a piece of art. What they see, how it makes them feel. The artwork stemmed from my visit to Kew Gardens with the idea of capturing different components of a variety of natural forms and creating them into abstract pieces of artwork; then to be produced onto luxury fabrics for interiors and furnishings. This sample has unusual colour combinations with the idea that it doesn't follow a specific trend, but to speak for itself and to be a timeless piece.

Name: Katie Anna Barrett
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art - Fashion Design
Description: This is an initial collage I did during my design development for my Graduate Collection. The collection was inspired by Bauhaus, surrealism, and people's need to document their life for all to see, as a way of proving their existence.

Name: Laura Davidson
University/Course: University of Dundee, Textile design
Description:
Fast fashion brands are generating trends that come and go far too quickly on our high streets. My goal is to create an alternative to these mass-produced and disposable garments by creating unique, made to last, fabrics for womenswear.  With independently handmade garments I hope to promote ethical clothing choices and handcrafted fashion.
I have  based my designs around my home, Caithness. I have been inspired by the rural surroundings of Caithness my whole life which has always been present in my work.  My main goal has been to illustrate the rural and unique character of Caithness and translate this through digital print.
My work aims stand out from the fast fashion lead high-street with one of a kind and original prints for fashion.

Name: Micha Lloyd
University/Course: University of Lincoln, BA(Hons) Fine Art
Description: Titled 'Oscillations', these pieces are part of a larger body of work which explores Gilles Deleuze's concept of Repetition,  Albert  Bandura's Social Learning Theory, and the significance of these subjects in relation to the artist's experiences of living with repetition OCD.  The photographs document a performance in which the artist carried out compulsive actions.  By attempting to sew over and imitate the shapes within these photographs, the original images become consumed by new layers of lines and shapes, producing an entirely new outcome. This process reminds the artist of the futility of her obsession with repeating actions until they are done 'correctly'.

Name: Jodie
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University, BA Illustration
Description: This is one layout from a book I designed, which explores figures and light sources at night in the city of Cambridge. In times like these, I feel as though this image resonates most with the types of familiar scenes we are all currently experiencing if and when we are to go outside.

Name: Ruth
University/Course: Graphic Design @ Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
Designing new packaging for the Highland Spring bottle. I drew inspiration from the Scottish Highlands and the landscape surrounding it in the Ochil Hills, where they naturally source spring water.

I created a customised type that was based on the sharp Basalt rock (that is in the soil) to add to the bottle's design. 

Using the slogan "Reach your peak" and incorporating a fun, illustration style to demonstrate people actively moving round the landscape demonstrates how water (and the brand) can help you thrive.

Name: Rosie Hurley
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin- BA Illustration
Description: For my FMP I re-illustrated Roald Dahl's story Esio Trot and this is an image from that series. This is the eith images in the series and illustrates the sentences "Good morning Mrs Silver, Alfie is looking well this morning' Mr Hoppy said. 'Isn't he gorgeous! I do so wish he would grow a little faster though', Mrs Silver replied."

Name: Isobel Grant
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University - Cambridge School of Art (BA Illustration (Hons))
Description: An image based on the fable, ‘The Frog and The Ox’. This piece is part of a larger series that focuses on frog themed fables. These images were mainly made using Procreate, however there are elements that were created through layers of acrylic ink, coloured pencils and graphic markers. Each piece in the series encapsulates the fable it was based on; ‘The Frog and the Ox’ focuses on a frog who blows himself up to be as large as an ox. This series is intended to be used as children’s book illustrations.

Name: Kayleigh Keen
University/Course: Anglia Ruskin University - BA Illustration
Description: This is the first print in my aquatint series inspired by The Werewolf by Angela Carter.

Name: Michael Bushell
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton
Description: It is part of the sculptures in Dudley. All of them are set on roundabouts on a bypass. Its called the Dudley Sculpture Trail. This is just one image from a series of work.

Name: Jessica Hornby
University/Course: University of Huddersfield
Description:
Analysing and challenging the misconceptions and pre-conceived idea’s about women in sport, I felt that this was particularly poignant given the recent World Cups and upcoming Olympics events. 

I approached local teams with a view to documenting sports at all levels e.g amateur, semi-professional and professional and was able to photograph action and portrait shots along with audio interviews with players and coaches. 

My research into gender roles and the attitudes associated with both men and women in sports has led to me questioning my own possible hypocritical opinions and views. The outcome of my work has caused me to consider the subject from all angles to ensure that I have represented a fair representation of the people involved.
Website: Instagram: jess_hornby it has a link to my website

Name: Paloma del Valle
University/Course: University of Edinburgh - Edinburgh College of Art, graduating from Performance Costume MFA
