Description: My project is the costume design for a TV adaptation of "The Book of Lost Tales" by J.R.R. Tolkien. The project focuses on the first season, that narrates the tale of Beren and Lúthien. The picture above shows the costume for the character Vëannë, an elf from the Teleri tribe. My work involves research, design development through sketches, colour palettes, 20 final illustrations with technical drawings and fabric samples as well as set design ideas and filming locations.

Name: Bex Hall
University/Course: University of Lincoln studying Photography
Description:
This project entitled, Scarred Earth, explores the meaning of the word ‘scar’; featuring scars as a geological or geographical entity with a focus upon the wounds inflicted on the landscape. 
Scarred Earth encapsulates the both the loneliness and desolation of our scarred landscape but also invites audiences to contemplate the impermanence of human impact.

Name: Chloe Darnill
University/Course: BA (Hons) Photography at Norwich University of the Arts
Description: This image of Holly belongs to a portrait series that focuses on subjects who experience or have experienced acne. The project began during my own struggles with the skin condition, when I felt isolated and a lack understanding from society. The project aims to uplift it's subjects, provide a sense of community and encourage a more normalised view of acne.

Name: Lillie Prior
University/Course: Nottingham Trent University BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description:
Migraines are the most common and disabling neurological disorder in the UK, affecting one in seven people. Enjoy The Silence aims to reduce the negative stereotype surrounding migraines and show people that they are more than just a headache.

The record cover and campaign material use typography and optical illusions to reflect the visual disturbances one may experience during a migraine attack. The campaign encourages people to explain how they are affected by migraines through music, using the website as a platform to gain support for this hidden disability.

Name: Olivia Taylor
University/Course: University of Huddersfield - Photography
Description: My focus is the overlooked every day, specifically the overlooked and highlighting the beauty in the banal that would otherwise go ignored and unacknowledged. My practice is founded on ideas of complex thinking translating through seemingly simplistic work, and of how the unconscious mind plays a role in each creative process.

Name: Ellen Harling
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, MA Communication Design
Description: Creating a new visual language for historic churches, taking inspiration from the characters of monumental brasses.

Name: Robert Rickers
University/Course: Falmouth University - BA Creative Advertising
Description: Persuading consumers to purchase hemp products as they have loads of environmental benefits e.g. act as a carbon sink

Name: Eleanor Marshman
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: The theoretical framework for my ongoing inquiry looks towards issues regarding sustainability in fashion as they are articulated within our changing relations to materiality and the physical objects that surround us. My proposal being that reconnecting with the material of clothes, as both producers and consumers, points towards a slowing down of the accelerated cycles of consumption and discard promoted by current fashion. The resulting piece subsequently elevates defects in clothing through referencing traditional styles and modes of production within design, all the while providing a poetic and critical observation on issues surrounding commerce.'

Name: Chien-wei Yu
University/Course: University of Edinburgh
Description: This is a piece from my graduate project Dear Life, which is based on twenty-four short stories by Alice Munro. The work is my interpretation of Leaving Maverley.

Name: Harry Marino & Luke Hibberd
University/Course: University of Lincoln - Creative Advertising
Description: being part of an advertising course. this is one of our marker visuals for a Rimmel campaign that we're proud of.

Name: Joe Habben
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art, Communication Design
Description: ‘In Moleca’ documents the events and effects of the ‘Acqua Alta’ (high-water) which transpires annually in the city of Venice, Italy. This tidal activity is a natural occurrence, however in recent decades it has been aggravated by the effects of human activity. Mass-tourism, global warming, urban expansion and industrialisation are damaging factors which have influenced the deterioration of the Venetian lagoon, this has led to the increasing tide and subsidence of the ‘floating city’. Exploring issues caused by human intervention; this on-going project highlights the tender balance between urban inhabitants and the environment. How can cities like Venice harmonise this interdependent relationship and adapt to the age of the Anthropocene in an increasingly globalised world?

Name: Billie Sprong
University/Course: Leeds Art University, Graphic Design
Description: Zonked as a typeface is fresh, contemporary and unique. The font combines simplicity and connotes the feelings of being dazed to construct an open and harmonious composition. It’s clear, fluid shapes create a distinctive aesthetic, which is well suited to headings and titles within editorial and advertising design. The font is provided in sans serif format to distinguish the gentle, relaxed nature of being ‘zonked’. This poster highlights the abstract, playful nature of the typeface.

Name: Liv Khloe
University/Course: Plymouth College Of Art
Description: La Femi is a magazine that aims to support new mothers during pregnancy and postpartum. La Femi interview’s mothers about their experiences and keeping our ethos in mind which is honesty and transparency. We care about mums and their well-being. One of our aims for this magazine is to give a positive alternative in the replacement of gossip magazines

Name: Michael Christodoulou
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Communication
Description: Two Weather a Storm is a Virtual Reality film which visualizes the emotions of two people that are weathering a storm together. The story has taken the form of two co-existing poems, and this is the branding and promotional posters for the Virtual Reality film.

Name: Daisy Blair
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, BA Illustration
Description: This illustration is taken from my silent book (a book that tells a story using only images, no text), which is called 'Return'. The story is based on Aesop's fable of The Labourer and The Nightingale, which I have adapted to be much more symbolic and abstract. My story shows the struggle between two characters: the Man and the Bird. The narrative is circular - the end brings you back to the beginning, and the book can be read both backwards and forwards. The story is interpretative and can be seen to represent many things, including the cycle of life and death and their symbiosis, humans' relationship with nature, or the concepts of good and evil or light and dark. I created the imagery manually, by drawing and using monoprint techniques, which I then stitched together digitally to create the final illustrations. This illustration in particular shows the Man's first step towards overpowering the Bird; the Bird falls, and the Man begins to climb up and out of the Bird's stomach.

Name: Ava-Lien Shoshan & Eleanor Farish
University/Course: Leeds Arts University; Creative Advertising
Description: ADT Home Security: To beat the burglar you must become the burglar

Name: Gabriel Paul
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic Design
Description:
The year is 2083, Space travel has developed to the point that the human race is ready to move to Mars, but how will gravity dependent objects have to adapt for their designs to be valid on the Red Planet? A zimmer frame designed with the elements
of Mars in mind, to make space travel for the elderly possible.

Name: Mary Flora Hart
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth, BA illustration
Description: This image is my personal favourite from a collection named Urban Eden. A short series that explores modern scenes with a small psychedelic overgrown twist. Each image is over 4 meters long to ensure it captures all the details, and made with the purpose of being printed as billboards and office murals, to encourage green initiatives.

Name: Gloria Ogunyinka
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts and Fashion Design
Description:
Spot the Real Thug is a satirical collection focussing on the designers heritage, an interesting
mix of Nigerian and Liverpudlian, taking inspiration from football hooliganism in the 1980s.
It’s intention is to provoke conversation about what it means to be mixed race, growing up in
a world where they’re considered half of something, and never quite enough to be
considered truly either. The collection also takes a serious tone, evoking guests to think about society, with the name
“Spot The Real Thug” taken from an article in the 1980s, on how to spot a football hooligan
simply by how they dress. The quote “the bovver-booted model on the left looks ready for a
punch-up but the casually dressed model on the right is wearing the new disguise”, inspired
the designer to look at how in society, black men are statistically more likely to be accused of
committing a crime simply by how they look, rather than what they’re doing. A topic the
designer feels strongly about, after the death of Trayvon Martin and the way the case was
handled.

Name: Findlay MacDonald
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art, Product Design
Description: This project, titled Vibrio, looks to a speculative future where our realtionships with our smart assistants become symbiotic, viewing them no longer as smart assistants but as household digital companions, thus, creating a relationship much like we have with our pets. Creating this symbiotic relationship relies on the user “feeding” the pets in the form of data, in return for full functionality and a hyper-personalised way of living. This leaves the user in a paradoxical situation, questioning whether keeping their pets alive and functioning warrents pushing the boundaries of their data privacy.

Name: Lotte Cassidy
University/Course: Illustration at Arts University Bournemouth
Description: Fancy a Cuppa?' is an animation about old age. Forgetfulness is a normal part of ageing. Memories come and go in no particular order. My Grandma tells us her childhood memories over a cup of tea.

Name: George Stockley
University/Course: University for the creative arts Graphic Design
Description:
Climate change is affecting everyone's lives, yet people still do not believe it is happening or even exists. This project shows coastal erosion. The more you use the book, pages start to erode away, just like the coastline. 

SEA books case study is the Isle of Wight - my and collaborative photographer @ben hometown - as here climate change has obvious and harsh effects on the coastline. 

With everything that is happening at this moment in time, there has been a glimmer of light in which the climate has proved it can heal. We must be mindful of this as we come out of isolation someday in the future.

Name: Lucia Calcagni
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Fine Art
Description: I paint places I have been to  and perfect the image to suit my memory of the place. This piece is painted from my trek up the Salkantay Mountain in Peru 5 years ago.

Name: Georgia Lauren Graham
University/Course: BA Fine Art, Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
...Painting Mess (2020)

Painting colour into what can be a very grey world.

Name: Fabio Scaglione
University/Course: Edinburgh College / Computer Arts & Design
Description:
The short film explores the complex tangle of feelings that humanity is experiencing in the global emergency. On one side, the feeling that all our certainties are collapsing and the necessity to self-isolate and adopt social distancing. On the other side, the reflection upon our impact on the environment, full of waste like plastic, which is slowly breaking into our own biology. In the end, the possibility to express ideas through creativity, imagination and arts, in order to reconsider our life in relation to our connection to the planet.

“Catharsis refers to the purification and purgation of emotions — particularly pity and fear — through art or any extreme change in emotion that results in renewal and restoration”.

Name: Ron van Zelst
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton. Bachelor degree (Hons) Music Production
Description: This is the logo I'm using for all my musical projects. ZERO when the logo is read as uploaded and for my alter ego releases the logo is flipped to OJ32. When pressed on vinyl the personas keep spinning and changing...

Name: Zinnia
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art  Graphic Design
Description:
Buy Local! 
Why look  further when a bunch of independent food and drink shops are still open for business just round the corner and now providing a delivery service. 
Nows the time to support your local producers to keep these businesses bubbling after Covid-19.

Name: Stelios Papageorgiou
University/Course: European University Cyprus, Graphic Design
Description:
Learning Resource Centre - University Of Cyprus
Part of VR animated posters series. Animated/Static  Typography as visual elements - part of my brand identify for my Thesis project for LRC Library.

Name: Mohammed lmddin
University/Course: Wolverhampton University
Description: film making

Name: Izabella Wiggins
University/Course: BA: Performance: Design & Practise, Central Saint Martins (UAL)
Description: This is a Digital illustration from the film Big(1988), I decided to present it in this style so the images were solely focused as images can give you context themselves. In this piece I aimed to capture the narrative of this scene through colour and focusing solely on the composition. I feel by doing this it intrigues my viewers to look closer and examine how my creative process of achieving this as well as creating a joyous piece for my viewers to enjoy!

Name: Erin Ruane
University/Course: Norwich University Of The Arts, Graphic Design
Description: In the heat of the moment, it’s important to stay protected. HEAT aims to encourage greater protection for those unexpected intimate moments with its discreet design. Inspired by the invention of the safety match, the collection includes a series of unique custom match boxes containing condoms for when you find your ‘perfect match’.

Name: Emily Hebe Mitchell
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts (NUA)
Description: Crochet Craze' is an image which I have styled and photographed. It centres around the theme of sustainable eco conscious fashion in juxtaposition with E-commerce's fast disposable consumerism. This is shown with the handmade Crochet balaclava worn by its designer, but she is wearing a piece sourced from a mass online clothing retailer.  It comments on the question: Where is fashion heading?

Name: Chloe
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts / Fashion Communication and Promotion
Description: Using fruity motifs and innuendos to raise awareness and support for the sensitive issue of breast cancer as a way to relieve the tension around the issue that effects 1 in 2 people in their life times.

Name: Emma Coleman
University/Course: Ravensbourne Uni - Advertising & Branding
Description: A campaign, making Drag relatable to the public by creating a brand 'Pandemic', which shows 3 values at the core of Drag's infectiousness (creativity, expression & confidence) these values are universal & relatable to everyone. The campaign led the public to an event where they would be infected by Drag.

Name: Joanna Kazub
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: This is an illustration connected to John Cooper Clarke's poem "Nation's Ode to the Coast" but I really wanted to twist the meaning. It is to show how much there is left unsaid, outside our field of vision.

Name: Valentina Nenkova
University/Course: Ravensbourne University, Advertising and Brand Design
Description:
Bulgarian emigration began in the early 1990s, the country has lost nearly 2 million people, this is partly due to Bulgaria having one of the lowest salary wages in the EU at €575 per month. It's predicted to have the fastest-shrinking population in the world. 

This campaign is formed by advertising various of jobs whiles giving the opportunity to showcase Bulgaria's secret beauty.

Name: Ellie Hammerton
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: A project looking at performance and atmosphere within the build up of the circus. Graduated 2018

Name: Nikki
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts, BA (Hons) Games Art and Design
Description: It was for a contest inspired by the show Peaky Blinders, showing the poverty and industrial atmosphere of Birmingham in the early 1900s.

Name: Courtney
University/Course: Uni of Wolverhampton, Acting BA (Hons)
Description: Gracious. Noble. Victorious.' A satirical play concerning Prince Harry's departure from the Royal Family. The hypocrisy of Royalty. The true meaning of family. The hope of a new generation. Will history repeat itself?

Name: Sheila Langton
University/Course: Norwich University of the arts studying textile design
Description: ‪My work is based on taking a traditional culture that is connected to my background turning it into a Mordan design through hand and digital processes using mark making and Geomtric shapes. Within my work I always used my surrounding as an inspiration to gathered primary rescue from. My work is very playful by the use of colours as I like to captures the eyes of my audience. ‬

Name: Harriet Spalding
University/Course: Norwich Arts University, Graphic Design
Description: Posters made for sweet Sensations condom range

Name: Erin Logan
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth studying Graphic Desin
Description: Quetzalli Brewing Co. is where a celebration of Hispanic culture meets curious new flavour combinations. Quetzalli’s flagship pale ale “Drag-on Me Around” is a dragon fruit and orange zest adventure which takes you on a journey to the home of the dragon fruit, Mexico.

Name: Tom Smith
University/Course: Film and Moving Image Production at Norwich University of the Arts
Description: A short documentary about the legacy of legendary Brixton Topcats coach Jimmy Rogers, told by 2x BBL MVP Justin Robinson.

Name: Sam Ray
University/Course: Goldsmiths, Design BA
Description:
"I tilted my head back and asked him for it, and as he deftly let it drop from his mouth to mine, I wondered if this simple, unremarkable act of chewing gum would bring me any kind of solace."
Writing and actions exploring temporality, materiality, and intimacy.

Name: Adele Machin
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton, studying photography
Description:
For my Final Major Project I am working within the medium of street photography and creating high contrast black and white images that depict how we survive within the urban environment. The subjects and points of focus in my images include derelict buildings, graffiti, people and streets; documenting human presence. 
	I like people watching as an idea and documenting my surroundings, this is because I’ve always highly liked street and candid photography where the photos have to be taken quickly or you miss an opportunity. Art is subjective so when walking down the street different things capture different people’s attention. For example, a wandering cat may catch a child’s attention and a broken window may grab the attention of a photographer

Name: Jo Lauren
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, studying MA Photography
Description: The work is an investigation into how a feeling of uncertainty about the modern world can be represented through photographs depicting a journey through a semi imagined dystopian place. It explores the in between; a space between the familiar and unfamiliar, the imagined and the real, stemming from Freud’s concept of the Uncanny.

Name: Natalie Lanzalaco
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
Good food makes you feel good. and I want my characters to represent how fun, quirky, and diverse food can be. 

The characters are designed to encourage children to delve into food from different cultures which they may not necessarily usually try. By making the characters cute and approachable I want to help diminish the challenging barrier parents often face from introducing kids to new tastes. 

On their own, the characters aim to provide an element of fun and silly-ness which every adult needs in their life!

Name: Courtney Herbert
University/Course: Greater Brighton Metropolitan College Textile Design
Description:
My final major project was inspired by artist Grayson
Perry for colour, the Tower of London  for primary research with an element of florals to create a cohesive menswear collection aimed towards the high end market for season SS/2021.

Name: Sophie Kent
University/Course: Norwich University Of The Arts, BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: A children's book about a lonely bird of paradise, titled 'One and Only' responding to the text given in the Carmelite Prize 2020 brief.

Name: Heather Morgan
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, studying Illustration
Description: This image is from the inside of a fold out record sleeve I made in response to my project brief ‘Songs for the Revolution’. I took inspiration from the protests for change during the 60s, as well as song lyrics  inspired by the new found power to the people and individuals fighting for peace, equality and acceptance. I wanted my project to reignite this  spark this in us, to come together and continue this revolution.

Name: Hannah Carlile, Charlie Sanderson & Will Butterfield
University/Course: Kingston University studying Graphic Design
Description:
Small Print

97% of people don’t read terms and conditions - they are discrete and made difficult to access by their physical scale and use of unfamiliar legal language. We decided to make T&C’s really really big, so big in fact that they are equally as awkward to read.

We increased the original size of The London Eye terms and conditions by 769 times. From ground level, they cannot be read in their hugely awkward scale. Only by riding in the capsule can you begin to make sense of them, by which point they’ve already been accepted.

Name: Elena Rodríguez Díaz
University/Course: I studied fashion design  at EASD Valencia
Description: The name of this project is "Organic Sensuality". It is a collection of sustainable lingerie made with cotton, silk and only natural dyes are use.

Name: Hannah Carlile, Will Butterfield & Gabriel Paul
University/Course: Kingston University studying graphic design
Description: When the sun pops out for a hot sec, there’s nothing us Brits love more than laying out on the lawn for a quick sunbathe before returning back to our busy lives. Carry your unique cut garden with you at all times, for that quick sunbathing session, wherever, whenever.

Name: Ellie Ross-Wilkinson
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description:
Throughout my final year of university, blue has been the main focus of my studies, both in project and dissertation. Research highlights blue to be highly versatile with many associations, resulting in blue being one of the world’s most popular colours, as well as my own. 

This recognition has inspired my journey to create the picture book ‘Feeling Blue’, a story that demonstrates these associations to a young audience, through the eyes of a blue protagonist. The project focuses around the understanding of blue and sadness, then explores blue’s relationship with other colours, enabling the reader to recognise positive interpretations of joy, cool and calm.

Name: Chloe Marie Boston
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts  /  Film & Moving Image Production
Description: RICKY is my grad film - a mockumentary following a cynical scarecrow as he tries to find his place in the world.

Name: Amy Winstone
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: A redesign of the album everything is wrong by Moby, it is part of a project I have been working on to bring people away from the digital side of music back to the visual side of it to create a really truly immersive experience. This one in particular also focuses on animal testing and abuse and confinement.

Name: Grace Farman
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts Fine Art
Description: Senescence - we all decay, we all die. It is instinct for us to turn a blind eye to what makes us uncomfortable, but if elements of decay are distant enough from our human existence, we are more willing to look at it. As an artist, I try to force audiences to look at abject subjects without them necessarily know that they are, and aim for them to see the beauty in it. This piece includes imagery of road kill and fungi, suggesting the complete cycle of life and death in nature.

Name: Will Reuben
University/Course: Kingston School of Art, Graphic Design
Description: A two sided publication with essays exploring the representation of masculinity within two creative industries.

Name: Catrin Hâf Feron
University/Course: BA (Hons) VFX at Norwich University of the Arts
Description: This piece is a rejection of the portrayal of women in the media. Using CG and computer simulation, this famous statue has had her individually taken from her face which is covered in milk to represent her material nature. This has been juxtaposed with the low camera angle to show that despite being reduced to form, she is powerful.

Name: Flora Miles
University/Course: Camberwell college of art
Description: My project is focusing on the idea of memory, in particular the memories we have of space. Using Socrates theory of the bed, I have created a book to explore this in relation to my Dads childhood home. I have never visited the house but feel I have my own memories from the stories I was told. The book includes archive images, descriptions from those who were there as well as a miniature model as my interpretation of the home.

Name: Maddie Exton
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts, Fine Art
Description: Using the energy of degree show to negate its hyper productivity, these simple degree show idea drawings are loyal to the process of making.

Name: Jordan
University/Course: University for the creative arts, Advertising
Description:
‘In the world of clean energy Mustang is still the car of freedom’

Electric cars virtually make no noise as they don’t have a petrol engine, the UK has passed a law that electric cars must make an artificial noise when travelling under 12mph. However, when travelling above this speed Mustangs go like the wind. 


‘Lost in the wind’


The line caters to both audiences as the wind is a reflection of the environment and also a subtle link towards the 1964 cars attitude towards speed.

Name: Fiona Lamburn
University/Course: Graphic Design at The University of Edinburgh
Description:
A premium tonic water made with activated charcoal, 
a natural antidote to the effects of alcohol. It detoxifies the gut to prevent a hangover and supports a balanced lifestyle. Inspired by Ancient Egyptian medicine, Blacken believes in the power of natural ingredients that can improve the drinkers well-being without compromising on style or flavour.

Name: Lara Hammersley
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Fashion Communication & Promotion
Description: This image is from a lookbook I made inspired by the Copenhagen brand Cecilie Bahnsen. The lookbook was made alongside an information booklet to help brands create more meaningful relationships with their customers.

Name: Rosemary Thomas
University/Course: University of the Arts Norwich, Design for Publishing
Description: The project reflects the themes of surveillance within the George Orwell book 1984 as there are many hidden eyes within the pattern. The pattern is intended to be applied to home furnishings such as cushions or curtains so you become watched within your own house.

Name: Leila Donald
University/Course: Grays School of Art, Aberdeen - BA Photography
Description: This image reflects the impermanence of life as well as fragility of life. This image was taken on the day in which my mother passed away - Monday 2nd March 2020. The  image encapsulates the Japanese aesthetic of Wabi Sabi.

Name: Zara Ahmed
University/Course: Graphic Design, University of Wolverhampton
Description: This is a page from my zine about male suicide and how talking can help prevent such things from happening. Talking about it for awareness and talking to each other more too. Although it was made before Coronavirus, the message feels even more poignant now.

Name: Asher Foster
University/Course: Norwich university of the arts
Description: The deconstruction of a novel for visually aware readers. An interactive poster concept for the National Theatre based on the book 1984. This is an example of how it would be advertised for the production.

Name: Lauryn Shankland
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, Graphic Design
Description: As a self-directed project, I developed the identity and advertising for an immersive fitness app for horror lovers. "Fright Fitness" is a library of auditory scary stories designed to motivate and enhance your running experience.

Name: April Howard
University/Course: Illustration at Plymouth College Of Art
Description: This is a sticker sheet I created for my recent degree project, a sticker book called Explore Conservation! Created to teach young children about endangered and extinct animals.

Name: Keri Lock
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art - BA Illustration
Description: A page from a mental health picture book illustrating the journey from negative to positive thoughts.

Name: Bethany Pickford
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton, Visual Communication (illustration)
Description: Most of my work focusses on people, both real and characters of my own invention. I love capturing their personality and aesthetics in my own art style. With these portraits and designs, I like to tell stories as part of my work. Showing emotion, personality, and what makes people unique is central to my work.

Name: Lois Emma Harkin
University/Course: University of Lincoln
Description: This project that focuses on the issues and identities that surround Redcar and Dormanstown. In an autobiographical and abstracted approach, this body of work, explored through paintings and representational objects, focuses on themes such as social stereotyping, community, crime, drug misuse, and lack of opportunity. This research-based painting practice takes the ‘site’ of Redcar and Dormanstown as its subject.

Name: Lisa Hooper
University/Course: Ravensbourne University, Advertising and Brand Design
Description: I create a brand proposal where the products are fully customisable and personalised to each individuals consumers nude shade. The brand would start with nail polish and lipstick and using an app the consumer would be able to take an image of themselves, select their ' nude' shade and buy a product in that exact colour. In a beauty conscious world, the vision is for everybody to have the option to access their individual skin tone shade in a beauty product.

Name: Robert McCormack
University/Course: Painting and Printmaking at the Glasgow School of Art
Description: A collection of dogs gather, two adults and one pup. Forgetting their pack, they articulate themselves through the nuclear family unit that domesticated them. Cast charcoal paws frantically draw self portraits while quiet rubber tongues erase them. Wooden armatures, that signal dog bodies, are hijacked and repurposed as drawing machines. Traces of Crufts apparatus, playground equipment and bones fight for attention as drawings move through a repetitive looping additive and reductive process.

Name: Matthew Hillary
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton and i study Visual Communication Graphic Design
Description: Stress is one of the main issues of today’s society. Many people who let stress get the best of them let stress related issues effect their performance at work, their fitness journey and other activities which you need a clear mind to successfully partake in it. I feel that many people suffer from anxiety and relaxation problems and feel they should suffer in silence and not speak about it. That’s why I wanted to produce an app to help people with these problems from the comfort of their home on their device.

Name: Emily Turner
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, BA Fine Art
Description: Window (2020), engages with the window as a framing device, one that can curate and control overlooked moments. The minimal structure acts as a threshold barrier, an obstruction that draws connections as well as challenges the relationship between the internal and external. Through cut out areas the schematic guides and limits the participant's movement through a pathway. Once they are within, the form frames other surrounding artworks. The nature of the structure is interdisciplinary, transitional from stand-alone art installations to interactive film sets.

Name: Gabor Turi
University/Course: Edinburgh College
Description: Digital Painting of a Tiger in the Jungle, Photoshop, 2020 Edinburgh, Gabor Turi

Name: Anna Daley
University/Course: Wolverhampton University BA Hons Animation
Description: A Victorian sideshow attraction that is really a child in disguise...

Name: Charlotte Leadley
University/Course: Plymouth College Of Art, BA (Hons) Illustration
Description: Ideation tells the story of the image making process of the illustration students in a studio / classroom setting. How exciting and magical idea generation can be, and the role of illustrators as storytellers, using our imaginations to create inspiring images.

Name: Hannah Lumley
University/Course: University of Strathclyde, MEng Product Design Engineering
Description: My project aim is to design a product which aids people with reduced mobility to use buses more safely. Focussing on decreasing falls, for people such as the elderly or those with poor balance, when they walk from their seat to the exit, as this is often before the bus stops. The solution I came up with is a supportive handle attached to the horizontal grab bar, and it glides along as the passenger walks. It is stored parallel so it is out the way of other passengers, then automatically rotates up when needed and back down.

Name: Harriet Rogers
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton
Description:
404.Gender is a genderless contemporary psychedelic street wear collection. Not SHE, not HE but WE! Designed and made by HettiStitch.

It is designed to represent everyone's individuality and unique identity.

The garments were completely reversible offering the wearer 4 different outfit options.

Photos by j.r.sphotographyy

Name: Tayo Adekunle
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh, Photography
Description: Tayo Adekunle’s work explores the commodification, fetishisation and sexualisation of the black female body, specifically through the human displays  in ethnographic expositions in the 18th and 19th centuries. The work is influenced by ethnographic photographs which were circulated as pornography where black (and other racial minority) bodies were photographed either naked in front of a white background, stripped of their identity, or surrounded by random tropical plants to make the photographs seem authentic. Referencing her Nigerian heritage through Nigerian fabric, Adekunle explores the relationship between the past and present ways of treating the black female body.

Name: Rio
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton. Product Design
Description: My work was for a competition by Incube, Funky Fabulous Furniture a company based in Telford. We were asked to Design a Sensory Reading Pod for either Primary School or Nursery children.  I decided to keep my design very simplistic and using no small parts making much safer yet very enjoyable for the children. I came second place and was only beaten to first place by 5 points.

Name: George Williams
University/Course: The University of Edinburgh, BA (hons) Painting
Description: I'm very much interested in the act of character creation and how this relates to escapism. Through figurative drawing and painting one can almost enter another body which cannot exist in our own reality, an artist can gain a sense control through the formal construction of an image, something which we often find lacking in the chaos of our daily lives. This painting 'Pierra' was inspired by Pierrot the clown, a stock character from Commedia dell'arte, an Italian form of theatre.

Name: Moniecha Warmington
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton
Description: The work explores how mental health story lines can be conveyed through movement/dance, looking into stories which surround Anxiety, depression, PTSD, and other mental health disorders

Name: Rachael Ward
University/Course: The University of Wolverhampton - Ba(Hons) Photography
Description:
Ward’s project Intangible Knots focuses on hairs hidden qualities, by incorporating cameraless and digital photographic techniques, in order to initiate a relationship with hair which never existed whilst she was maturing.

The objectification of hair through subtraction and its physical manipulation allows for the creation of unusual and intriguing shapes. Ward enjoys being open about her relationship with hair and while challenging immediate perceptions her work persuades the viewer to engage with this subject and delve deeper through observative methods.

Ward’s work is a personal journey and subject of her life of how the relationship with hair was never fully maintained. Moreover, Intangible Knots investigates the social and cultural perception of hair perceived and forces us to consider why our relationship with hair is so important.

Name: Matthew
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton studying BA (Hons) Photography
Description: A New Prosperity is an enduring contemporary documentary project focusing on the fundamental chapters arising in the UK, at the beginning of the new decade: the day of the general election (December 2019), the tranquil devastation of the floods (February 2020), the spread the COVID-19 in the UK (March 2020). These images discreetly aim to encapsulate the mood and the consequences on the country, specifically the area of West Midlands, by dutifully documenting the responses and the development of these events. The project concentrates on producing a defining representation of the UK today, as its post-Brexit utopianism is ravaged by disasters that are forcing us to face the magnitude of recent social and political decisions.

Name: Rebekah Bosworth
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton - BA (Hons) in Drama
Description: A comedic rhyming monologue delivered by a young factory worker, who is hopelessly in love with her employer. She soon realises that he and her best friend are lovers. Taking place in a cabaret style show, the monologue is crude and uncensored, as Gracie from Oldham takes the audience on a journey from infatuation to heartbreak, and heartbreak to rage.

Name: Emily Mallett
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton, photography
Description:
Forbidden Childhood
The struggle of childhood desires to be free and play, so suddenly denied by the onset of universal lockdown. Wanting to play in the park, so sadly forced to make her own fun beyond the locked gates.

Name: Eleazer Budnah
University/Course: University of Wolverhampton, BA(Hons) Sound Production
Description: The piece is called Instant Delivery, and it's a personal observation of the growth of consumerism in our current digital landscape. It's a mixed media collage that borrows from retro-futuristic aesthetics reminiscent of the 80s.

Name: Emily Lowes
University/Course: Edinburgh College of Art: Illustration
Description: This print is a piece from a worldbuilding project. I've been making prints and comics themed around a fictional world where everything floats. This work looks at a creation myth from that world involving a cycle of rebirth that is tied to a gigantic snake god shedding its skin.

Name: Emily Keate
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth, studying BA (Hons) Graphic Design
Description: Growing Together, a community scheme seeing the fusion of families with a lack of cooking knowledge, with a lonely elderly demographic. Through the use of community vegetable boxes and personal boxes full of seeds for herbs and veg, recipe cards, soil, and activity cards; the elderly will teach families how to cook easy to follow nutritious meals; all this also helping to combat their loneliness at the same time.

Name: Stan Reader
University/Course: Ravensbourne
Description: As we get older our exercise levels begin to deplete especially when the opportunities are harder to come by. You’ve still got it is a branding project that’s creating an initiative for 35+-year-old males to not only get them involved in exercise but create a sense of community for an especially neglected demographic in the fitness industry. The design for the campaign is been heavily influenced by its south American heritage and aims to reflect the demographics of nostalgic interests.

Name: Callum Stacey
University/Course: Arts University Bournemouth
Description: A campaign targeted at 18-25 year old males, with the aim to promote and normalise conversations around toxic masculinity and men’s mental health. To encourage people to talk and be more open about these themes. Using punk-rock band IDLES’ powerful lyrics combined with innovative forms of typographic design the campaign aims to spark the attention of the target audience, helping ignite conversations with these issues through this 3D poster.

Name: Libby Triggs
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art. Graphic Design
Description:
The aim of the project is to show relationships of texts to images; the focus will be on investigating the relationship between Graphic Design applied practices and contemporary processes as a catalyst for expressive graphic communication.
For my educational and learning book I aim to target children aged from 3-7 years old. This is due to the comprehensive style of the book. The book I aim to create uses the main character as a mermaid. From this, society would stereotype this to be aimed at female children.
The book not only is aimed at children learning and exploring fun, interesting and educational facts about sea creatures but also helps a bond form between the parent/guardian and the child. My book aims to help children learn and develop their understanding of life under the sea as well as encouraging their imagination and understanding of emotions.

Name: Lotte Lawson
University/Course: University of the West of Scotland, Graphic Design
Description: Chess is more than 1,500 years old and is played in every country in the world. There are just 32 pieces and pawns on a 64-square board, yet more possible game variants than there are atoms in the universe. It is a game of politics, strategy and power struggles, as well as being highly rich n metaphors for the human experience.

Name: Jemima Whitaker
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Graphic Design Ba (Hons)
Description: Transmutation is a collaborative publication with sculptor Ben Allan, focussing on The Crystal Palace Dinosaurs and how they transgress the borders between geology, biology and archaeology. The publication is ambiguous in its form, reflecting the transmutation of the Crystal Palace iguanodon.

Name: Elisa Czerwenka
University/Course: School of Communication Arts 2.0 - Advertising
Description: We updated Spotify's famous Listen like you used to campaign to show how our world has changed in 2020.

Name: Orla McConaghy
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design - Textile Design
Description: My unisex fashion collection aims to enable the wearer to achieve a sense of controlled disruption, when external disruption is unavoidable. Inspired by repetitive architecture in bustling cities, a break in busy routines and daily patterns can offer new perspectives and creative bursts.

Name: Shiv
University/Course: Ravensbourne University London, Advertising and Brand Design
Description: A project aimed at 1st generation immigrant parents to help them understand creative pathways to help support their children through creative careers.

Name: Daniel Brooks
University/Course: Leeds Arts University/ Graphic Design
Description: The trilogy of books depicts Moby Dick, Captain Blood and Adventures of Huckleberry Finn through illustrations of the water that the book is based around. The books are screen printed on to a fabric hardback cover thats colour represents the waters depth.

Name: Charlotte Higginson
University/Course: University of Lincoln
Description: When we go abroad on holiday, we often assume that everyone we come across will speak English. And that is often the case. But there can sometimes be a miscommunication when we don’t speak even the basics of the language. Don’t miss out on opportunities with Rosetta Stone.
Website: Use email and I can provide Portfolio copy.

Name: Megan
University/Course: University of Lincoln - Photography
Description: Floodwaters' is a digital photomontage series created using primarily archived images from the county of Norfolk. These images depict the disastrous impact that the North Sea Floods of 1953 had on the region and its inhabitants. While dealing with themes of nostalgia and tourism this project alludes to what may transpire with the possibility of history repeating itself.

Name: Chloe Stockwell
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts - Graphic Design
Description: Coin Laundry is a vibrant restaurant and bar found in London. The identity takes inspiration from a laundrette; from interiors and language to the motion of clothes on a wash. The restaurant's menus are inspired by vintage detergent packaging and laundrette ticketing.

Name: Lídia
University/Course: Ravensbourne University London - BA Cons Advertising and Brand Design
Description: Through the clutter is a design fiction that reimagines a world where packaging design is replaced by guidelines given by the Government. Through the creation of a Universal Packaging Manual, it challenges the role of designers around the issue of consumerism by making all products look the same.

Name: Dominic Manderson
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art - Communication Design: Photography
Description: For two days, the town of Ashbourne is temporarily turbulent through the annual game of Royal Shrovetide Football. With its limited rules, hundreds sprawl in huddles across the town, brawling for a touch of the ball. To score is a momentous achievement due to the game’s legacy. Therefore, it is the responsibility of future generations to act as custodians for the game. Though respecting the unification and inclusivity Shrovetide brings – alongside its aggressive nature, I question the line between tradition and patriarchal dominance in allowing men to temporary fulfil their desired image of masculinity. In particular with younger generations and the rise of challenging the norms of gender, will they emulate what the past has told them to do?

Name: Dominic Manderson
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art - Communication Design: Photography
Description: For two days, the town of Ashbourne is temporarily turbulent through the annual game of Royal Shrovetide Football. With its limited rules, hundreds sprawl in huddles across the town, brawling for a touch of the ball. To score is a momentous achievement due to the game’s legacy. University/Course: Glasgow School of Art - Communication Design: Photography
Description: For two days, the town of Ashbourne is temporarily turbulent through the annual game of Royal Shrovetide Football. Name: Nicole McLaughlin
University/Course: Duncan and Jordanstone College of Art and Design
Description: Knitted Glass is based on a poem that was written by a Dundee Student - Hannah Whaley. It tells the story of an abusive friendship. How harmful someone can be to your mental state.

Name: Dominic Manderson
University/Course: Glasgow School of Art - Communication Design: Photography
Description: For two days, the town of Ashbourne is temporarily turbulent through the annual game of Royal Shrovetide Football. With its limited rules, hundreds sprawl in huddles across the town, brawling for a touch of the ball. To score is a momentous achievement due to the game’s legacy. Therefore, it is the responsibility of future generations to act as custodians for the game. Though respecting the unification and inclusivity Shrovetide brings – alongside its aggressive nature, I question the line between tradition and patriarchal dominance in allowing men to temporary fulfil their desired image of masculinity. In particular with younger generations and the rise of challenging the norms of gender, will they emulate what the past has told them to do?

Name: Aaron Lovelock
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, Ba(Hons) Photography
Description: My image is from my final major project, Don't Feed The Ghosts. Don't Feed The Ghosts is a combination of conceptual and documentary photography, to raise awareness and create a talking point in the stigmatised topic of suicide.

Name: Francisco Freniche-Velazquez
University/Course: Strathclyde University. Sports Engineering
Description: This is a basketball passing training device. The device mixes two training methods, conventional training -which is the most common type and is based on muscle memory-, and vision training -which trains the aspects of the vision that are specific to the sport-.

Name: Lauren Patchett
University/Course: University of Dundee (DJCAD) and Textile Design.
Description: Men’s mental health is a growing issue in today’s society. Being from Northern Ireland, I have seen this problem manifest prominently there. The starting point for this project was the legacy of conflict in Northern Ireland and the impact that can still be felt today. This is particularly notable within the male population and is discussed by Karen Nickel in her thesis.  She says that women were concerned about their “menfolk” who were, “hiding their emotions behind an angry silence”.  As a textile designer I wanted to communicate, albeit abstractly, some of the emotion and energy that surrounds things that have gone unsaid. Through a process led exploration of materials, I developed an experimental yet methodical design approach to the development of colour, pattern and structure. I then created a collection that plays on the jarring and discordant which explores unknown narratives prominently. I have showcased the fabrics as contemporary, high end Menswear.

Name: Ruben Buffery
University/Course: Leeds Arts University
Description: This is a 6 month long collaboration between fashion designers, photographer and graphic designers. It explores the theme of hear no, see no and speak no evil within 3 unique publications using amazing garment design, photography and art direction.

Name: Harvey Chessells
University/Course: Leeds Arts University Graphic Design
Description: I have a hunger for visual identity, publication design and typography. Focusing on research, materials and production allows me to create outcomes are highly detailed and rationally intricate.

Name: Matthew Greene
University/Course: Dundee University, DJCAD
Description: Through knitted and constructed textiles, I have explored ways to make a more tactile item to help stimulate and/or relax the user. I have trapped and embedded beads and small objects within the knitted structures creating a range of weights and prompting different types of interaction from the user.

Name: Sabrina Sasso
University/Course: University of Strathclyde, MSc Product Design & Innovation
Description: Re-designing the Mobile Gaming Experience

Name: Charlotte Elcock
University/Course: Communication Design, Photo at The Glasgow School of Art
Description:
Movie Stills #2 
A photo series in which each image alludes to its own narrative. The images provoke a feeling of anticipation. Tension is created as the subject seems disengaged with his or her immediate surroundings, distracted by something off camera. This plays into the imagination of the viewer and leaves the story up to the individual.

Name: Tamara
University/Course: Leeds arts, Graphic Design
Description: My work is a digital imagination for an immersive photo exhibition that stores memories.

Name: Matt Dobson
University/Course: Internet Design (BSc) - Plymouth University
Description:
Luupro is an online community for creators to get social about the projects they're working on. You can create a project and share regular updates to keep others up to date with what you're working on. You can follow your favourite creators and provide and gain feedback on your projects from other like minded individuals.

Conventional portfolio platforms only allow you to share that final shiny project image, with Luupro, you can share every step of project progression, from concept to fruition.

Name: Zak Haddock
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Graphic Design
Description: The No Evil series is a set of three fashion photography publications exploring the theme of Hear No Evil, See No Evil, Speak No Evil through the work and talent at Leeds Arts University. Each of the three publications explores one of the individual themes, using different photographers, designers and garments to get three diverse outcomes.

Name: Greg McIndoe
University/Course: Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, Dundee
Description: This artwork was inspired by the The Trick by Imtiaz Dharker. It is one of 3 love poem illustrations I created which made the shortlist of the Book Illustration Competition 2020 run by the Folio Society and House of Illustration.

Name: Rebecca Johnston
University/Course: University of Strathclyde and Product Design Engineering
Description: I designed a board game that is aimed to teach the families' of LGBTQ+ individuals about identity and LGBTQ+ culture. This is to ensure better mental health in LGBTQ+ individuals through acceptance of their loved ones.

Name: Hannah Davies
University/Course: University of Derby& BA hons in Textile Design.
Description: My project is based on Saint Petersburg mosque in Russia. Fabrics have been design and woven for high end and boutique hotel interiors. Throughout my project I have made use of weaving, knit and printing sectors to create a full range collection.

Name: Madison LaRose
University/Course: Edinburgh College Of Art: MFA Illustration
Description: This image is from a Children's Book I've worked on for my degree show called Layla's Lantern. It is about a girl whose fear of the dark overwhelms her, and she is unable to fall asleep. This fear is represented visually through a dark sea of water in the beginning of the story.

Name: Any Rushton
University/Course: Birmingham City University, Textile Design
Description: Intricate collage and hand drawn sea creatures were the main driver of this project, the collection was aimed towards a children’s interior market. The collection should stimulate imagination and create an awareness of the world for young children.

Name: Helen Laurenson
University/Course: Design for Textiles at Heriot Watt University
Description: A toile de jouy print inspired by the landscape and wildlife of the Shetland Islands.

Name: Chee Yong Truong
University/Course: University of Strathclyde: MSc Product Design and Innovation
Description:
The project focuses on designing a product that aids the visually impaired individuals enabling safe and independent mobility navigating and orientating within various environments.” 

For visually impaired users, mobility is one of the key difficulties that occur in their everyday lives as they struggle to overcome a variety of difficult barriers. Users find it difficult to locate objects above knee-level, therefore, could cause significant consequences such as accidents or falls. 

The product designed is an inclusively designed smartwatch and electronic mobility aid suited for anyone living with impaired sight. It uses an advanced alert and haptic system that enables the device to notify users of surrounding obstacles, and able to track and receive real-time detections providing a safe and improved mobility experience for the user.

Name: Edward Hart
University/Course: University of Strathclyde
Description: Improve lifeguards’ overall effectiveness, through the implementation of a multifunctional lifeguard rescue device. Aiding in rescues and early intervention, ultimately leading to more lives being saved.

Name: Rachel Stanley
University/Course: Leeds Arts University - Creative Advertising
Description: My work is focused on an essay I previously wrote. My essay was ‘How does influencer or celebrity endorsement affect the successfulness of a campaign?’ I had to write my own brief and figure out an existing problem. I found out that Lush makes a lot of its sales on Valentines as couples are buying each other bath bombs and other items from the store. So how can we get bigger sales on valentines day? By including all the singles and encouraging them to love themselves by treating and indulging themselves in Lush's new range.

Name: Oliver Grand
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: ryu is influenced and named after the Japanese mythical legendary dragon, known as the Ryu. The colour palate for the design came from the strikingly colourful key ingredient, the dragon fruit, handpicked from Okinawa, South of Japan. Crafted by Japanese artisans with centuries old tradition of meticulous attention to detail.

Name: Ella Flood and Erin Ruane
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, BA Graphic Design
Description: In response to the D&AD Brand a Bike Hire Scheme brief, we created an identity for the invented Brighton-based 'Bright Hire'. Bike hire schemes are often dull and uninspiring. Bright Hire was created with the intention that it couldn't be overlooked. Brighton is a quirky, colourful and unapologetically different coastal treasure. To honour this individuality, our scheme draws on the distinct visual aesthetic of the iconic Brighton stick of rock. Throughout the identity, rocky textures and stripes fill the illustrations, Pride-inspired wavy rainbows flood the posters and playful copy related to 'rock', 'roll' and 'bright' create a happy and confident tone of voice. The identity spreads across uniquely Brighton touchpoints, such as a photo stand-in on the pier; Bright Hire also has it's own rock-inspired route system. In collaboration with Lucy & Yak, Bright Hire would produce limited edition rock-striped apparel. Our identity is a celebration of the quirky, colourful and anything-goes attitude of Brighton. Bright Hire is as vibrant as the city, because Brighton rocks!

Name: Lisa Hocking
University/Course: Plymouth College of Art, Graphic Design
Description: A submission to a live competition to mash together two appearingly opposing things (in this case wine and maple bacon) to create something completely new and unique.

Name: Natasha Crudgington
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts, Graphic Design
Description: Bellywash is a charcoal shot created for the health drink sector. Charcoal energises and restores the body. Inspired by coal and the mining community, Bellywash is a term used by miners for a non-alcoholic drink.

Name: Emily Frith
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts - Graphic Design
Description:
Moxi is a one-of-a-kind, 100% natural energy drink made with Ilex Guayusa leaf, which is native to the Ecudorian rainforest.

It is an iced tea, which can be taken to work, the gym, or wherever you may need a little energy boost. Giving your day a little bit more 'Moxi' (which means full of energy / creativity).

The Guayusa leaf is bursting with health benefits, which makes this drink a perfect alternative to the unhealthy caffeinated fizzy drinks and energy drinks we see on supermarket shelves today.

Inspired by the colourful patterns worn by the Kichwa Community of Ecuador, where Guayusa leaf is harvested, the packaging features an eye-catching, bold and energetic design.

Name: Emma-Louise Hannaway
University/Course: Graphic Design at Norwich University of the Arts
Description: Zucker beer builds unity. Aimed to inspire togetherness and create deeper bonds with people. Paperchain labels connect each bottle and, encourage friends to physically connect.

Name: Lauren Stephenson
University/Course: The Arts University Of Bournemouth, Illustration
Description:
"Giant Cup Of Self Love" 

This lady is bathing in a giant teacup which represents the importance of taking care of ourselves. This captures the positivity and love we have to give so that we don't become worn down but instead be revitalised.

Name: Hannah Nicole Drew
University/Course: Norwich University of The Arts, Photography
Description: working from home fits with my best friend in quarentine #wfh

Name: Jack Thompson
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts
Description: I produced a cover for the band 'Prey Drive' for their upcoming (now released) single called 'Shinjuku'. They told me a bit about the song and I created several outcomes however this is the one the band resonated with most since it actually captured a different song perfectly. The song is now available on all relevant platforms featuring my cover design.

Name: Abby
University/Course: Norwich University of the Arts studying Graphic Design
Description: A rebrand for the popular ice cream brand Kelly's of Cornwall. Taking inspiration from all things Cornish.

Name: Paulina Böhme
University/Course: Graphic and Product Design at the Free University of Bolzano
Description: The "Wormclub" is a Vermiculture (Or Worm-Composter) made for the Lunchroom Clubhouse in Amsterdam. The city has no general organic waste collection, and to reduce their food waste the restaurant decided to compost it and turn it into valuable soil. The Bin is made for a big amount of waste, which will be fermented without any odor by the help of compost worms. Beside that there are more features and functionalities included in the Wormclub to make composting faster, easier, and more fun in order to raise awareness about the waste each person could reduce and save from the landfills each day.
